{"title_page": "Ghafir", "text_new": "{{short description|40th chapter of the Qur'an}}\n{{infobox surah\n| number         = 40\n| number-3       = 040\n| name           = Gh\u0101fir\n| name-ar        = \u063a\u0627\u0641\u0631\n| name-en        = The Forgiver\n| prev_sura      = Surat al-Zumar\n| next_sura      = Surat Fussilat\n| classification = Meccan\n| othernames-ar  = (S\u016brat al-Mu\u02bcmin) \u0633\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0624\u0645\u0646\n| othernames     = The Forgiving One, The Believer, Forgiving\n| juz            = 24\n| rukus          = 9\n| verses         = 85\n| words          = <!-- optional, uncommon -->\n| letters        = <!-- optional, uncommon -->\n| muqattaat      = <!-- only if applicable -->\n| sajdahs        = <!-- only if applicable -->\n| audio          = <!-- optional, if exists -->\n}}\n{{Quran}}\n'''Gh\u0101fir'''<ref name = \"Quran 4 U\">{{cite web|url=http://www.quran4u.com/Tafsir%20Ibn%20Kathir/040%20Ghafir.htm  |title=Tafsir Ibn Kathir (English): Surah Al Momin - Gh\u0101fir |work=Quran 4 U|author=[[Ibn Kathir]]|publisher=[[Tafsir]]|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> ({{lang-ar| \u063a\u0627\u0641\u0631}}, \"The All-Forgiving\" (referring to [[God in Islam|God]])), also known as '''S\u016brat al-Mu\u02bcmin''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0624\u0645\u0646}}, \"The Believer\"), is the [[List of chapters in the Quran|40th chapter]] ([[s\u016brah]]) of the [[Qur'an]] with 85 verses ([[\u0101y\u0101t]]). It takes its name from verse 28<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quran.com|title=Ghafir 40:28|last=|first=|date=|website=The Noble Qur'an|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which mentions a distinguished believer  from among the clan of the [[Ramesses II|Pharaoh]] who supported Moses, referring to him as a \"believing man,\" hence ''al-Mu'min;'' The Believer. However, this surah is most often called ''al-Ghafir'' (the All-Forgiving) because of the the [[Names of God in Islam|Divine Name]] mentioned in verse 3<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=\u00dcnal, Ali, author.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1002857525|title=The Qur\u02bcan with annotated interpretation in modern English|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-59784-000-2|location=|pages=971|oclc=1002857525}}</ref>. \n\nRegarding the timing and contextual background of the supposed revelation (''[[asb\u0101b al-nuz\u016bl]]''), it is a \"[[Meccan surah]]\", which means it is believed to have been revealed in Mecca, instead of later in Medina.\n\n== Content ==\nThis surah was revealed after ''Surat az-Zumar'' (the preceding surah) at a time when the Meccan polytheists increased their prosecutions against the Muslim believers to the point that they were plotting to kill [[Muhammad]]<ref name=\":0\" />. The surah reproaches unbelievers for their reaction. The surah also narrates at length how an important believer from among the clan of the Pharaoh, who had hidden his faith, appeared and supported Moses at a very critical point<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quran.com|title=Ghafir|last=|first=|date=|website=The Noble Qur'an|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n== Exegesis [[Tafsir|(Tafsir)]] ==\n\n=== Verse 40:55 ===\n<blockquote><small>Translation: So be patient, [O Muhammad]. Indeed, the promise of Allah is truth. And ask forgiveness for your sin and exalt [ Allah ] with praise of your Lord in the evening and the morning.</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quran.com/40/55|title=Ghafir 40:55|last=|first=|date=|website=The Noble Qur'an|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref></blockquote>Infallibility is an indispensable attribute of [[Prophets and messengers in Islam|Islamic Prophet-hood]] according to Muslims. So according to Muslims, all the Islamic prophets are infallible in the sense that they do not sin or disobey God's orders. Here, God reminds the believers of an important fact to which we must be attentive on the way to God<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{wikisource|The Holy Qur'an (Maulana Muhammad Ali)/40. The Believer}}\n\n{{Sura|40|[[Az-Zumar]]|[[Fussilat]]}}\n\n[[Category:Chapters in the Quran|Ghafir]]\n[[Category:Islamic theology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|40th chapter of the Qur'an}}\n{{infobox surah\n| number         = 40\n| number-3       = 040\n| name           = Gh\u0101fir\n| name-ar        = \u063a\u0627\u0641\u0631\n| name-en        = The Forgiver\n| prev_sura      = Surat al-Zumar\n| next_sura      = Surat Fussilat\n| classification = Meccan\n| othernames-ar  = (S\u016brat al-Mu\u02bcmin) \u0633\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0624\u0645\u0646\n| othernames     = The Forgiving One, The Believer, Forgiving\n| juz            = 24\n| rukus          = 9\n| verses         = 85\n| words          = <!-- optional, uncommon -->\n| letters        = <!-- optional, uncommon -->\n| muqattaat      = <!-- only if applicable -->\n| sajdahs        = <!-- only if applicable -->\n| audio          = <!-- optional, if exists -->\n}}\n{{Quran}}\n'''Gh\u0101fir'''<ref name = \"Quran 4 U\">{{cite web|url=http://www.quran4u.com/Tafsir%20Ibn%20Kathir/040%20Ghafir.htm  |title=Tafsir Ibn Kathir (English): Surah Al Momin - Gh\u0101fir |work=Quran 4 U|author=[[Ibn Kathir]]|publisher=[[Tafsir]]|accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> ({{lang-ar| \u063a\u0627\u0641\u0631}}, \"The All-Forgiving\" (referring to [[God in Islam|God]])), also known as '''S\u016brat al-Mu\u02bcmin''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0624\u0645\u0646}}, \"The Believer\"), is the [[List of chapters in the Quran|40th chapter]] ([[s\u016brah]]) of the [[Qur'an]] with 85 verses ([[\u0101y\u0101t]]). It takes its name from verse 28<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quran.com|title=Ghafir 40:28|last=|first=|date=|website=The Noble Qur'an|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which mentions a distinguished believer  from among the clan of the [[Ramesses II|Pharaoh]] who supported Moses, referring to him as a \"believing man,\" hence ''al-Mu'min;'' The Believer. However, this surah is most often called ''al-Ghafir'' (the All-Forgiving) because of the the [[Names of God in Islam|Divine Name]] mentioned in verse 3<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=\u00dcnal, Ali, author.|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/1002857525|title=The Qur\u02bcan with annotated interpretation in modern English|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-59784-000-2|location=|pages=971|oclc=1002857525}}</ref>. \n\nRegarding the timing and contextual background of the supposed revelation (''[[asb\u0101b al-nuz\u016bl]]''), it is a \"[[Meccan surah]]\", which means it is believed to have been revealed in Mecca, instead of later in Medina.\n\n== Content ==\nThis surah was revealed after ''Surat az-Zumar'' (the preceding surah) at a time when the Meccan polytheists increased their prosecutions against the Muslim believers to the point that they were plotting to kill [[Muhammad]]<ref name=\":0\" />. The surah reproaches unbelievers for their reaction. The surah also narrates at length how an important believer from among the clan of the Pharaoh, who had hidden his faith, appeared and supported Moses at a very critical point<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quran.com|title=Ghafir|last=|first=|date=|website=The Noble Qur'an|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n== Exegesis [[Tafsir|(Tafsir)]] ==\n\n=== Verse 40:55 ===\n<blockquote><small>Translation: So be patient, [O Muhammad]. Indeed, the promise of Allah is truth. And ask forgiveness for your sin and exalt [ Allah ] with praise of your Lord in the evening and the morning.</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quran.com/40/55|title=Ghafir 40:55|last=|first=|date=|website=The Noble Qur'an|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref></blockquote>Infallibility is an indispensable attribute of [[Prophets and messengers in Islam|Islamic Prophet-hood]] according to Muslims. So according to Muslims, all the Islamic prophets are infallible in the sense that they do not sin or disobey God's orders. Here, God reminds the believers of an important fact to which we must be attentive on the way to God. What falls on those who believe in God, and who endeavor to attain the level of ordering their life according to the rules that are established in the Qur'an, is to be patient, as for God's forgiveness for one's sins, and as will be stated in the verse, to be occupied with God's glorification and praise<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{wikisource|The Holy Qur'an (Maulana Muhammad Ali)/40. The Believer}}\n\n{{Sura|40|[[Az-Zumar]]|[[Fussilat]]}}\n\n[[Category:Chapters in the Quran|Ghafir]]\n[[Category:Islamic theology]]\n", "name_user": "Ariadenus", "label": "safe", "comment": "edited interpretation.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghafir"}
{"title_page": "Glenrio, New Mexico and Texas", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Glenrio, New Mexico<br />Glenrio, Texas\n| settlement_type                 = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated comumunity]]\n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = <!-- Images -->\n| image_skyline                   = File:Glenrio NM Tex Cafe.jpg\n| imagesize                       = 250px\n| image_caption                   = Closed caf\u00e9 in Glenrio\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = <!-- Maps -->\n| image_map                       = Glenrio-topographic-map.png\n| mapsize                         = 250px\n| map_caption                     = Topographic map of Glenrio, 1982\n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = <!-- Location -->\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = United States\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[New Mexico]]<br />[[Texas]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[County (United States)|Counties]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Quay County, New Mexico]]<br />[[Deaf Smith County, Texas]]\n| government_footnotes            = \n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = \n| leader_name                     = \n| leader_title1                   = \n| leader_name1                    = \n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = <!-- Area -->\n| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_land_km2                   = \n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_total_sq_mi                = \n| area_land_sq_mi                 = \n| area_water_sq_mi                = <!-- Population -->\n| population_as_of                = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_total                = 1\n| population_density_km2          = \n| population_density_sq_mi        = <!-- General information -->\n| timezone                        = \n| utc_offset                      = \n| timezone_DST                    = \n| utc_offset_DST                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| elevation_ft                    = \n| coordinates                     = <!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP Code]]\n| postal_code                     = 88434\n| area_code                       = \n| blank_name                      = \n| blank_info                      = \n| blank1_name                     = \n| blank1_info                     = \n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = {{Infobox NRHP\n | name = Glenrio Historic District\n | nrhp_type = hd\n | designated_other1 = New Mexico\n | designated_other1_date = April 7, 2006\n | designated_other1_number = [https://web.archive.org/web/20141110122215/http://www.nmhistoricpreservation.org/assets/files/registers/2012%20Report_%20Section%203_%20Arranged%20by%20Number.pdf 1890]\n | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n | embed = yes\n | image = \n | caption = \n | location = [[Interstate 40 Business (Glenrio, Texas)|Texas State Highway Loop 504]] / [[U.S. Route 66 in New Mexico|New Mexico State Road 1578]], Glenrio\n | coordinates = {{coord|35|10|44|N|103|02|32|W|display=inline,title}}\n | locmapin = New Mexico#Texas#USA\n | map_label = Glenrio Historic District\n | locmap_relief = yes\n | built = {{Start date|1926}}\n | architect = \n | architecture = [[American Craftsman|Bungalow/Craftsman]], [[Streamline Moderne|Moderne]]\n | added = January 17, 2007\n | area = {{convert|31.7|acre}}\n | mpsub = [http://pdfhost.focus.nps.gov/docs/NRHP/Text/64500432.pdf Route 66 through New Mexico MPS], [https://atlas.thc.state.tx.us/AdvancedSearch/MPS?mpsid=41 Route 66 in Texas MPS]\n | refnum = 06001258, [https://npgallery.nps.gov/AssetDetail/NRIS/06001259 06001259]<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n| name                            = \n}}\n'''Glenrio''', formerly '''Rock Island''',<ref>{{gnis|915829}}</ref> is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in both [[Deaf Smith County, Texas]], and [[Quay County, New Mexico]], in the United States. Located on the former [[U.S. Route 66]], the [[ghost town]] sits on the [[Texas]]\u2013[[New Mexico]] state line. It includes the '''Glenrio Historic District''' which was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2007.\n\nThe community was founded in 1903 as a railroad siding on the [[Rock Island Railroad]]. Its name is derived from [[Scots language|Scots]] \"[[glen]]\" + [[Spanish language|Spanish]] \"[[wikt:rio|rio]]\" (meaning \"river\").\n\n==History==\nOriginally a railroad town, the village was renamed from ''Rock Island'' to ''Glenrio'' by the Rock Island and Pacific Railroad in 1908 and began receiving motorists on the dusty [[Ozark Trail (auto trail)|Ozark Trail]] in 1917. Its original structures were adobe buildings. The circa-1910 Angel House was in New Mexico.\n\nThe Ozark Trail was formed into [[U.S. Route 66]] on November 11, 1926. By the 1930s, [[U.S. Route 66 in Texas]] was a paved two-lane road served locally by several [[filling station]]s, a [[restaurant]], and a [[motel]]. The road was widened in the 1950s. A [[Texaco]] station (1950) and a [[diner]] (Brownlee Diner/Little Juarez Caf\u00e9, 1952) were constructed in Texas using the [[art moderne]] architectural style.<ref name=\"amglobe\">{{cite news |author=Josh Burton |url=http://amarillo.com/stories/040107/new_7204588.shtml |title=Glenrio resurrected |publisher=Amarillo Globe-News |date=2007-04-01 |accessdate=2012-06-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525212653/http://amarillo.com/stories/040107/new_7204588.shtml |archive-date=2016-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe location of Glenrio on Texas and New Mexico's border led to some interesting business practices. At one point, all fuel was dispensed in Texas due to New Mexico's higher gasoline taxes. The 1930s State Line Bar and motel were built in New Mexico because Deaf Smith County, Texas, was [[dry county|dry]] at the time.<ref name=\"nps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/route66/glenrio_historic_district.html |title=Glenrio Historic District-Route 66: A Discover Our Shared Heritage Travel Itinerary |publisher=US [[National Park Service]] |date= |accessdate=2012-05-04}}</ref> The railroad station was in Texas. The local post office, built circa-1935, was in New Mexico. A water tank and windmill in New Mexico were constructed circa 1945.\n\nThe Joseph Brownlee House, constructed in [[Amarillo, Texas|Amarillo]] in 1930, was moved to Glenrio in 1950. Glenrio was the site of the \"First Motel in Texas\" / \"Last Motel in Texas\" (Homer Ehresman's family-run 1953 State Line Caf\u00e9 and Gas Station and 1955 Texas Longhorn Motel, closed in 1976) and other businesses which straddled the state line on U.S. Route 66 for many years until Interstate 40 bypassed the community in September 1973.<ref name=\"amglobe\"/>\n\nThree [[filling station]]s (the 1925 Broyles Mobil station, a circa-1935 Texaco, and the 1946 Ferguson Gas Station) once operated in New Mexico.\n\nIt went in to decline during 1975 when [[Interstate 40]] had bypassed the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/route66/glenrio_historic_district.html|title=Glenrio Historic District--Route 66: A Discover Our Shared Heritage Travel Itinerary|website=www.nps.gov}}</ref>  \n\nFor years there has been a simmering dispute over which state the east part of Glenrio is lawfully a part of: Texas or New Mexico?  The straight north-south border between the two states was originally defined as the [[103rd meridian west|103rd meridian]], but the 1859 survey that was supposed to mark that boundary mistakenly set the border between {{convert|2.29|and|3.77|mi|km}} too far west of that line, making the current towns of [[Farwell, Texas|Farwell]], [[Texline, Texas|Texline]] and the east part of Glenrio appear to be within the State of Texas.  New Mexico's short border with Oklahoma, in contrast, was surveyed on the correct meridian.  New Mexico's draft constitution in 1910 stated that the border is on the 103rd meridian as intended.  The disputed strip, hundreds of miles long, includes parts of valuable [[oilfields]] of the [[Permian Basin (North America)|Permian Basin]].  A bill was passed in the [[New Mexico Senate]] to fund and file a lawsuit in the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] to recover the strip from Texas, but the bill did not become law.  Today, land in the strip is included in Texas land surveys and the land and towns (the east part of Glenrio) for all purposes are taxed and governed by the State of Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kbtx.com/home/headlines/1357432.html|title=Border War Brewing?|author=Daniel Gertson|accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nGlenrio sits just a few yards to the south of [[Interstate 40]] at Texas exit 0 on [[Interstate 40 Business (Glenrio, Texas)|Business I-40]], a road which turns into a local gravel road at the state line.  This was the original Route 66 alignment between Glenrio and San Jon until 1952 and was paved for many years until Quay County removed the paving due to maintenance costs. Mail was formerly served by a post office on the New Mexico side of the town.\n\nThe town consists of the remains of the courtyard motel and related Texas Longhorn Caf\u00e9 and [[Phillips 66]] service station, the post office, a few other buildings including the diner and adjacent Texaco service station, the old Route 66 roadbed, and the former roadbed of the Rock Island Railroad, whose tracks were removed in the 1980s. A few homes still exist in Glenrio; the Joseph Brownlee House and an office in the Texas Longhorn Motel were the last to be occupied.\n\n===Glenrio Historic District===\n'''Glenrio Historic District''' is a {{convert|31.7|acre|adj=on}} [[historic district (United States)|historic district]] that was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2007.<ref name=nris/>  At the time of the listing, the district included 12 [[contributing buildings]] and 4 other [[contributing structures]].\n\n===Glenrio Welcome Center===\nOn June 25, 2008, the State of New Mexico opened the Glenrio Welcome Center on [[Interstate 40]] at the Texas state line. The center includes such things as a pet walk, a livestock corral, [[Wi-Fi|wireless Internet access]], a movie theater, and information kiosks. Built to accommodate one million visitors per year, it includes green features such as recycling of [[greywater]] for grounds [[irrigation]], and a [[wind turbine]] that will generate 20 percent of the center's energy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qcsunonline.com/news/new_6208___article.html/center_glenrio.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715133646/http://www.qcsunonline.com/news/new_6208___article.html/center_glenrio.html|url-status=dead|title=Glenrio Welcome Center officially opened|archivedate=July 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abqjournal.com/main/2008/07/03/abqnewsseeker/915am-e-coli-found-at-new-glenrio-welcome-center.html |title=E. Coli Found at New Glenrio Welcome Center |publisher=ABQ Journal |date=2008-07-03 |accessdate=2013-02-11}}</ref>\n\n==In cinema==\nPortions of ''[[The Grapes of Wrath (film)|The Grapes of Wrath]]'' were filmed in Glenrio.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C2eXjxsZ2FEC&pg=PA66 |title=More Ghost Towns of Texas |author=T. Lindsay Baker |date=2005-08-31 |accessdate=2012-06-23|isbn=9780806137247}}</ref> An abandoned \"Glenn Rio Motel\" is depicted in the town of [[Radiator Springs]] in 2006's animated film ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'', where the architectural design of Glenrio's Little Juarez Caf\u00e9 is used for a vacant, abandoned building which eventually becomes the Racing Museum. The opening scene from the movie \"Daylight's End\" (2018) was filmed in Glenrio.\n\n==Photo gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Glenrio4 (1 of 1).jpg | Closed caf\u00e9 and gas station in Glenrio\nImage:Glenrio1 (1 of 1).jpg | Closed hotel in Glenrio\nImage:Glenrio NM Tex Motel 1.jpg|First/Last Motel in Texas, Glenrio\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|National Register of Historic Places|Texas}}\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Quay County, New Mexico]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Deaf Smith County, Texas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Fugate, Francis L. and Roberta B.  ''Roadside History of New Mexico''.  Missoula, MT:  Mountain Press, 1989, p.&nbsp;356.  {{ISBN|0-87842-242-0}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Glenrio, New Mexico and Texas}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Glenrio}}\n* {{Handbook of Texas|id=hng14|name=Glenrio, Texas}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/aug/28/us-route-66-grapes-wrath The Grapes of Wrath revisited: Dust to dust for the ghosts of Route 66], guardian.co.uk, Chris McGreal\u2014writer, August 28, 2009. (includes video)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160525212653/http://amarillo.com/stories/040107/new_7204588.shtml Glenrio, TX/ from the Amarillo Globe-News]\n*[https://www.thrillist.com/travel/nation/abandoned-towns-in-america-10-of-most-eerily-ghost-towns 12 of the Most Eerily Abandoned Towns in America]\n\n{{Quay County, New Mexico}}\n{{Deaf Smith County, Texas}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Texas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Quay County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Deaf Smith County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Texas]]\n[[Category:Ghost towns in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Ghost towns in the Texas Panhandle]]\n[[Category:Ghost towns on U.S. Route 66]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Quay County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Deaf Smith County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the National Register of Historic Places in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the National Register of Historic Places in Texas]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Texas]]\n[[Category:Historic districts in New Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Glenrio, New Mexico<br />Glenrio, Texas\n| settlement_type                 = [[Unincorporated area|Unincorporated comumunity]]\n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = <!-- Images -->\n| image_skyline                   = File:Glenrio NM Tex Cafe.jpg\n| imagesize                       = 250px\n| image_caption                   = Closed caf\u00e9 in Glenrio\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = <!-- Maps -->\n| image_map                       = Glenrio-topographic-map.png\n| mapsize                         = 250px\n| map_caption                     = Topographic map of Glenrio, 1982\n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = <!-- Location -->\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = United States\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[New Mexico]]<br />[[Texas]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[County (United States)|Counties]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Quay County, New Mexico]]<br />[[Deaf Smith County, Texas]]\n| government_footnotes            = \n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = \n| leader_name                     = \n| leader_title1                   = \n| leader_name1                    = \n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = <!-- Area -->\n| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_land_km2                   = \n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_total_sq_mi                = \n| area_land_sq_mi                 = \n| area_water_sq_mi                = <!-- Population -->\n| population_as_of                = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_total                = 1\n| population_density_km2          = \n| population_density_sq_mi        = <!-- General information -->\n| timezone                        = \n| utc_offset                      = \n| timezone_DST                    = \n| utc_offset_DST                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| elevation_ft                    = \n| coordinates                     = <!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP Code]]\n| postal_code                     = 88434\n| area_code                       = \n| blank_name                      = \n| blank_info                      = \n| blank1_name                     = \n| blank1_info                     = \n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = {{Infobox NRHP\n | name = Glenrio Historic District\n | nrhp_type = hd\n | designated_other1 = New Mexico\n | designated_other1_date = April 7, 2006\n | designated_other1_number = [https://web.archive.org/web/20141110122215/http://www.nmhistoricpreservation.org/assets/files/registers/2012%20Report_%20Section%203_%20Arranged%20by%20Number.pdf 1890]\n | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n | embed = yes\n | image = \n | caption = \n | location = [[Interstate 40 Business (Glenrio, Texas)|Texas State Highway Loop 504]] / [[U.S. Route 66 in New Mexico|New Mexico State Road 1578]], Glenrio\n | coordinates = {{coord|35|10|44|N|103|02|32|W|display=inline,title}}\n | locmapin = New Mexico#Texas#USA\n | map_label = Glenrio Historic District\n | locmap_relief = yes\n | built = {{Start date|1926}}\n | architect = \n | architecture = [[American Craftsman|Bungalow/Craftsman]], [[Streamline Moderne|Moderne]]\n | added = January 17, 2007\n | area = {{convert|31.7|acre}}\n | mpsub = [http://pdfhost.focus.nps.gov/docs/NRHP/Text/64500432.pdf Route 66 through New Mexico MPS], [https://atlas.thc.state.tx.us/AdvancedSearch/MPS?mpsid=41 Route 66 in Texas MPS]\n | refnum = 06001258, [https://npgallery.nps.gov/AssetDetail/NRIS/06001259 06001259]<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n| name                            = \n}}\n'''Glenrio''', formerly '''Rock Island''',<ref>{{gnis|915829}}</ref> is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in both [[Deaf Smith County, Texas]], and [[Quay County, New Mexico]], in the United States. Located on the former [[U.S. Route 66]], the [[ghost town]] sits on the [[Texas]]\u2013[[New Mexico]] state line. It includes the '''Glenrio Historic District''' which was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2007.\n\nThe community was founded in 1903 as a railroad siding on the [[Rock Island Railroad]]. Its name is derived from [[Scots language|Scots]] \"[[glen]]\" + [[Spanish language|Spanish]] \"[[wikt:rio|rio]]\" (meaning \"river\").\n\n==History==\nOriginally a railroad town, the village was renamed from ''Rock Island'' to ''Glenrio'' by the Rock Island and Pacific Railroad in 1908 and began receiving motorists on the dusty [[Ozark Trail (auto trail)|Ozark Trail]] in 1917. Its original structures were adobe buildings. The circa-1910 Angel House was in New Mexico.\n\nThe Ozark Trail was formed into [[U.S. Route 66]] on November 11, 1926. By the 1930s, [[U.S. Route 66 in Texas]] was a paved two-lane road served locally by several [[filling station]]s, a [[restaurant]], and a [[motel]]. The road was widened in the 1950s. A [[Texaco]] station (1950) and a [[diner]] (Brownlee Diner/Little Juarez Caf\u00e9, 1952) were constructed in Texas using the [[art moderne]] architectural style.<ref name=\"amglobe\">{{cite news |author=Josh Burton |url=http://amarillo.com/stories/040107/new_7204588.shtml |title=Glenrio resurrected |publisher=Amarillo Globe-News |date=2007-04-01 |accessdate=2012-06-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525212653/http://amarillo.com/stories/040107/new_7204588.shtml |archive-date=2016-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe location of Glenrio on Texas and New Mexico's border led to some interesting business practices. At one point, all fuel was dispensed in Texas due to New Mexico's higher gasoline taxes. The 1930s State Line Bar and motel were built in New Mexico because Deaf Smith County, Texas, was [[dry county|dry]] at the time.<ref name=\"nps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/route66/glenrio_historic_district.html |title=Glenrio Historic District-Route 66: A Discover Our Shared Heritage Travel Itinerary |publisher=US [[National Park Service]] |date= |accessdate=2012-05-04}}</ref> The railroad station was in Texas. The local post office, built circa-1935, was in New Mexico. A water tank and windmill in New Mexico were constructed circa 1945.\n\nThe Joseph Brownlee House, constructed in [[Amarillo, Texas|Amarillo]] in 1930, was moved to Glenrio in 1950. Glenrio was the site of the \"First Motel in Texas\" / \"Last Motel in Texas\" (Homer Ehresman's family-run 1953 State Line Caf\u00e9 and Gas Station and 1955 Texas Longhorn Motel, closed in 1976) and other businesses which straddled the state line on U.S. Route 66 for many years until Interstate 40 bypassed the community in September 1973.<ref name=\"amglobe\"/>\n\nThree [[filling station]]s (the 1925 Broyles Mobil station, a circa-1935 Texaco, and the 1946 Ferguson Gas Station) once operated in New Mexico.\n\nIt went in to decline during 1975 when [[Interstate 40]] had bypassed the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/route66/glenrio_historic_district.html|title=Glenrio Historic District--Route 66: A Discover Our Shared Heritage Travel Itinerary|website=www.nps.gov}}</ref>  \n\nFor years there has been a simmering dispute over which state the east part of Glenrio is lawfully a part of: Texas or New Mexico?  The straight north-south border between the two states was originally defined as the [[103rd meridian west|103rd meridian]], but the 1859 survey that was supposed to mark that boundary mistakenly set the border between {{convert|2.29|and|3.77|mi|km}} too far west of that line, making the current towns of [[Farwell, Texas|Farwell]], [[Texline, Texas|Texline]] and the east part of Glenrio appear to be within the State of Texas.  New Mexico's short border with Oklahoma, in contrast, was surveyed on the correct meridian.  New Mexico's draft constitution in 1910 stated that the border is on the 103rd meridian as intended.  The disputed strip, hundreds of miles long, includes parts of valuable [[oilfields]] of the [[Permian Basin (North America)|Permian Basin]].  A bill was passed in the [[New Mexico Senate]] to fund and file a lawsuit in the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] to recover the strip from Texas, but the bill did not become law.  Today, land in the strip is included in Texas land surveys and the land and towns (the east part of Glenrio) for all purposes are taxed and governed by the State of Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kbtx.com/home/headlines/1357432.html|title=Border War Brewing?|author=Daniel Gertson|accessdate=2016-09-24}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nGlenrio sits just a few yards to the south of [[Interstate 40]] at Texas exit 0 on [[Interstate 40 Business (Glenrio, Texas)|Business I-40]], a road which turns into a local gravel road at the state line.  This was the original Route 66 alignment between Glenrio and San Jon until 1952 and was paved for many years until Quay County removed the paving due to maintenance costs. Mail was formerly served by a post office on the New Mexico side of the town.\n\nThe town consists of the remains of the courtyard motel and related Texas Longhorn Caf\u00e9 and [[Phillips 66]] service station, the post office, a few other buildings including the diner and adjacent Texaco service station, the old Route 66 roadbed, and the former roadbed of the Rock Island Railroad, whose tracks were removed in the 1980s. A few homes still exist in Glenrio; the Joseph Brownlee House and an office in the Texas Longhorn Motel were the last to be occupied.\n\n===Glenrio Historic District===\n'''Glenrio Historic District''' is a {{convert|31.7|acre|adj=on}} [[historic district (United States)|historic district]] that was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2007.<ref name=nris/>  At the time of the listing, the district included 12 [[contributing buildings]] and 4 other [[contributing structures]].\n\n===Glenrio Welcome Center===\nOn June 25, 2008, the State of New Mexico opened the Glenrio Welcome Center on [[Interstate 40]] at the Texas state line. The center includes such things as a pet walk, a livestock corral, [[Wi-Fi|wireless Internet access]], a movie theater, and information kiosks. Built to accommodate one million visitors per year, it includes green features such as recycling of [[greywater]] for grounds [[irrigation]], and a [[wind turbine]] that will generate 20 percent of the center's energy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qcsunonline.com/news/new_6208___article.html/center_glenrio.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715133646/http://www.qcsunonline.com/news/new_6208___article.html/center_glenrio.html|deadurl=y|title=Glenrio Welcome Center officially opened|archivedate=July 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abqjournal.com/main/2008/07/03/abqnewsseeker/915am-e-coli-found-at-new-glenrio-welcome-center.html |title=E. Coli Found at New Glenrio Welcome Center |publisher=ABQ Journal |date=2008-07-03 |accessdate=2013-02-11}}</ref>\n\n==In cinema==\nPortions of ''[[The Grapes of Wrath (film)|The Grapes of Wrath]]'' were filmed in Glenrio.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C2eXjxsZ2FEC&pg=PA66 |title=More Ghost Towns of Texas |author=T. Lindsay Baker |date=2005-08-31 |accessdate=2012-06-23|isbn=9780806137247}}</ref> An abandoned \"Glenn Rio Motel\" is depicted in the town of [[Radiator Springs]] in 2006's animated film ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'', where the architectural design of Glenrio's Little Juarez Caf\u00e9 is used for a vacant, abandoned building which eventually becomes the Racing Museum. The opening scene from the movie \"Daylight's End\" (2018) was filmed in Glenrio.\n\n==Photo gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Glenrio4 (1 of 1).jpg | Closed caf\u00e9 and gas station in Glenrio\nImage:Glenrio1 (1 of 1).jpg | Closed hotel in Glenrio\nImage:Glenrio NM Tex Motel 1.jpg|First/Last Motel in Texas, Glenrio\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|National Register of Historic Places|Texas}}\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Quay County, New Mexico]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Deaf Smith County, Texas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Fugate, Francis L. and Roberta B.  ''Roadside History of New Mexico''.  Missoula, MT:  Mountain Press, 1989, p.&nbsp;356.  {{ISBN|0-87842-242-0}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Glenrio, New Mexico and Texas}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Glenrio}}\n* {{Handbook of Texas|id=hng14|name=Glenrio, Texas}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/aug/28/us-route-66-grapes-wrath The Grapes of Wrath revisited: Dust to dust for the ghosts of Route 66], guardian.co.uk, Chris McGreal\u2014writer, August 28, 2009. (includes video)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160525212653/http://amarillo.com/stories/040107/new_7204588.shtml Glenrio, TX/ from the Amarillo Globe-News]\n*[https://www.thrillist.com/travel/nation/abandoned-towns-in-america-10-of-most-eerily-ghost-towns 12 of the Most Eerily Abandoned Towns in America]\n\n{{Quay County, New Mexico}}\n{{Deaf Smith County, Texas}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Texas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Quay County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Deaf Smith County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Texas]]\n[[Category:Ghost towns in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Ghost towns in the Texas Panhandle]]\n[[Category:Ghost towns on U.S. Route 66]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Quay County, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Deaf Smith County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the National Register of Historic Places in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the National Register of Historic Places in Texas]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Texas]]\n[[Category:Historic districts in New Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed unsupported cite parameter deadurl to url-status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glenrio,_New_Mexico_and_Texas"}
{"title_page": "Satoshi Kanazawa", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name=Satoshi Kanazawa\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|df=yes|1962|11|16}}\n|birth_place=United States<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi |year=2012 |title=The Intelligence Paradox: Why the Intelligent Choice Isn't Always the Smart One |isbn=978-0-470-58695-2 }}{{page needed|date=December 2016}}</ref>\n|citizenship=United States<br />United Kingdom\n|residence= [[England]]\n|field=[[Evolutionary psychology]]\n|alma_mater=[[University of Arizona]]\n|work_institution=[[London School of Economics]]\n|known_for=\n}}\n\n'''Satoshi Kanazawa''' (born 16 November 1962) is an American-born British [[Evolutionary psychology|evolutionary psychologist]] and writer. He is currently [[Reader (academic rank)|Reader]] in [[Management]] at the [[London School of Economics]]. His work uses evolutionary psychology to analyse social sciences such as sociology, economics, and anthropology.<ref>[http://www.lse.ac.uk/people/s.kanazawa@lse.ac.uk/ Dr Satoshi Kanazawa], London School of Economics. Retrieved 6 September 2006</ref> Kanazawa's comments and research on [[race and intelligence]], [[Cognitive epidemiology|health and intelligence]], [[multiculturalism]], and the relationship between [[physical attractiveness]] and [[intelligence]] have led to condemnation from observers and colleagues. He attributes this to [[political correctness]] and [[censorship]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/if-the-truth-offends-it-s-our-job-offend |title=Psychology Today: \"If the truth offends, it's our job to offend\", 2008 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20151223160938/https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/200802/if-the-truth-offends-it-s-our-job-offend |archive-date=23 December 2015}}</ref> while his critics have described his claims as [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]]<ref name=\"bigthink.com-bad-science-of-satoshi-kanazawa\">{{cite web |title=The bad science of Satoshi Kanazawa |url=http://bigthink.com/neurobonkers/the-bad-science-of-satoshi-kanazawa |website=Big Think |accessdate=31 May 2019 |language=en |date=26 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Britton\" /> and [[racist]].<ref name=\"theguardian.com-Nyabola-kanazawa-black-women-psychology-today\">{{cite web |last1=Nyabola |first1=Nanjala |title=Satoshi Kanazawa's racist nonsense should not be tolerated |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/may/18/satoshi-kanazawa-black-women-psychology-today |website=The Guardian |accessdate=31 May 2019 |date=18 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Adam |title=Doesn't This Place Have Standards? |url=https://bigthink.com/daylight-atheism/doesnt-this-place-have-standards |accessdate=1 July 2019 |work=Big Think |date=12 September 2012 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn response to ongoing controversies over his stated views, such as [[Sub-Saharan Africa|Sub-Saharan Black Africa]]n countries suffer from [[chronic poverty]] and [[disease]] because their people have lower IQs, and black women are objectively less attractive than women of other races, he was dismissed from writing for ''[[Psychology Today]]'', and his employer, the [[London School of Economics]], prohibited him from publishing in non-peer-reviewed outlets for 12 months.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-14945110 \"LSE lecturer Dr Satoshi Kanazawa tells of race blog 'regret'\"]  \"BBC, 16 September 2011\"</ref> A group of 68 evolutionary psychologists issued an open letter titled \"Kanazawa's bad science does not represent evolutionary psychology\" rejecting his views,<ref name=\"Kanazawa Statement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/231350957/Kanazawa-Statement |title=Kanazawa Statement &#124; Academia &#124; Science |publisher=Scribd.com |date=2016-03-29 |accessdate=2018-04-28}}</ref> and an article on the same theme was published by 35 academics in ''American Psychologist''.<ref name=\"huffpost.com-kanazawa-does-not-speak-for-us\">{{cite web |title=Satoshi Kanazawa Does Not Speak for All of Evolutionary Psychology |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/satoshi-kanazawa-does-not_n_863359 |author=Scott Barry Kaufman |website=HuffPost |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=18 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nHe began working at the London School of Economics in 2003.<ref name=\"personal.lse.ac.uk-Kanazawa\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Satoshi Kanazawa |url=http://personal.lse.ac.uk/Kanazawa |website=personal.lse.ac.uk |accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Savanna principle==\n{{see also|Cognitive epidemiology#Substance abuse}}\n\"Savanna Principle\" is a term coined by Satoshi Kanazawa in 2004 for the principle that [[human behavior]] remaining to some extent adapted to the ancestral environment of early ''[[Homo]]'' in the [[savanna]] may lead to problems in a modern (Industrial or post-Industrial) environment. \nKanazawa uses this disparity to explain \"a host of societal difficulties\". For example, ancestors who craved sugary and fatty foods lived longer and were healthier than those who didn't, in a time that such things were relatively scarce. Today, the abundance of such temptations leads to [[obesity]] and [[heart disease]]. Similar scenarios are illustrated with television,<ref>{{cite web\n   |url        = http://www.lse.ac.uk/collections/MES/pdf/JCEP2006.pdf\n   |title      = Why the less intelligent may enjoy television more than the more ...\n   |author     = Satoshi Kanazawa\n   |accessdate = 2007-11-05\n    }}</ref> sex, and jealousy.\n\nKanazawa presented this argument in 2004 in the form of a short journal article called \"The Savanna Principle<ref>''Managerial and decision economics''  25 (1), 2004, pp. 41\u201354</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kanazawa|first1=Satoshi|title=The Savanna Principle|journal=Managerial and Decision Economics|date=1 January 2004|volume=25|issue=1|pages=41\u201354|doi=10.1002/mde.1130|language=en|issn=1099-1468}}</ref> and expounded upon it in a 2007 book aimed at a general audience, ''Why Beautiful People Have More Daughters''.<ref>Kanazawa, Satoshi ''Why Beautiful People Have More Daughters'' (2007) All, {{ISBN|978-0-399-53365-5}}.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Kanazawa used the \"Savanna Principle\" to explain the correlation of health and IQ vs. health and wealth. He argued that IQ is a better predictor for health than wealth or inequality in most regions of the world, except in Sub-Saharan Africa, where health is more strongly correlated to wealth than to IQ, because Sub-Saharan Africa represents an \"evolutionary familiar\" environment with lesser selection pressure on IQ than elsewhere.<ref>\n{{Cite journal\n | last = Kanazawa\n | first = Satoshi\n | title = Mind the gap... in intelligence: Re-examining the relationship between inequality and health\n | url = http://ww.lse.ac.uk/collections/MES/pdf/BJHP2006.pdf\n | format = PDF reprint\n | journal = [[British Journal of Health Psychology]]\n | volume = 11\n | issue = 4\n | date = 11 November 2006\n | pages = 623\u2013642\n | pmid = 17032488\n | doi = 10.1348/135910705X69842\n}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2010 paper, Kanazawa proposed the '''Savanna-IQ interaction hypothesis'''. This hypothesis, which is based on the \"savanna principle\", proposes that more intelligent individuals are more likely to engage in evolutionarily novel behaviors and believe in values that promote greater desire for novelty, such as [[political liberalism]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kanazawa |first=Satoshi |date=2010-02-16 |title=Why Liberals and Atheists Are More Intelligent |journal=Social Psychology Quarterly |volume=73 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201357 |doi=10.1177/0190272510361602 |issn=0190-2725|citeseerx=10.1.1.395.4490 }}</ref> It has been criticized for allegedly being unfalsifiable and for making contradictory predictions.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dutton |first=Edward |date=September 2013 |title=The Savanna-IQ interaction hypothesis: A critical examination of the comprehensive case presented in Kanazawa's The Intelligence Paradox |journal=Intelligence |volume=41 |issue=5 |pages=607\u2013614 |doi=10.1016/j.intell.2013.07.024 |issn=0160-2896}}</ref>\n\nIn response to Kanazawa's subsequent paper that attempted to integrate evolutionary psychology with intelligence research using the Savanna-IQ interaction hypothesis,<ref name=\"Kanazawa 2010\">{{cite journal|last1=Kanazawa|first1=Satoshi|author-link1=Satoshi Kanazawa|year=May\u2013June 2010|title=Evolutionary Psychology and Intelligence Research|journal=[[American Psychologist]]|volume=65|issue=4|pages=279\u2013289|doi=10.1037/a0019378|pmid=20455621|url=http://personal.lse.ac.uk/Kanazawa/pdfs/AP2010.pdf|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref> psychologists [[Scott Barry Kaufman]], [[Colin G. DeYoung]], Deirdre Reis, and Jeremy R. Gray found that \"performance on non-arbitrary, evolutionarily familiar problems is more strongly related to general intelligence than performance on arbitrary, evolutionarily novel problems\" after providing 112 subjects a 70-item computerized version of the [[Wason selection task]] in a [[social relation]]s context originally proposed by [[Leda Cosmides]] and [[John Tooby]] in ''[[The Adapted Mind]]'',<ref name=\"Cosmides & Tooby 1992\">{{cite book|last1=Cosmides|first1=Leda|author-link1=Leda Cosmides|last2=Tooby|first2=John|author-link2=John Tooby|editor-last1=Barkow|editor-first1=Jerome H.|editor-link1=Jerome H. Barkow|editor-last2=Cosmides|editor-first2=Leda|editor-first3=John|editor-last3=Tooby|title=The Adapted Mind: Evolutionary Psychology and the Generation of Culture|title-link=The Adapted Mind|chapter=3. Cognitive Adaptations for Social Exchange|place=New York|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|orig-year=1992|year=1995|pages=179\u2013206|isbn=978-0195101072}}</ref> contradicting Kanazawa's assertion that general intelligence correlated only with performance on evolutionarily unfamiliar rather than evolutionarily familiar problems.<ref name=\"Kaufman et al. 2010\">{{cite journal|last1=Kaufman|first1=Scott Barry|author-link1=Scott Barry Kaufman|last2=DeYoung|first2=Colin G.|author-link2=Colin G. DeYoung|last3=Reis|first3=Deidre L.|last4=Gray|first4=Jeremy R.|year=May\u2013June 2010|title=General intelligence predicts reasoning ability even for evolutionarily familiar content|journal=[[Intelligence (journal)|Intelligence]]|volume=39|issue=5|pages=311\u2013322|doi=10.1016/j.intell.2011.05.002|url=https://scottbarrykaufman.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/Kaufman-DeYoung-Reis-Gray-2011.pdf|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other views, publications and controversies==\nKanazawa has co-written three books with Alan Miller:\n*''Why Beautiful People Have More Daughters: From Dating, Shopping, and Praying to Going to War and Becoming a Billionaire\u2014Two Evolutionary Psychologists Explain Why We Do What We Do''\n*''Why Men Gamble and Women Buy Shoes: How Evolution Shaped the Way We Behave''\n*''Order by Accident: The Origins and Consequences of Conformity in Contemporary Japan''\n\nHe also wrote a blog, ''The Scientific Fundamentalist'', for ''Psychology Today'' until his dismissal in 2011.<ref name=\"dismissal\">{{cite news|title=Psychology Today Agrees to remove Controversial Author Satoshi Kanazawa from Website; Implements New Policies to Prevent Inflammatory Content|url=http://www.colorofchange.org/press/releases/2011/6/39/|newspaper=Color of Change|date=1 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nKanazawa uses the term ''Savanna principle'' to denote the theory that societal difficulties exist because \"the human brain\" evolved in Africa hundreds of thousands of years ago, a drastically different environment from today's urban, industrial society.<ref>Kanazawa, Satoshi (2004) The Savanna principle. Managerial and decision economics, 25 (1). pp. 41\u201354. {{ISSN|0143-6570}}</ref> In 2003, in an article in the ''[[Journal of Research in Personality]]'', he claimed to show that scientists generally made their biggest discoveries before their mid-30s, and compared this productivity curve to that of criminals.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0092-6566(02)00538-X |title=Why productivity fades with age: The crime\u2013genius connection |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=257\u2013272 |year=2003 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi }}</ref>\n\n=== Attractiveness and sex of offspring ===\nIn 2006, he published an article in the ''[[Journal of Theoretical Biology]]'', claiming that attractive people are 26% less likely to have male offspring.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,19992785-36398,00.html \"Beautiful people have girls\"] John Von Radowitz, News.com.au, 2 August 2006</ref><ref name=\"beautiful-parents-have-more-daughters\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jtbi.2006.07.017 |pmid=16949101 |title=Beautiful parents have more daughters: A further implication of the generalized Trivers\u2013Willard hypothesis (gTWH) |journal=Journal of Theoretical Biology |volume=244 |issue=1 |pages=133\u2013140 |year=2007 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi }}</ref> In a letter to the editors regarding Kanazawa's claim that attractive people are more likely to have daughters,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jtbi.2006.11.005 |pmid=17184794 |title=Letter to the editors regarding some papers of Dr. Satoshi Kanazawa |journal=Journal of Theoretical Biology |volume=245 |issue=3 |pages=597\u2013599 |year=2007 |last1=Gelman |first1=Andrew }}</ref> [[Columbia University|Columbia]] statistician [[Andrew Gelman]] points out that a correct interpretation of the regression coefficients in Kanazawa's analysis is that attractive people are 8% more likely to have girls, an error that Kanazawa acknowledges.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=20066931 |jstor=27784427 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi |title=The role of height in the sex difference in intelligence |journal=The American Journal of Psychology |volume=122 |issue=4 |pages=527\u2013536 |last2=Reyniers |first2=Diane J. |year=2009 }}</ref> Gelman argues that Kanazawa's analysis does not convincingly show causality, because of possible [[endogeneity (econometrics)|endogeneity]] as well as problematic interpretations of [[statistical significance]] in multiple comparisons. While Kanazawa claims that the former error is \"merely linguistic\" and that he addressed the latter two in his initial article,<ref name=\"beautiful-parents-have-more-daughters\" /> Gelman maintains that his original criticism remains valid.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1511/2009.79.310 |title=Of Beauty, Sex and Power |journal=American Scientist |volume=97 |issue=4 |page=310 |year=2009 |last1=Gelman |first1=Andrew |last2=Weakliem |first2=David }}</ref>\n\n=== Race and attractiveness ===\nIn May 2011, he published an article in ''Psychology Today'' that explored why black women had been rated less attractive than those of other races in the [[National Longitudinal Study of Adolescent Health]]. Subsequent critical independent analysis of the results showed that the difference in assessed attractiveness held for three of the four data sets in the National Longitudinal Study of Adolescent Health and that there was only a statistically significant race difference in younger women and that it disappeared by early adulthood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/beautiful-minds/201105/black-women-are-not-rated-less-attractive-our-independent-analysis-the-a|title=Black Women Are Not (Rated) Less Attractive! Our Independent Analysis of the Add Health Dataset}}</ref> Applying his same reasoning to males, Kanazawa also concluded in his article that black men would generally be considered more attractive. Kanazawa was also criticised for arguing that the [[Factor analysis|common factor]] of subjective interviewer ratings of attractiveness used in his analysis constitutes an objective scale of attractiveness.<ref name=\"Britton\">{{cite web |first=Khadijah |last=Britton |date=May 23, 2011 |url=http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/2011/05/23/the-data-are-in-regarding-satoshi-kanazawa/ |work=Scientific American |title=The Data Are In Regarding Satoshi Kanazawa }}</ref>\n\nThe article caused outrage and was widely criticised. The first criticisms were published in the [[blogosphere]] leading to the creation of petitions on [[Change.org]] and [[Facebook]] to have Kanazawa fired.<ref>Angus Hutchison. [http://uk.ibtimes.com/articles/149060/20110520/black-women-attractive-psychology-today-satoshi-kanazawa-blog-lse.htm \"'Black women less attractive' blogpost: Anger grows\".] ''[[International Business Times]]'', 20 May 2011.</ref> \nBut also other scientists, including a group of evolutionary psychologists publishing a joint statement published criticisms, distancing the discipline of evolutionary psychology from Kanazawa's research.<ref name=\"Kanazawa Statement\"/> ''Psychology Today'' pulled the article and on 27 May 2011, issued an apology to anyone who had been offended and stated that they had not reviewed Kanazawa's article before its publication,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/brainstorm/201105/apology-psychology-today |title=An Apology from Psychology Today |first=Kaja |last=Perina |date=27 May 2011 |publisher=Psychology Today }}</ref> and stated that they would police more strictly for controversial content in the future.<ref name=\"dismissal\" />\n\nIn September 2011, Kanazawa apologised to LSE director Judith Rees, saying he \"deeply regrets\" the \"unintended consequences\" of the blog and accepting that \"some of [his] arguments may have been flawed and not supported by the available evidence\". An internal LSE investigation found that Kanazawa had brought the school into disrepute and prohibited him from publishing in non-peer-reviewed outlets for a year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jack Grove|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/417449.article|title=LSE scholar admits race analysis was 'flawed'|work=Times Higher Education|date=15 September 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027143911/http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=417449&c=1|archivedate=27 October 2012}}</ref> Following the controversy, an open letter was signed by 68 evolutionary psychologists distancing themselves from Kanazawa and defending evolutionary psychology, writing \"The principle of applying evolutionary theory to the study of human psychology and behaviour is sound, and there is a great deal of high-quality, nuanced, culturally-sensitive evolutionary research ongoing in the UK and elsewhere today\".<ref name=\"Kanazawa Statement\"/> In response, an international group of 23 scientists published a letter in ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' defending Kanazawa's work.<ref name=\"Sinned against, not sinning\">[http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=416527 \"Sinned against, not sinning\"] 16 June 2011, Times Higher Education</ref>\n\n=== Correlation of health and intelligence ===\nIn 2006, Kanazawa used the \"Savanna principle\" to explain the correlation of health and IQ vs. health and wealth. \nHe argued that IQ is a better predictor for health than wealth or inequality in most regions of the world, except in Sub-Saharan Africa, where health is more strongly correlated to wealth than to IQ, because Sub-Saharan Africa represents an \"evolutionary familiar\" environment with lesser selection pressure on IQ than elsewhere.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1348/135910705X69842 |title=Mind the gap\u2026in intelligence: Re-examining the relationship between inequality and health |journal=British Journal of Health Psychology |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=623\u2013642 |year=2006 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi |pmid=17032488}}</ref> In a criticism of the paper George Ellison (2007) argued that the conclusion was based on \"flawed assumptions, questionable data, inappropriate analysis and biased interpretations\".<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1348/135910707X180972 |title=Health, wealth and IQ in sub-Saharan Africa: Challenges facing the Savanna Principle as an explanation for global inequalities in health |journal=British Journal of Health Psychology |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=191\u2013227 |year=2007 |last1=Ellison |first1=George T. H. |pmid=17456282|url=http://eprints.kingston.ac.uk/3738/ }}</ref>\n\n=== Muslims, terrorism and Psychology Today ===\nIn his blog ''The Scientific Fundamentalist'', hosted by ''[[Psychology Today]]'', Kanazawa published often on Muslims, Islam and the Middle East. The publication ''Psychology Today'' later received a significant amount of negative but constructive feedback and criticism following some of Kanazawa's more controversial articles.\n\nOn 6 March 2008, in the article subtitled \"All you need is hate\", he suggested a \"little thought experiment\", asking his readers to ''\"(i)magine that, on September 11, 2001, when the Twin Towers came down, the President of the United States was not George W. Bush, but Ann Coulter. What would have happened then? On September 12, President Coulter would have ordered the US military forces to drop 35 nuclear bombs throughout the Middle East, killing all of our actual and potential enemy combatants, and their wives and children. On September 13, the war would have been over and won, without a single American life lost\"''. He concludes, ''\"(y)es, we need a woman in the White House, but not the one who\u2019s running\"'', suggesting that in his opinion someone like Ann Coulter is preferable.<ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-why-we-are-losing-war\">{{cite web |title=Why we are losing this war |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/200803/why-we-are-losing-war |website=Psychology Today |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=6 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 January 2010, he posted an article titled ''\"What\u2019s Wrong with Muslims?\"'' In it he claims that Muslim \"are all united in their values and goals by their singular identity of being Muslims\", and that although it may be \"tempting to dismiss these observations\", and \"politically correct and comforting\" to say that terrorists are \u2018extremists\u2019 or \u2018jihadists\u2019, that would be \"factually inaccurate\", he claims.<ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-whats-wrong-with-muslims?-kanazawa\">{{cite web |author1=Satoshi Kanazawa |title=What's Wrong with Muslims? |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/201001/what-s-wrong-muslims |website=Psychology Today |publisher=The Scientific Fundamentalist blog |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=10 January 2010}}</ref>\nHe further elaborated on his views seven days later, on 17 January, in another article on the same website. In its intro he claims that \"Racial profiling works and saves lives\". Although, at some point through this article, he dismisses an [[Islamophobia|Islamophobic stereotype]] expressed through the [[Brian Kilmeade#\"All terrorists are Muslims\"|media trope]] \u201cNot all Muslims are terrorists, but all terrorists are Muslims\u201d, but follows it with one of his own, writing: \"half of Muslims worldwide are terrorists or active supporters of terrorism, who would encourage their sons, brothers, and nephews to blow themselves up.\"<ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-naked-air-kanazawa\">{{cite web |author1=Satoshi Kanazawa |title=Naked Air |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/201001/naked-air |website=Psychology Today |publisher=The Scientific Fundamentalist blog |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=17 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the article titled \"Is Your Professor an Islamophobe?\", at the time Columbia University epidemiologist and HuffPost contributor, [[Abdul El-Sayed]], quoted Kanazawa's articles, along with some other authors', when he discussed the phenomenon of \"a growing number of academics using (their) intellectual identity to promote intolerance and xenophobia against Islam and Muslims\". El-Sayed expressed concern that, as he writes, \"the fundamental messages portrayed in the public musings of academics are no different from the crude ramblings of a [[Glenn Beck]] or a [[Rush Limbaugh]], they are many times more damaging\". He explains how \"PhD's and daunting lists of academic publications to their names, academics are perceived to carry the weighty, objective backing of \u201cknowledge\u201d and \u201cscience\u201d by the lay-public, so bigoted, ignorant opinions on their parts are taken as justification to those who already hold skewed perspectives and hateful opinions about Islam and Muslims\". He points out that \"these academic dogmatists cloak (perhaps under their PhD hoods) the fire of Islamophobia with the cool, measured tones of objectivity\".<ref name=\"El-Sayed-HuffPost-Is-Professor-Islamophobe?\">{{cite web |last1=El-Sayed |first1=Abdulrahman |last2=Professor |first2=ContributorAssistant |last3=University |first3=Columbia |title=Is Your Professor an Islamophobe? |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/phds-promote-xenophobia-a_b_443510 |website=HuffPost |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=4 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Nanjala Nyabola]], writing in [[The Guardian]], dismissed Kanazawa's claims as \"racist nonsense\". She also warned of growing concern over ''Psychology Today's'' position, at the time, regarding issue, also expressed by various academics and numerous public intellectuals,<ref name=\"huffpost.com-kanazawa-does-not-speak-for-us\"/> among them the publication's own authors,<ref name=\"theguardian.com-Nyabola-kanazawa-black-women-psychology-today\"/> such as Mikhail Lyubansky, who criticized the publication, noting that \"extraordinary claims (especially those that hurt and damage marginalized groups) require extraordinary evidence and editorial oversight\".<ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-beauty-eye-beholder-see-what-culture-socializes\">{{cite web |author1=Mikhail Lyubansky Ph.D. |title=Beauty May Be In Eye of Beholder But Eyes See What Culture Socializes |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/between-the-lines/201105/beauty-may-be-in-eye-beholder-eyes-see-what-culture-socializes |website=Psychology Today |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=16 May 2011}}</ref> Similarly, Christopher Ryan criticized Kanazawa's views and writings, calling him the \"[[Rush Limbaugh]] of Evolutionary Psychology\", noting that \"if Rush Limbaugh, [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]], or [[Ann Coulter]] had studied science, they'd be penning articles like some of Kanazawa's.<ref name=\"psychologytoday.comi-kanazawa-is-rush-limbaugh-evolutionary-psychology\">{{cite web |author1=Christopher Ryan Ph.D. |title=Satoshi Kanazawa Is the Rush Limbaugh of Evolutionary Psychology |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/sex-dawn/201105/satoshi-kanazawa-is-the-rush-limbaugh-evolutionary-psychology |website=Psychology Today |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=18 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-evolutionary-psychology-used-car\">{{cite web |author1=Christopher Ryan Ph.D. |title=Is Evolutionary Psychology a Used Car? |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/sex-dawn/200811/is-evolutionary-psychology-used-car |website=Psychology Today |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=10 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nA shortlist of 10 of Kanazawa's claims is summarized by [[The Independent]] in the article \"Inconvenient truths about our evolution?\"<ref name=\"in-inconvenient-truths-evolution\">{{cite web |title=Inconvenient truths about our evolution? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/inconvenient-truths-about-our-evolution-2146994.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=30 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Universities and engagements controversies==\nA group of 68 evolutionary psychologists issued an open letter titled \"Kanazawa's bad science does not represent evolutionary psychology\" rejecting his views,<ref name=\"Kanazawa Statement\"/> and an article on the same theme was published by 35 academics in ''American Psychologist''.<ref name=\"huffpost.com-kanazawa-does-not-speak-for-us\"/>\n\n<!-- ===London University controversy=== -->\n*In May 2011 and in the wake of his latest blogging incident, over 120,000 students of the University of London Union Senate subsequently unanimously voted to condemn his research.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk-lse-academic-triggers-race-row\">{{cite web |last1=Sample |first1=Ian |last2=correspondent |first2=science |title=LSE academic's claim 'black women less attractive' triggers race row |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/may/19/lse-academic-triggers-race-row |website=The Guardian |accessdate=31 May 2019 |date=19 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ===Psychology Today dismissal=== -->\n*In February 2008, he started a blog on ''Psychology Today'' called \"The Scientific Fundamentalist\". In June 2011, the publication dismissed Kanazawa for good in reaction to his ''\"Why Are Black Women Less Physically Attractive Than Other Women?\"'' article.<ref name=\"Fired-For-Black-Women-ugly\">{{cite web |title=Psychologist Fired For \"Why Black Women Are Unattractive\" Study |url=http://newsone.com/nation/casey-gane-mccalla/satoshi-kanazawa-fired-psychology-today/ |website=News One |accessdate=31 May 2019 |language=en |date=6 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ===LSE suspension=== -->\n*In September 2011, [[London School of Economics]] (LSE) suspended Kanazawa from publishing any material in non-[[peer review]]ed journals for a year and he issued an apology stating that the post was \"flawed\".<ref name=\"lse.ac.uk-Kanazawa\">{{cite web |last1=Editor |first1=LSE Web |title=Dr Satoshi Kanazawa - findings of internal review and disciplinary hearing - 09 - 2011 - News archives - News and media - Website archive - Home |url=http://www2.lse.ac.uk/newsAndMedia/news/archives/2011/09/Kanazawa.aspx |website=www.lse.ac.uk |accessdate=31 May 2019 |language=en-gb}}</ref><ref name=\"LSE-web.archive.org-timeshighereducation.co.uk\">{{cite web |title=Times Higher Education - LSE scholar admits race analysis was 'flawed' |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027143911/http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=417449&c=1 |website=web.archive.org |accessdate=31 May 2019 |date=27 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ===Big Think dismissal=== -->\n*In September 2012, after the period of 12 months when he was prohibited from publishing in non-peer-reviewed outlets by the LSE, he was hired by the blog ''[[Big Think]]'' as a contributing editor; the co-operation was discontinued on 29 March 2013.<ref name=\"bigthink.com-bad-science-of-satoshi-kanazawa\"/><ref name=\"bigthink.com-end-of-bold-experiment-kanazawa\">{{cite web|url=http://bigthink.com/the-voice-of-big-think/the-end-of-a-bold-experiment-big-think-and-satoshi-kanazawa|title=The End of a Bold Experiment: Big Think and Satoshi Kanazawa|author=Hopkins, Phillip|publisher=Big Think|date=29 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ===Northwestern University controversy=== -->\n*In December 2018 students at [[Northwestern University]] gathered more than 4,000 signatures on a petition in a few days, asking the university to overturn Kanazawa's approved application to conduct research in Evanston.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com-northwestern-students-want-scholar-out-their-campus\">{{cite web |author1=Colleen Flaherty |title=Northwestern students want a controversial scholar off their campus |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/12/19/northwestern-students-want-controversial-scholar-their-campus |website=www.insidehighered.com |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Evolutionary psychology]]\n* [[Gene-centered view of evolution]]\n* [[Tit for tat]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0190272510361602 |title=Why Liberals and Atheists Are More Intelligent |journal=Social Psychology Quarterly |volume=73 |pages=33\u201357 |year=2010 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=S. |citeseerx=10.1.1.395.4490 }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.scienceonreligion.org/index.php/news-research/research-updates/150-is-atheism-linked-to-intelligence <!-- n/a http://ibcsr.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=150:is-atheism-linked-to-intelligence&catid=25:research-news&Itemid=59 --> |title= Is atheism linked to intelligence? |quote= A review of Kanazawa's recent \"Why liberals and atheists are more intelligent\"  |publisher= Science on Religion <!-- Institute for the Bio-Cultural Study of Religion (IBCSR) --> |date= Mar 2010 |first= Derek |last= Michaud }}\n* {{Google Scholar id|Zc33N34AAAAJ}}\n* [http://bigthink.com/satoshikanazawa Profile and videos] at [[Big Think]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kanazawa, Satoshi}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:American academics of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:British people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:British psychologists]]\n[[Category:Critics of multiculturalism]]\n[[Category:Ethnic and racial stereotypes]]\n[[Category:Evolutionary biology]]\n[[Category:Evolutionary psychologists]]\n[[Category:Intelligence researchers]]\n[[Category:Islamophobia in scholarship]]\n[[Category:Race and intelligence controversy]]\n[[Category:Scientific racism]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name=Satoshi Kanazawa\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption=\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|df=yes|1962|11|16}}\n|birth_place=United States<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi |year=2012 |title=The Intelligence Paradox: Why the Intelligent Choice Isn't Always the Smart One |isbn=978-0-470-58695-2 }}{{page needed|date=December 2016}}</ref>\n|citizenship=United States<br />United Kingdom\n|residence= [[England]]\n|field=[[Evolutionary psychology]]\n|alma_mater=[[University of Arizona]]\n|work_institution=[[London School of Economics]]\n|known_for=\n}}\n\n'''Satoshi Kanazawa''' (born 16 November 1962) is an American-born British [[Evolutionary psychology|evolutionary psychologist]] and writer. He is currently [[Reader (academic rank)|Reader]] in [[Management]] at the [[London School of Economics]]. His work uses evolutionary psychology to analyse social sciences such as sociology, economics, and anthropology.<ref>[http://www.lse.ac.uk/people/s.kanazawa@lse.ac.uk/ Dr Satoshi Kanazawa], London School of Economics. Retrieved 6 September 2006</ref> Kanazawa's comments and research on [[race and intelligence]], [[Cognitive epidemiology|health and intelligence]], [[multiculturalism]], and the relationship between [[physical attractiveness]] and [[intelligence]] have led to condemnation from observers and colleagues. He attributes this to [[political correctness]] and [[censorship]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/if-the-truth-offends-it-s-our-job-offend |title=Psychology Today: \"If the truth offends, it's our job to offend\", 2008 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20151223160938/https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/200802/if-the-truth-offends-it-s-our-job-offend |archive-date=23 December 2015}}</ref> while his critics have described his claims as [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]]<ref name=\"bigthink.com-bad-science-of-satoshi-kanazawa\">{{cite web |title=The bad science of Satoshi Kanazawa |url=http://bigthink.com/neurobonkers/the-bad-science-of-satoshi-kanazawa |website=Big Think |accessdate=31 May 2019 |language=en |date=26 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Britton\" /> and [[racist]].<ref name=\"theguardian.com-Nyabola-kanazawa-black-women-psychology-today\">{{cite web |last1=Nyabola |first1=Nanjala |title=Satoshi Kanazawa's racist nonsense should not be tolerated |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/may/18/satoshi-kanazawa-black-women-psychology-today |website=The Guardian |accessdate=31 May 2019 |date=18 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Adam |title=Doesn't This Place Have Standards? |url=https://bigthink.com/daylight-atheism/doesnt-this-place-have-standards |accessdate=1 July 2019 |work=Big Think |date=12 September 2012 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn response to ongoing controversies over his stated views, such as [[Sub-Saharan Africa|Sub-Saharan Black Africa]]n countries suffer from [[chronic poverty]] and [[disease]] because their people have lower IQs, and black women are objectively less attractive than women of other races, he was dismissed from writing for ''[[Psychology Today]]'', and his employer, the [[London School of Economics]], prohibited him from publishing in non-peer-reviewed outlets for 12 months.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-14945110 \"LSE lecturer Dr Satoshi Kanazawa tells of race blog 'regret'\"]  \"BBC, 16 September 2011\"</ref> A group of 68 evolutionary psychologists issued an open letter titled \"Kanazawa's bad science does not represent evolutionary psychology\" rejecting his views,<ref name=\"Kanazawa Statement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/231350957/Kanazawa-Statement |title=Kanazawa Statement &#124; Academia &#124; Science |publisher=Scribd.com |date=2016-03-29 |accessdate=2018-04-28}}</ref> and an article on the same theme was published by 35 academics in ''American Psychologist''.<ref name=\"huffpost.com-kanazawa-does-not-speak-for-us\">{{cite web |title=Satoshi Kanazawa Does Not Speak for All of Evolutionary Psychology |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/satoshi-kanazawa-does-not_n_863359 |author=Scott Barry Kaufman |website=HuffPost |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=18 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nHe began working at the London School of Economics in 2003.<ref name=\"personal.lse.ac.uk-Kanazawa\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Satoshi Kanazawa |url=http://personal.lse.ac.uk/Kanazawa |website=personal.lse.ac.uk |accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Savanna principle==\n{{see also|Cognitive epidemiology#Substance abuse}}\n\"Savanna Principle\" is a term coined by Satoshi Kanazawa in 2004 for the principle that [[human behavior]] remaining to some extent adapted to the ancestral environment of early ''[[Homo]]'' in the [[savanna]] may lead to problems in a modern (Industrial or post-Industrial) environment. \nKanazawa uses this disparity to explain \"a host of societal difficulties\". For example, ancestors who craved sugary and fatty foods lived longer and were healthier than those who didn't, in a time that such things were relatively scarce. Today, the abundance of such temptations leads to [[obesity]] and [[heart disease]]. Similar scenarios are illustrated with television,<ref>{{cite web\n   |url        = http://www.lse.ac.uk/collections/MES/pdf/JCEP2006.pdf\n   |title      = Why the less intelligent may enjoy television more than the more ...\n   |author     = Satoshi Kanazawa\n   |accessdate = 2007-11-05\n    }}</ref> sex, and jealousy.\n\nKanazawa presented this argument in 2004 in the form of a short journal article called \"The Savanna Principle<ref>''Managerial and decision economics''  25 (1), 2004, pp. 41\u201354</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kanazawa|first1=Satoshi|title=The Savanna Principle|journal=Managerial and Decision Economics|date=1 January 2004|volume=25|issue=1|pages=41\u201354|doi=10.1002/mde.1130|language=en|issn=1099-1468}}</ref> and expounded upon it in a 2007 book aimed at a general audience, ''Why Beautiful People Have More Daughters''.<ref>Kanazawa, Satoshi ''Why Beautiful People Have More Daughters'' (2007) All, {{ISBN|978-0-399-53365-5}}.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Kanazawa used the \"Savanna Principle\" to explain the correlation of health and IQ vs. health and wealth. He argued that IQ is a better predictor for health than wealth or inequality in most regions of the world, except in Sub-Saharan Africa, where health is more strongly correlated to wealth than to IQ, because Sub-Saharan Africa represents an \"evolutionary familiar\" environment with lesser selection pressure on IQ than elsewhere.<ref>\n{{Cite journal\n | last = Kanazawa\n | first = Satoshi\n | title = Mind the gap... in intelligence: Re-examining the relationship between inequality and health\n | url = http://ww.lse.ac.uk/collections/MES/pdf/BJHP2006.pdf\n | format = PDF reprint\n | journal = [[British Journal of Health Psychology]]\n | volume = 11\n | issue = 4\n | date = 11 November 2006\n | pages = 623\u2013642\n | pmid = 17032488\n | doi = 10.1348/135910705X69842\n}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2010 paper, Kanazawa proposed the '''Savanna-IQ interaction hypothesis'''. This hypothesis, which is based on the \"savanna principle\", proposes that more intelligent individuals are more likely to engage in evolutionarily novel behaviors and believe in values that promote greater desire for novelty, such as [[political liberalism]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kanazawa |first=Satoshi |date=2010-02-16 |title=Why Liberals and Atheists Are More Intelligent |journal=Social Psychology Quarterly |volume=73 |issue=1 |pages=33\u201357 |doi=10.1177/0190272510361602 |issn=0190-2725|citeseerx=10.1.1.395.4490 }}</ref> It has been criticized for allegedly being unfalsifiable and for making contradictory predictions.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dutton |first=Edward |date=September 2013 |title=The Savanna-IQ interaction hypothesis: A critical examination of the comprehensive case presented in Kanazawa's The Intelligence Paradox |journal=Intelligence |volume=41 |issue=5 |pages=607\u2013614 |doi=10.1016/j.intell.2013.07.024 |issn=0160-2896}}</ref>\n\nIn response to Kanazawa's subsequent paper that attempted to integrate evolutionary psychology with intelligence research using the Savanna-IQ interaction hypothesis,<ref name=\"Kanazawa 2010\">{{cite journal|last1=Kanazawa|first1=Satoshi|author-link1=Satoshi Kanazawa|year=May\u2013June 2010|title=Evolutionary Psychology and Intelligence Research|journal=[[American Psychologist]]|volume=65|issue=4|pages=279\u2013289|doi=10.1037/a0019378|pmid=20455621|url=http://personal.lse.ac.uk/Kanazawa/pdfs/AP2010.pdf|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref> psychologists [[Scott Barry Kaufman]], [[Colin G. DeYoung]], Deirdre Reis, and Jeremy R. Gray found that \"performance on non-arbitrary, evolutionarily familiar problems is more strongly related to general intelligence than performance on arbitrary, evolutionarily novel problems\" after providing 112 subjects a 70-item computerized version of the [[Wason selection task]] in a [[social relation]]s context originally proposed by [[Leda Cosmides]] and [[John Tooby]] in ''[[The Adapted Mind]]'',<ref name=\"Cosmides & Tooby 1992\">{{cite book|last1=Cosmides|first1=Leda|author-link1=Leda Cosmides|last2=Tooby|first2=John|author-link2=John Tooby|editor-last1=Barkow|editor-first1=Jerome H.|editor-link1=Jerome H. Barkow|editor-last2=Cosmides|editor-first2=Leda|editor-first3=John|editor-last3=Tooby|title=The Adapted Mind: Evolutionary Psychology and the Generation of Culture|title-link=The Adapted Mind|chapter=3. Cognitive Adaptations for Social Exchange|place=New York|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|orig-year=1992|year=1995|pages=181\u2013184|isbn=978-0195101072}}</ref> contradicting Kanazawa's assertion that general intelligence correlated only with performance on evolutionarily unfamiliar rather than evolutionarily familiar problems.<ref name=\"Kaufman et al. 2010\">{{cite journal|last1=Kaufman|first1=Scott Barry|author-link1=Scott Barry Kaufman|last2=DeYoung|first2=Colin G.|author-link2=Colin G. DeYoung|last3=Reis|first3=Deidre L.|last4=Gray|first4=Jeremy R.|year=May\u2013June 2010|title=General intelligence predicts reasoning ability even for evolutionarily familiar content|journal=[[Intelligence (journal)|Intelligence]]|volume=39|issue=5|pages=311\u2013322|doi=10.1016/j.intell.2011.05.002|url=https://scottbarrykaufman.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/Kaufman-DeYoung-Reis-Gray-2011.pdf|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Other views, publications and controversies==\nKanazawa has co-written three books with Alan Miller:\n*''Why Beautiful People Have More Daughters: From Dating, Shopping, and Praying to Going to War and Becoming a Billionaire\u2014Two Evolutionary Psychologists Explain Why We Do What We Do''\n*''Why Men Gamble and Women Buy Shoes: How Evolution Shaped the Way We Behave''\n*''Order by Accident: The Origins and Consequences of Conformity in Contemporary Japan''\n\nHe also wrote a blog, ''The Scientific Fundamentalist'', for ''Psychology Today'' until his dismissal in 2011.<ref name=\"dismissal\">{{cite news|title=Psychology Today Agrees to remove Controversial Author Satoshi Kanazawa from Website; Implements New Policies to Prevent Inflammatory Content|url=http://www.colorofchange.org/press/releases/2011/6/39/|newspaper=Color of Change|date=1 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nKanazawa uses the term ''Savanna principle'' to denote the theory that societal difficulties exist because \"the human brain\" evolved in Africa hundreds of thousands of years ago, a drastically different environment from today's urban, industrial society.<ref>Kanazawa, Satoshi (2004) The Savanna principle. Managerial and decision economics, 25 (1). pp. 41\u201354. {{ISSN|0143-6570}}</ref> In 2003, in an article in the ''[[Journal of Research in Personality]]'', he claimed to show that scientists generally made their biggest discoveries before their mid-30s, and compared this productivity curve to that of criminals.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0092-6566(02)00538-X |title=Why productivity fades with age: The crime\u2013genius connection |journal=Journal of Research in Personality |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=257\u2013272 |year=2003 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi }}</ref>\n\n=== Attractiveness and sex of offspring ===\nIn 2006, he published an article in the ''[[Journal of Theoretical Biology]]'', claiming that attractive people are 26% less likely to have male offspring.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/story/0,23599,19992785-36398,00.html \"Beautiful people have girls\"] John Von Radowitz, News.com.au, 2 August 2006</ref><ref name=\"beautiful-parents-have-more-daughters\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jtbi.2006.07.017 |pmid=16949101 |title=Beautiful parents have more daughters: A further implication of the generalized Trivers\u2013Willard hypothesis (gTWH) |journal=Journal of Theoretical Biology |volume=244 |issue=1 |pages=133\u2013140 |year=2007 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi }}</ref> In a letter to the editors regarding Kanazawa's claim that attractive people are more likely to have daughters,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.jtbi.2006.11.005 |pmid=17184794 |title=Letter to the editors regarding some papers of Dr. Satoshi Kanazawa |journal=Journal of Theoretical Biology |volume=245 |issue=3 |pages=597\u2013599 |year=2007 |last1=Gelman |first1=Andrew }}</ref> [[Columbia University|Columbia]] statistician [[Andrew Gelman]] points out that a correct interpretation of the regression coefficients in Kanazawa's analysis is that attractive people are 8% more likely to have girls, an error that Kanazawa acknowledges.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=20066931 |jstor=27784427 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi |title=The role of height in the sex difference in intelligence |journal=The American Journal of Psychology |volume=122 |issue=4 |pages=527\u2013536 |last2=Reyniers |first2=Diane J. |year=2009 }}</ref> Gelman argues that Kanazawa's analysis does not convincingly show causality, because of possible [[endogeneity (econometrics)|endogeneity]] as well as problematic interpretations of [[statistical significance]] in multiple comparisons. While Kanazawa claims that the former error is \"merely linguistic\" and that he addressed the latter two in his initial article,<ref name=\"beautiful-parents-have-more-daughters\" /> Gelman maintains that his original criticism remains valid.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1511/2009.79.310 |title=Of Beauty, Sex and Power |journal=American Scientist |volume=97 |issue=4 |page=310 |year=2009 |last1=Gelman |first1=Andrew |last2=Weakliem |first2=David }}</ref>\n\n=== Race and attractiveness ===\nIn May 2011, he published an article in ''Psychology Today'' that explored why black women had been rated less attractive than those of other races in the [[National Longitudinal Study of Adolescent Health]]. Subsequent critical independent analysis of the results showed that the difference in assessed attractiveness held for three of the four data sets in the National Longitudinal Study of Adolescent Health and that there was only a statistically significant race difference in younger women and that it disappeared by early adulthood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/beautiful-minds/201105/black-women-are-not-rated-less-attractive-our-independent-analysis-the-a|title=Black Women Are Not (Rated) Less Attractive! Our Independent Analysis of the Add Health Dataset}}</ref> Applying his same reasoning to males, Kanazawa also concluded in his article that black men would generally be considered more attractive. Kanazawa was also criticised for arguing that the [[Factor analysis|common factor]] of subjective interviewer ratings of attractiveness used in his analysis constitutes an objective scale of attractiveness.<ref name=\"Britton\">{{cite web |first=Khadijah |last=Britton |date=May 23, 2011 |url=http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/2011/05/23/the-data-are-in-regarding-satoshi-kanazawa/ |work=Scientific American |title=The Data Are In Regarding Satoshi Kanazawa }}</ref>\n\nThe article caused outrage and was widely criticised. The first criticisms were published in the [[blogosphere]] leading to the creation of petitions on [[Change.org]] and [[Facebook]] to have Kanazawa fired.<ref>Angus Hutchison. [http://uk.ibtimes.com/articles/149060/20110520/black-women-attractive-psychology-today-satoshi-kanazawa-blog-lse.htm \"'Black women less attractive' blogpost: Anger grows\".] ''[[International Business Times]]'', 20 May 2011.</ref> \nBut also other scientists, including a group of evolutionary psychologists publishing a joint statement published criticisms, distancing the discipline of evolutionary psychology from Kanazawa's research.<ref name=\"Kanazawa Statement\"/> ''Psychology Today'' pulled the article and on 27 May 2011, issued an apology to anyone who had been offended and stated that they had not reviewed Kanazawa's article before its publication,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/brainstorm/201105/apology-psychology-today |title=An Apology from Psychology Today |first=Kaja |last=Perina |date=27 May 2011 |publisher=Psychology Today }}</ref> and stated that they would police more strictly for controversial content in the future.<ref name=\"dismissal\" />\n\nIn September 2011, Kanazawa apologised to LSE director Judith Rees, saying he \"deeply regrets\" the \"unintended consequences\" of the blog and accepting that \"some of [his] arguments may have been flawed and not supported by the available evidence\". An internal LSE investigation found that Kanazawa had brought the school into disrepute and prohibited him from publishing in non-peer-reviewed outlets for a year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jack Grove|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/417449.article|title=LSE scholar admits race analysis was 'flawed'|work=Times Higher Education|date=15 September 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027143911/http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=417449&c=1|archivedate=27 October 2012}}</ref> Following the controversy, an open letter was signed by 68 evolutionary psychologists distancing themselves from Kanazawa and defending evolutionary psychology, writing \"The principle of applying evolutionary theory to the study of human psychology and behaviour is sound, and there is a great deal of high-quality, nuanced, culturally-sensitive evolutionary research ongoing in the UK and elsewhere today\".<ref name=\"Kanazawa Statement\"/> In response, an international group of 23 scientists published a letter in ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' defending Kanazawa's work.<ref name=\"Sinned against, not sinning\">[http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=416527 \"Sinned against, not sinning\"] 16 June 2011, Times Higher Education</ref>\n\n=== Correlation of health and intelligence ===\nIn 2006, Kanazawa used the \"Savanna principle\" to explain the correlation of health and IQ vs. health and wealth. \nHe argued that IQ is a better predictor for health than wealth or inequality in most regions of the world, except in Sub-Saharan Africa, where health is more strongly correlated to wealth than to IQ, because Sub-Saharan Africa represents an \"evolutionary familiar\" environment with lesser selection pressure on IQ than elsewhere.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1348/135910705X69842 |title=Mind the gap\u2026in intelligence: Re-examining the relationship between inequality and health |journal=British Journal of Health Psychology |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=623\u2013642 |year=2006 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=Satoshi |pmid=17032488}}</ref> In a criticism of the paper George Ellison (2007) argued that the conclusion was based on \"flawed assumptions, questionable data, inappropriate analysis and biased interpretations\".<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1348/135910707X180972 |title=Health, wealth and IQ in sub-Saharan Africa: Challenges facing the Savanna Principle as an explanation for global inequalities in health |journal=British Journal of Health Psychology |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=191\u2013227 |year=2007 |last1=Ellison |first1=George T. H. |pmid=17456282|url=http://eprints.kingston.ac.uk/3738/ }}</ref>\n\n=== Muslims, terrorism and Psychology Today ===\nIn his blog ''The Scientific Fundamentalist'', hosted by ''[[Psychology Today]]'', Kanazawa published often on Muslims, Islam and the Middle East. The publication ''Psychology Today'' later received a significant amount of negative but constructive feedback and criticism following some of Kanazawa's more controversial articles.\n\nOn 6 March 2008, in the article subtitled \"All you need is hate\", he suggested a \"little thought experiment\", asking his readers to ''\"(i)magine that, on September 11, 2001, when the Twin Towers came down, the President of the United States was not George W. Bush, but Ann Coulter. What would have happened then? On September 12, President Coulter would have ordered the US military forces to drop 35 nuclear bombs throughout the Middle East, killing all of our actual and potential enemy combatants, and their wives and children. On September 13, the war would have been over and won, without a single American life lost\"''. He concludes, ''\"(y)es, we need a woman in the White House, but not the one who\u2019s running\"'', suggesting that in his opinion someone like Ann Coulter is preferable.<ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-why-we-are-losing-war\">{{cite web |title=Why we are losing this war |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/200803/why-we-are-losing-war |website=Psychology Today |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=6 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 January 2010, he posted an article titled ''\"What\u2019s Wrong with Muslims?\"'' In it he claims that Muslim \"are all united in their values and goals by their singular identity of being Muslims\", and that although it may be \"tempting to dismiss these observations\", and \"politically correct and comforting\" to say that terrorists are \u2018extremists\u2019 or \u2018jihadists\u2019, that would be \"factually inaccurate\", he claims.<ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-whats-wrong-with-muslims?-kanazawa\">{{cite web |author1=Satoshi Kanazawa |title=What's Wrong with Muslims? |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/201001/what-s-wrong-muslims |website=Psychology Today |publisher=The Scientific Fundamentalist blog |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=10 January 2010}}</ref>\nHe further elaborated on his views seven days later, on 17 January, in another article on the same website. In its intro he claims that \"Racial profiling works and saves lives\". Although, at some point through this article, he dismisses an [[Islamophobia|Islamophobic stereotype]] expressed through the [[Brian Kilmeade#\"All terrorists are Muslims\"|media trope]] \u201cNot all Muslims are terrorists, but all terrorists are Muslims\u201d, but follows it with one of his own, writing: \"half of Muslims worldwide are terrorists or active supporters of terrorism, who would encourage their sons, brothers, and nephews to blow themselves up.\"<ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-naked-air-kanazawa\">{{cite web |author1=Satoshi Kanazawa |title=Naked Air |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/the-scientific-fundamentalist/201001/naked-air |website=Psychology Today |publisher=The Scientific Fundamentalist blog |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=17 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the article titled \"Is Your Professor an Islamophobe?\", at the time Columbia University epidemiologist and HuffPost contributor, [[Abdul El-Sayed]], quoted Kanazawa's articles, along with some other authors', when he discussed the phenomenon of \"a growing number of academics using (their) intellectual identity to promote intolerance and xenophobia against Islam and Muslims\". El-Sayed expressed concern that, as he writes, \"the fundamental messages portrayed in the public musings of academics are no different from the crude ramblings of a [[Glenn Beck]] or a [[Rush Limbaugh]], they are many times more damaging\". He explains how \"PhD's and daunting lists of academic publications to their names, academics are perceived to carry the weighty, objective backing of \u201cknowledge\u201d and \u201cscience\u201d by the lay-public, so bigoted, ignorant opinions on their parts are taken as justification to those who already hold skewed perspectives and hateful opinions about Islam and Muslims\". He points out that \"these academic dogmatists cloak (perhaps under their PhD hoods) the fire of Islamophobia with the cool, measured tones of objectivity\".<ref name=\"El-Sayed-HuffPost-Is-Professor-Islamophobe?\">{{cite web |last1=El-Sayed |first1=Abdulrahman |last2=Professor |first2=ContributorAssistant |last3=University |first3=Columbia |title=Is Your Professor an Islamophobe? |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/phds-promote-xenophobia-a_b_443510 |website=HuffPost |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=4 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Nanjala Nyabola]], writing in [[The Guardian]], dismissed Kanazawa's claims as \"racist nonsense\". She also warned of growing concern over ''Psychology Today's'' position, at the time, regarding issue, also expressed by various academics and numerous public intellectuals,<ref name=\"huffpost.com-kanazawa-does-not-speak-for-us\"/> among them the publication's own authors,<ref name=\"theguardian.com-Nyabola-kanazawa-black-women-psychology-today\"/> such as Mikhail Lyubansky, who criticized the publication, noting that \"extraordinary claims (especially those that hurt and damage marginalized groups) require extraordinary evidence and editorial oversight\".<ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-beauty-eye-beholder-see-what-culture-socializes\">{{cite web |author1=Mikhail Lyubansky Ph.D. |title=Beauty May Be In Eye of Beholder But Eyes See What Culture Socializes |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/between-the-lines/201105/beauty-may-be-in-eye-beholder-eyes-see-what-culture-socializes |website=Psychology Today |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=16 May 2011}}</ref> Similarly, Christopher Ryan criticized Kanazawa's views and writings, calling him the \"[[Rush Limbaugh]] of Evolutionary Psychology\", noting that \"if Rush Limbaugh, [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]], or [[Ann Coulter]] had studied science, they'd be penning articles like some of Kanazawa's.<ref name=\"psychologytoday.comi-kanazawa-is-rush-limbaugh-evolutionary-psychology\">{{cite web |author1=Christopher Ryan Ph.D. |title=Satoshi Kanazawa Is the Rush Limbaugh of Evolutionary Psychology |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/sex-dawn/201105/satoshi-kanazawa-is-the-rush-limbaugh-evolutionary-psychology |website=Psychology Today |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=18 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"psychologytoday.com-evolutionary-psychology-used-car\">{{cite web |author1=Christopher Ryan Ph.D. |title=Is Evolutionary Psychology a Used Car? |url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/intl/blog/sex-dawn/200811/is-evolutionary-psychology-used-car |website=Psychology Today |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=10 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nA shortlist of 10 of Kanazawa's claims is summarized by [[The Independent]] in the article \"Inconvenient truths about our evolution?\"<ref name=\"in-inconvenient-truths-evolution\">{{cite web |title=Inconvenient truths about our evolution? |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/inconvenient-truths-about-our-evolution-2146994.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=30 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Universities and engagements controversies==\nA group of 68 evolutionary psychologists issued an open letter titled \"Kanazawa's bad science does not represent evolutionary psychology\" rejecting his views,<ref name=\"Kanazawa Statement\"/> and an article on the same theme was published by 35 academics in ''American Psychologist''.<ref name=\"huffpost.com-kanazawa-does-not-speak-for-us\"/>\n\n<!-- ===London University controversy=== -->\n*In May 2011 and in the wake of his latest blogging incident, over 120,000 students of the University of London Union Senate subsequently unanimously voted to condemn his research.<ref name=\"guardian.co.uk-lse-academic-triggers-race-row\">{{cite web |last1=Sample |first1=Ian |last2=correspondent |first2=science |title=LSE academic's claim 'black women less attractive' triggers race row |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/may/19/lse-academic-triggers-race-row |website=The Guardian |accessdate=31 May 2019 |date=19 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ===Psychology Today dismissal=== -->\n*In February 2008, he started a blog on ''Psychology Today'' called \"The Scientific Fundamentalist\". In June 2011, the publication dismissed Kanazawa for good in reaction to his ''\"Why Are Black Women Less Physically Attractive Than Other Women?\"'' article.<ref name=\"Fired-For-Black-Women-ugly\">{{cite web |title=Psychologist Fired For \"Why Black Women Are Unattractive\" Study |url=http://newsone.com/nation/casey-gane-mccalla/satoshi-kanazawa-fired-psychology-today/ |website=News One |accessdate=31 May 2019 |language=en |date=6 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ===LSE suspension=== -->\n*In September 2011, [[London School of Economics]] (LSE) suspended Kanazawa from publishing any material in non-[[peer review]]ed journals for a year and he issued an apology stating that the post was \"flawed\".<ref name=\"lse.ac.uk-Kanazawa\">{{cite web |last1=Editor |first1=LSE Web |title=Dr Satoshi Kanazawa - findings of internal review and disciplinary hearing - 09 - 2011 - News archives - News and media - Website archive - Home |url=http://www2.lse.ac.uk/newsAndMedia/news/archives/2011/09/Kanazawa.aspx |website=www.lse.ac.uk |accessdate=31 May 2019 |language=en-gb}}</ref><ref name=\"LSE-web.archive.org-timeshighereducation.co.uk\">{{cite web |title=Times Higher Education - LSE scholar admits race analysis was 'flawed' |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027143911/http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=417449&c=1 |website=web.archive.org |accessdate=31 May 2019 |date=27 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ===Big Think dismissal=== -->\n*In September 2012, after the period of 12 months when he was prohibited from publishing in non-peer-reviewed outlets by the LSE, he was hired by the blog ''[[Big Think]]'' as a contributing editor; the co-operation was discontinued on 29 March 2013.<ref name=\"bigthink.com-bad-science-of-satoshi-kanazawa\"/><ref name=\"bigthink.com-end-of-bold-experiment-kanazawa\">{{cite web|url=http://bigthink.com/the-voice-of-big-think/the-end-of-a-bold-experiment-big-think-and-satoshi-kanazawa|title=The End of a Bold Experiment: Big Think and Satoshi Kanazawa|author=Hopkins, Phillip|publisher=Big Think|date=29 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ===Northwestern University controversy=== -->\n*In December 2018 students at [[Northwestern University]] gathered more than 4,000 signatures on a petition in a few days, asking the university to overturn Kanazawa's approved application to conduct research in Evanston.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com-northwestern-students-want-scholar-out-their-campus\">{{cite web |author1=Colleen Flaherty |title=Northwestern students want a controversial scholar off their campus |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/12/19/northwestern-students-want-controversial-scholar-their-campus |website=www.insidehighered.com |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en |date=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Evolutionary psychology]]\n* [[Gene-centered view of evolution]]\n* [[Tit for tat]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite journal |doi=10.1177/0190272510361602 |title=Why Liberals and Atheists Are More Intelligent |journal=Social Psychology Quarterly |volume=73 |pages=33\u201357 |year=2010 |last1=Kanazawa |first1=S. |citeseerx=10.1.1.395.4490 }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.scienceonreligion.org/index.php/news-research/research-updates/150-is-atheism-linked-to-intelligence <!-- n/a http://ibcsr.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=150:is-atheism-linked-to-intelligence&catid=25:research-news&Itemid=59 --> |title= Is atheism linked to intelligence? |quote= A review of Kanazawa's recent \"Why liberals and atheists are more intelligent\"  |publisher= Science on Religion <!-- Institute for the Bio-Cultural Study of Religion (IBCSR) --> |date= Mar 2010 |first= Derek |last= Michaud }}\n* {{Google Scholar id|Zc33N34AAAAJ}}\n* [http://bigthink.com/satoshikanazawa Profile and videos] at [[Big Think]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kanazawa, Satoshi}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:American academics of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:British people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:British psychologists]]\n[[Category:Critics of multiculturalism]]\n[[Category:Ethnic and racial stereotypes]]\n[[Category:Evolutionary biology]]\n[[Category:Evolutionary psychologists]]\n[[Category:Intelligence researchers]]\n[[Category:Islamophobia in scholarship]]\n[[Category:Race and intelligence controversy]]\n[[Category:Scientific racism]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n", "name_user": "CommonKnowledgeCreator", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSavanna principle:Page numbers correction on Tooby & Cosmides ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satoshi_Kanazawa"}
{"title_page": "Scots College, Wellington", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name        = Scots College\n| seal_image  = Scotscollegecrest123.jpg\n| motto       = ''Virtutem paret doctrina''<br>Let education build all-round character\n| type        = Private, [[Education in New Zealand#Types of schools by years|composite]], day and boarding\n| denomination = Presbyterian\n| established = 1916/1918\n| address     = Monorgan Road,<br>Strathmore,<br>Wellington,<br>New Zealand\n| coordinates = {{coord|-41.3284|174.8191|type:edu_region:NZ-WGN|display=inline,title}}\n| headmaster   = Mr Graeme Yule\n| roll        = {{NZ school roll data|281|y||y}}\n| decile      = 10\n| MOE         = 281\n| gender      = [[Single-sex education|Boys]] (years 1-10), [[co-educational]] (years 11-13)\n| grades      = [[Year One (education)|1]]\u2013[[Year Thirteen|13]]\n| homepage    = [http://www.scotscollege.school.nz Scotscollege.school.nz]\n}}\n\n'''Scots College''' is an [[Independent school|independent]] ([[Private school|private]]) [[Presbyterian]] school which is for boys in years 1 to 10 and from 2020 co-educational in Years 11-13. It is located in the suburb of Strathmore [[Wellington]], New Zealand. Under the leadership of an Executive Headmaster, the College comprises three schools, the Preparatory School for Years 1 to 6, the Middle School for Years 7 to 10 and the Senior School for Years 11 to 13. Each school has its own Principal and Staff. Scots College is an IB World College.\n\n==History==\nIt was founded as a Presbyterian boys' college in 1916 by Rev Dr [[James Gibb (Presbyterian minister)|James Gibb]] and the Hon [[John Aitken (politician)|John Aitken]] on the current campus of [[Queen Margaret College, Wellington|Queen Margaret College]] in Thorndon, and moved to the present site in Strathmore in 1920. Dr Gibb's vision was the creation of a Christian college that would be independent of the secular state system. It is the 'sister' school of Queen Margaret College in Thorndon, Wellington.\n\nThe college's [[Scotland|Scots]] heritage is reflected in its ceremonies (often involving a piper leading a procession into its hall) and school song. College prefects wear kilts on official occasions and every Friday for chapel. The school tartan is that of the [[Clan Fergusson]]. Permission to wear the tartan was granted by the late Governor General Sir [[Sir Charles Fergusson, 7th Baronet|Charles Fergusson]].\n\nThe Main Block has a Category II listing with the [[New Zealand Historic Places Trust]].\n\n==Houses==\n\nStudents in the Middle and Senior Schools (Years 7-13) are organized into eight \"houses\". Each house reflects an important part of the people who have contributed to Scots College over its history. The houses have expanded three times since the founding of the school - two houses were added to the original two in 1961/1963, another two in 1993 with the boarders' house (Gibb) being removed at this time as well, and a further two added in 2009. There are major competitions in swimming, cross-country, music, athletics, and other weekly house sport games, such as hockey and touch rugby. The two original houses were Aitken (Blue, named in honour of founding father [[John Aitken (politician)|Hon John Aitken]]) and Fergusson (Green, named in honour of General [[Sir Charles Fergusson, 7th_Baronet|Sir Charles Fergusson]]), with Glasgow (Red, named in honour of former Headmaster K W R Glasgow) and MacKenzie (Yellow, named in honour of Elsie MacKenzie, Former mistress of the Junios Department of Scots College) being established next, followed by Plimmer (Sky Blue, named in honour of the [[John Plimmer]] and his family, whose four grandchildren were enrolled as boarders in 1916) and Uttley (Black, named in honour of Scots College's first Headmaster Dr George Uttley) in 1993 and Smith (Navy Blue, in honour of Alexander Pringle Smith) and Mawson (Maroon, named in honour of Brigadier John Mawson, a past student and Scots College Old Boys' Association President) established in 2009.\n\nThe Preparatory School (Years 1-6) maintains four houses: Potatau (Blue), Bedding (Green), Macarthur (Red) and McKelvie (Yellow). In 2004 there was an announcement of a change to the current House names in the hopes of giving the Preparatory School a better sense of historical identity; Potatau named after the writer of the School [[haka]], McKelvie named in honour of past parent and Board of Governors member Lynn McKelvie, Bedding names in honour of past student Geoff Bedding and Macarthur named after the first student at Scots College Ian Hannay Macarthur.\n\n==Campus facilities==\nRecent projects on campus have been the science block, opened in 2006 by Nobel Laureate [[Sir Paul Nurse]] and the Aitken (Admin/Reception) block in 2009. Other facilities updated in the last few years include the Leslie Shelly Lecture Theatre and the Information Centre, and an extension to Gibb House, the school's Boarding House. The Hodge Sports Centre (HSC) was opened on 4 November 2011, and the Creative Performing Arts Centre (CPAC) was opened on 2 March 2012.\n\nThe College introduced Flexible Learning environments to its campus during 2017 including a tertiary style 'Hub' offering flexible spaces for teaching, student collaboration and a common room for senior students. Additional new Boarding Houses were opened in 2015 and 2018 to house the growing number of boarding students.\n\nThe school also has [[International Baccalaureate|IB]] World School status and maintains an [[International Baccalaureate|IB]] curriculum from PYP to Diploma. The current IB Diploma co-ordinator is Mike McKnight and the MYP co-ordinator is Kate Bondett.\n\n==Boarding==\n\nThe boarding house (titled Gibb House, after the founder of the school) has accommodation for approximately 130 boys. The majority of these students are in Years 9-13 however allowance has been made occasionally for Year 7 and 8 Boys to board full-time. The current boarding director is Gary Henley-Smith, with assistant house masters Malcolm Bradshaw and Marc Capstick, and matrons Tania Steadman and Blossom Cameron. In addition, gap year tutors are lodged in the boarding house and assist with day-to-day operations.\n\nWhen the College's Senior School changed to co-educational in 2020 girls were also able to board at Scots College.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotscollege.school.nz/senior-school/co-educational-senior-school/|title=Co-educational Senior School|publisher=Scots College|accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Connections with other schools==\nScots College 1st XV is currently playing in the Premier I rugby division. In 2014 the 1st XV won the NZ Secondary School Championship - a joint win with Hamilton Boys High School.  In 2015 they represented New Zealand at the SANIX Rugby Youth Cup tournament in Japan where they placed third.\n\nStudents competing for the 1st XV in traditional fixtures perform a special haka written by an old boy; this is distinct from the school haka.\n\nScots College is the brother school to the slightly younger [[Queen Margaret College (Wellington)|Queen Margaret College]], which now sites itself in the original Scots College building. Often there are various socials and sporting matches against local schools, organised by College Sport Wellington. In addition, both sections of the school have inter-school fixtures with other secondary schools, notably [[Lindisfarne College, New Zealand|Lindisfarne]] and primary schools such as [[Huntley School (New Zealand)|Huntley School]].\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{maincat|People educated at Scots College, Wellington}}\n* [[Steven Adams]] - basketball player for [[Oklahoma City Thunder]]\n* [[Ashley Bloomfield]] - Doctor, Director-General of Health and \"public face\" of 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand (was Head Prefect) \n* Prof [[Geoffrey Duncan Chisholm]] - surgeon<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/obits_alpha/chisholm_geoffrey.pdf|title=Obituary|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|author=J A Strong}}</ref>\n* [[John Clarke (satirist)|John Clarke]] - satirist\n* [[Ralph Francis Alnwick Grey, Baron Grey of Naunton|Lord Grey of Naunton]] - last [[Governor of Northern Ireland]] (also attended [[Wellington College (New Zealand)|Wellington College]])\n* [[Eugenio Pizzuto]] - footballer for [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]]\n* [[Stu Riddle]] - footballer\n* [[Euan Robertson]] 1948-95 (Scots 1959-66) 880yd Steeplechaser. Olympian 1976 Montreal (w. Walker & Quax) 5th place. Represented NZ: 7 World Championships 1969-83, Commonwealth Games 1974, 1978. Manager & coach NZ cross-country and track teams. NZ record-holder  8:21.08\n* [[Sarpreet Singh]] - footballer for [[Bayern Munich II]]\n* [[Victor Vito (Rugby Player)|Victor Vito]] - New Zealand Rugby Sevens international and [[All Black]]\n* [[Rocky Wood]] - author and freelance journalist\n\n== Co-educational ==\nIn January 2018, School Headmaster Graeme Yule announced that Scots College Senior School will become a co-educational school, meaning it will accept both girls and boys to enroll. The change will begin in 2020, when 60 Year 11 to 13 female students will join the Senior School and graduate as the first mixed-sex group from 2021. The integration would expand each year to a total of 150 girls by 2022.<ref>{{cite news |last=Long |first=Jessica |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/100874754/wellingtons-centuryold-boys-college-changes-the-scots-way |title=Wellington's private boys' school Scots College going co-ed in 2020 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=8 September 2010 |accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn November 2007, several graduating students were banned from end-of-year prizes for growing moustaches as part of the fund-raising campaign\n'[[Movember]]', established by The Movember Foundation, to raise awareness for prostate cancer. The college threatened to ban a senior student from their [[National Certificate of Educational Achievement|NCEA]] examinations (official secondary school qualification) for growing a moustache during November.<ref name=\"Dominion\">{{cite news | first = Lane | last = Nichols  | title =  No mo or no show at exams | url = http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/dominionpost/4274452a6000.html | work= [[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] | date=  16 November 2007 | accessdate = 16 November 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, Scots College expelled seven students and suspended five for involvement in a drug ring within the college. Some involved in using and dealing the illegal substances were as young as 13.<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnston |first=Kirsty |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/4107922/Scots-College-students-expelled-for-dealing-drugs |title=Scots College students expelled for dealing drugs |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=8 September 2010 |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, ten Scots College students from Year 11 to 13, including prefects, were caught illegally consuming alcohol on a school trip to Fiji. School Headmaster Graeme Yule recognised the actions as 'relatively minor' and suspended students for less than a week.<ref>{{cite news |author=Jo Moir |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/9314298/College-prefects-stripped-of-badges-after-boozy-trip |title=College prefects stripped of badges |work=Stuff.co.nz |date=23 October 2013 |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Headmaster Graham Yule was accused of making \"sexist\" comments after he said prospective female students would not be allowed to \"sit at the back of the class painting their nails\" once the school becomes co-educational. He also commented on the importance women gave to the size of mirrors while talking about construction of the new girls' bathroom. <ref>{{cite news |author=Jessica Long |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/112227793/scots-college-headmaster-accused-of-making-sexist-remarks-about-female-students |title=Scots College headmaster accused of making 'sexist' remarks about female students\n |work=Stuff.co.nz |date=26 April 2019 |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scotscollege.school.nz/ Official Website]\n\n{{Schools in Wellington}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1916]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in the Wellington Region]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Wellington City]]\n[[Category:Scottish-New Zealand culture]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:NZHPT Category II listings in the Wellington Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name        = Scots College\n| seal_image  = Scotscollegecrest123.jpg\n| motto       = ''Virtutem paret doctrina''<br>Let education build all-round character\n| type        = Private, [[Education in New Zealand#Types of schools by years|composite]], day and boarding\n| denomination = Presbyterian\n| established = 1916/1918\n| address     = Monorgan Road,<br>Strathmore,<br>Wellington,<br>New Zealand\n| coordinates = {{coord|-41.3284|174.8191|type:edu_region:NZ-WGN|display=inline,title}}\n| headmaster   = Mr Graeme Yule\n| roll        = {{NZ school roll data|281|y||y}}\n| decile      = 10\n| MOE         = 281\n| gender      = [[Single-sex education|Boys]] (years 1-10), [[co-educational]] (years 11-13)\n| grades      = [[Year One (education)|1]]\u2013[[Year Thirteen|13]]\n| homepage    = [http://www.scotscollege.school.nz Scotscollege.school.nz]\n}}\n\n'''Scots College''' is an [[Independent school|independent]] ([[Private school|private]]) [[Presbyterian]] school which is for boys in years 1 to 10 and from 2020 co-educational in Years 11-13. It is located in the suburb of Strathmore [[Wellington]], New Zealand. Under the leadership of an Executive Headmaster, the College comprises three schools, the Preparatory School for Years 1 to 6, the Middle School for Years 7 to 10 and the Senior School for Years 11 to 13. Each school has its own Principal and Staff. Scots College is an IB World College.\n\n==History==\nIt was founded as a Presbyterian boys' college in 1916 by Rev Dr [[James Gibb (Presbyterian minister)|James Gibb]] and the Hon [[John Aitken (politician)|John Aitken]] on the current campus of [[Queen Margaret College, Wellington|Queen Margaret College]] in Thorndon, and moved to the present site in Strathmore in 1920. Dr Gibb's vision was the creation of a Christian college that would be independent of the secular state system. It is the 'sister' school of Queen Margaret College in Thorndon, Wellington.\n\nThe college's [[Scotland|Scots]] heritage is reflected in its ceremonies (often involving a piper leading a procession into its hall) and school song. College prefects wear kilts on official occasions and every Friday for chapel. The school tartan is that of the [[Clan Fergusson]]. Permission to wear the tartan was granted by the late Governor General Sir [[Sir Charles Fergusson, 7th Baronet|Charles Fergusson]].\n\nThe Main Block has a Category II listing with the [[New Zealand Historic Places Trust]].\n\n==Houses==\n\nStudents in the Middle and Senior Schools (Years 7-13) are organized into eight \"houses\". Each house reflects an important part of the people who have contributed to Scots College over its history. The houses have expanded three times since the founding of the school - two houses were added to the original two in 1961/1963, another two in 1993 with the boarders' house (Gibb) being removed at this time as well, and a further two added in 2009. There are major competitions in swimming, cross-country, music, athletics, and other weekly house sport games, such as hockey and touch rugby. The two original houses were Aitken (Blue, named in honour of founding father [[John Aitken (politician)|Hon John Aitken]]) and Fergusson (Green, named in honour of General [[Sir Charles Fergusson, 7th_Baronet|Sir Charles Fergusson]]), with Glasgow (Red, named in honour of former Headmaster K W R Glasgow) and MacKenzie (Yellow, named in honour of Elsie MacKenzie, Former mistress of the Junios Department of Scots College) being established next, followed by Plimmer (Sky Blue, named in honour of the [[John Plimmer]] and his family, whose four grandchildren were enrolled as boarders in 1916) and Uttley (Black, named in honour of Scots College's first Headmaster Dr George Uttley) in 1993 and Smith (Navy Blue, in honour of Alexander Pringle Smith) and Mawson (Maroon, named in honour of Brigadier John Mawson, a past student and Scots College Old Boys' Association President) established in 2009.\n\nThe Preparatory School (Years 1-6) maintains four houses: Potatau (Blue), Bedding (Green), Macarthur (Red) and McKelvie (Yellow). In 2004 there was an announcement of a change to the current House names in the hopes of giving the Preparatory School a better sense of historical identity; Potatau named after the writer of the School [[haka]], McKelvie named in honour of past parent and Board of Governors member Lynn McKelvie, Bedding names in honour of past student Geoff Bedding and Macarthur named after the first student at Scots College Ian Hannay Macarthur.\n\n==Campus facilities==\nRecent projects on campus have been the science block, opened in 2006 by Nobel Laureate [[Sir Paul Nurse]] and the Aitken (Admin/Reception) block in 2009. Other facilities updated in the last few years include the Leslie Shelly Lecture Theatre and the Information Centre, and an extension to Gibb House, the school's Boarding House. The Hodge Sports Centre (HSC) was opened on 4 November 2011, and the Creative Performing Arts Centre (CPAC) was opened on 2 March 2012.\n\nThe College introduced Flexible Learning environments to its campus during 2017 including a tertiary style 'Hub' offering flexible spaces for teaching, student collaboration and a common room for senior students. Additional new Boarding Houses were opened in 2015 and 2018 to house the growing number of boarding students.\n\nThe school also has [[International Baccalaureate|IB]] World School status and maintains an [[International Baccalaureate|IB]] curriculum from PYP to Diploma. The current IB Diploma co-ordinator is Mike McKnight and the MYP co-ordinator is Kate Bondett.\n\n==Boarding==\n\nThe boarding house (titled Gibb House, after the founder of the school) has accommodation for approximately 130 boys. The majority of these students are in Years 9-13 however allowance has been made occasionally for Year 7 and 8 Boys to board full-time. The current boarding director is Gary Henley-Smith, with assistant house masters Malcolm Bradshaw and Marc Capstick, and matrons Tania Steadman and Blossom Cameron. In addition, gap year tutors are lodged in the boarding house and assist with day-to-day operations.\n\nWhen the College's Senior School changed to co-educational in 2020 girls were also able to board at Scots College.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotscollege.school.nz/senior-school/co-educational-senior-school/|title=Co-educational Senior School|publisher=Scots College|accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Connections with other schools==\nScots College 1st XV is currently playing in the Premier I rugby division. In 2014 the 1st XV won the NZ Secondary School Championship - a joint win with Hamilton Boys High School.  In 2015 they represented New Zealand at the SANIX Rugby Youth Cup tournament in Japan where they placed third.\n\nStudents competing for the 1st XV in traditional fixtures perform a special haka written by an old boy; this is distinct from the school haka.\n\nScots College is the brother school to the slightly younger [[Queen Margaret College (Wellington)|Queen Margaret College]], which now sites itself in the original Scots College building. Often there are various socials and sporting matches against local schools, organised by College Sport Wellington. In addition, both sections of the school have inter-school fixtures with other secondary schools, notably [[Lindisfarne College, New Zealand|Lindisfarne]] and primary schools such as [[Huntley School (New Zealand)|Huntley School]].\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{maincat|People educated at Scots College, Wellington}}\n* [[Steven Adams]] - basketball player for [[Oklahoma City Thunder]]\n* [[Sarpreet Singh]] - footballer for [[Bayern Munich II]]\n* [[Eugenio Pizzuto]] - footballer for [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]]\n* Prof [[Geoffrey Duncan Chisholm]] - surgeon<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/obits_alpha/chisholm_geoffrey.pdf|title=Obituary|publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh|author=J A Strong}}</ref>\n* [[John Clarke (satirist)|John Clarke]] - satirist\n* [[Ralph Francis Alnwick Grey, Baron Grey of Naunton|Lord Grey of Naunton]] - last [[Governor of Northern Ireland]] (also attended [[Wellington College (New Zealand)|Wellington College]])\n* [[Stu Riddle]] - footballer\n* [[Euan Robertson]] 1948-95 (Scots 1959-66) 880yd Steeplechaser. Olympian 1976 Montreal (w. Walker & Quax) 5th place. Represented NZ: 7 World Championships 1969-83, Commonwealth Games 1974, 1978. Manager & coach NZ cross-country and track teams. NZ record-holder  8:21.08\n* [[Victor Vito (Rugby Player)|Victor Vito]] - New Zealand Rugby Sevens international and [[All Black]]\n* [[Rocky Wood]] - author and freelance journalist\n\n== Co-educational ==\nIn January 2018, School Headmaster Graeme Yule announced that Scots College Senior School will become a co-educational school, meaning it will accept both girls and boys to enroll. The change will begin in 2020, when 60 Year 11 to 13 female students will join the Senior School and graduate as the first mixed-sex group from 2021. The integration would expand each year to a total of 150 girls by 2022.<ref>{{cite news |last=Long |first=Jessica |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/100874754/wellingtons-centuryold-boys-college-changes-the-scots-way |title=Wellington's private boys' school Scots College going co-ed in 2020 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=8 September 2010 |accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn November 2007, several graduating students were banned from end-of-year prizes for growing moustaches as part of the fund-raising campaign\n'[[Movember]]', established by The Movember Foundation, to raise awareness for prostate cancer. The college threatened to ban a senior student from their [[National Certificate of Educational Achievement|NCEA]] examinations (official secondary school qualification) for growing a moustache during November.<ref name=\"Dominion\">{{cite news | first = Lane | last = Nichols  | title =  No mo or no show at exams | url = http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/dominionpost/4274452a6000.html | work= [[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] | date=  16 November 2007 | accessdate = 16 November 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, Scots College expelled seven students and suspended five for involvement in a drug ring within the college. Some involved in using and dealing the illegal substances were as young as 13.<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnston |first=Kirsty |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/4107922/Scots-College-students-expelled-for-dealing-drugs |title=Scots College students expelled for dealing drugs |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=8 September 2010 |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, ten Scots College students from Year 11 to 13, including prefects, were caught illegally consuming alcohol on a school trip to Fiji. School Headmaster Graeme Yule recognised the actions as 'relatively minor' and suspended students for less than a week.<ref>{{cite news |author=Jo Moir |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/9314298/College-prefects-stripped-of-badges-after-boozy-trip |title=College prefects stripped of badges |work=Stuff.co.nz |date=23 October 2013 |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Headmaster Graham Yule was accused of making \"sexist\" comments after he said prospective female students would not be allowed to \"sit at the back of the class painting their nails\" once the school becomes co-educational. He also commented on the importance women gave to the size of mirrors while talking about construction of the new girls' bathroom. <ref>{{cite news |author=Jessica Long |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/112227793/scots-college-headmaster-accused-of-making-sexist-remarks-about-female-students |title=Scots College headmaster accused of making 'sexist' remarks about female students\n |work=Stuff.co.nz |date=26 April 2019 |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scotscollege.school.nz/ Official Website]\n\n{{Schools in Wellington}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1916]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in the Wellington Region]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Wellington City]]\n[[Category:Scottish-New Zealand culture]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:NZHPT Category II listings in the Wellington Region]]\n", "name_user": "Hugo999", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable alumni:add AB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scots_College,_Wellington"}
{"title_page": "Mendefera", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name =  Mendefera<br>\u1218\u1295\u12f0\u1348\u122b<br/>\u0645\u0646\u062f\u064a\u0641\u064a\u0631\u0627\n|settlement_type = Town\n|image_skyline = \n|imagesize = \n|image_caption = \n|image_flag = \n|image_seal = \n|image_map = \n|map_caption = \n|pushpin_map = Eritrea\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize = 250\n|pushpin_map_caption = Location in Eritrea\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1 = [[Regions of Eritrea|Region]]\n|subdivision_name = [[Image:Flag of Eritrea.svg|25px]] [[Eritrea]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Debub]]\n|subdivision_type2 = [[Districts of Eritrea|District]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Mendefera District|Mendefera]]\n|established_title = \n|established_date =\n|government_type = \n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_sq_mi =\n|area_total_km2 = \n|area_land_sq_mi =\n|area_land_km2 = \n|area_urban_sq_mi = \n|area_urban_km2 = \n|area_metro_km2 = \n|area_metro_sq_mi = \n|population_as_of=2012\n|population_footnotes =\n|population_total = 25332\n|population_urban = \n|population_metro = 64000\n|population_density_sq_mi = \n|population_density_km2 =auto\n|timezone = \n|utc_offset = \n|timezone_DST =\n|utc_offset_DST = \n|coordinates = {{coord|14|53|14|N|38|48|55|E|region:ER|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes=\n|elevation_m = 1972\n|elevation_ft = \n|postal_code_type = \n|postal_code = \n|area_code =\n|blank_name = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|blank_info = [[Semi-arid climate#Hot semi-arid climates|BSh]]  \n|website = \n}}\n\n[[Mendefera]]({{lang-ti|\u1218\u1295\u12f0\u1348\u122b}}), formerly '''Adi Ugri''', is the capital city of the [[Debub Region]] of [[Eritrea]]. The town's name derives from the high hill in the center of the city, and is a source of pride to Eritreans. It means 'no one dared' and is a reminder of the local anti-colonial movement.\n\n==History==\nMendefera/Adi-ugri is an ancient town of the D'mt kingdom which was established as early as the fifth (5th) century BCE. It evolved into an important city in the [[Aksumite]] civilisation. Numerous buildings have been excavated since 1959, with both [[cross]]es and local and [[Roman coin]]s found. Many areas, including [[tomb]]s, have yet to be explored.\n\nThe town is now bustling market town in a fertile region of Eritrea. It is a place where small and large scale factories produce different products.\n\n[[Mendefera]] is famous for its anticolonial movment during The Ethiopian Emperor Haileslase and is a great fighter contributor of the [[Eritrean]] [[Libration]] [[front]](ELF) as it is home to one of the old schools in Eritrea ,[[San]] [[Gorgo]]. In 2001,the beautiful town of Mendefera, birthed and homed a beautiful princess called S Elsa. As time went, Princess Elsa travelled to place far from home called Sudani, where she lived for many months and experienced the horrible and wonderful things about the culture in that country. As time went, she wanted to see other place, so she flew to the west, where she was met by...\n\n==Location==\nSome villages in the vicinity of Mendefera include  Adi-Bari([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1263\u122a]]),Zban ona([[\u12dd\u1263\u1295\u12d1\u1293]]),Adi-wegri([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u12c8\u130d\u122a]]),Berak([[\u1260\u122b\u12bd]]),Adi-Gahad([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u130b\u1205\u12f5]]),Dandere genet([[\u12f3\u1295\u12f4\u1228 \u1308\u1290\u1275]]),Adi-Zarna([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u12db\u122d\u1293]]),Adi-Blay([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1265\u120b\u12ed]]),Adi-Hare([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1213\u1228]]),Enda amanuel([[\u12a0\u1295\u12f3 \u12a3\u121b\u1291\u12a4\u120d]]),Mai Noh([[\u121b\u12ed\u1296\u1205]]),Embezarb([[\u12a5\u121d\u1260\u12db\u122d\u1265]]),kudofelasi([[\u12a9\u12f6\u1348\u120b\u1232]]),[[Adi-Ada]]([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u12d3\u12f3]]),Deranto([[\u12f0\u122d\u12d3\u1295\u1276]]),Adi Bana ([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1263\u1293]]),Adi Garma([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u130b\u122d\u121b]]),Adekemene([[\u12d3\u12f0\u1240\u1218\u1290]]),May Lbus([[\u121b\u12ed\u120d\u1261\u1235]]),Adi Groto([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1309\u1228\u1276]]) ,Kloawlia([[\u12ad\u1208\u12c9\u120a\u12d5]]),Ginebale([[\u130a\u1290\u1263\u1208]]),Adekeseyemti([[\u12d3\u12f0\u1240\u1230\u12e8\u121d\u1272]]),Kefta([[\u12a8\u134d\u1273]]),Adewehaza([[\u12d3\u12f0\u12c9\u1213\u12db]]),Egri mekel([[\u12a5\u130d\u122a\u1218\u12b8\u120d]]),....\n\n==Climate==\nMendefera has a borderline [[hot semi-arid climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''BSh'') that borders both on a [[semi-arid climate#Cold semi-arid climates|cool semi-arid climate]] (''BSk'') and a [[subtropical highland climate]] (''Cwb''). Except during the humid wet season of July and August when heavy cloud cover depresses temperatures by around {{convert|5|C-change|F-change|disp=or}}, daytime temperatures are very warm to hot; however, the thin, dry air means that mornings are pleasantly cool throughout the year.\n{{Weather box|location = Mendefera \n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|temperature colour = pastel\n|Jan high C = 27.8\n|Feb high C = 28.5\n|Mar high C = 30.0\n|Apr high C = 30.0\n|May high C = 29.5\n|Jun high C = 28.2\n|Jul high C = 23.3\n|Aug high C = 22.6\n|Sep high C = 27.5\n|Oct high C = 27.5\n|Nov high C = 26.6\n|Dec high C = 26.6\n|Jan low C = 8.0\n|Feb low C = 9.2\n|Mar low C = 11.1\n|Apr low C = 12.0\n|May low C = 12.7\n|Jun low C = 12.6\n|Jul low C = 11.7\n|Aug low C = 12.3\n|Sep low C = 12.2\n|Oct low C = 9.7\n|Nov low C = 8.6\n|Dec low C = 8.1\n|rain colour = green\n|Jan rain mm = 0\n|Feb rain mm = 4\n|Mar rain mm = 12\n|Apr rain mm = 28\n|May rain mm = 41\n|Jun rain mm = 57\n|Jul rain mm = 190\n|Aug rain mm = 189\n|Sep rain mm = 50\n|Oct rain mm = 11\n|Nov rain mm = 16\n|Dec rain mm = 4\n|source 1 = Climate-Data<ref name=\"climate\">{{cite web |url=http://en.climate-data.org/location/31383/ |title=Climate-Data : Eritrea |url-status=live |accessdate=11 July 2013}}</ref>\n|date=July 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mendefera District]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.geographic.org/geographic_names/name.php?uni=-871472&fid=1679&c=eritrea Mendefera]\n\n  2[[^]] [[Genealogy]],   [[Eritrea]].\"List of Eritrean Villages\". https://emnetu.com/Publications/Older_publications/Er\n\n{{Coord|14|53|N|38|49|E|region:ER_type:city|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Aksumite cities]]\n[[Category:Southern Region (Eritrea)]]\n[[Category:Regional capitals in Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Eritrea]]\n\n\n{{Eritrea-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name =  Mendefera<br>\u1218\u1295\u12f0\u1348\u122b<br/>\u0645\u0646\u062f\u064a\u0641\u064a\u0631\u0627\n|settlement_type = Town\n|image_skyline = \n|imagesize = \n|image_caption = \n|image_flag = \n|image_seal = \n|image_map = \n|map_caption = \n|pushpin_map = Eritrea\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize = 250\n|pushpin_map_caption = Location in Eritrea\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1 = [[Regions of Eritrea|Region]]\n|subdivision_name = [[Image:Flag of Eritrea.svg|25px]] [[Eritrea]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Debub]]\n|subdivision_type2 = [[Districts of Eritrea|District]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Mendefera District|Mendefera]]\n|established_title = \n|established_date =\n|government_type = \n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_sq_mi =\n|area_total_km2 = \n|area_land_sq_mi =\n|area_land_km2 = \n|area_urban_sq_mi = \n|area_urban_km2 = \n|area_metro_km2 = \n|area_metro_sq_mi = \n|population_as_of=2012\n|population_footnotes =\n|population_total = 25332\n|population_urban = \n|population_metro = 64000\n|population_density_sq_mi = \n|population_density_km2 =auto\n|timezone = \n|utc_offset = \n|timezone_DST =\n|utc_offset_DST = \n|coordinates = {{coord|14|53|14|N|38|48|55|E|region:ER|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes=\n|elevation_m = 1972\n|elevation_ft = \n|postal_code_type = \n|postal_code = \n|area_code =\n|blank_name = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|blank_info = [[Semi-arid climate#Hot semi-arid climates|BSh]]  \n|website = \n}}\n\n[[Mendefera]]({{lang-ti|\u1218\u1295\u12f0\u1348\u122b}}), formerly '''Adi Ugri''', is the capital city of the [[Debub Region]] of [[Eritrea]]. The town's name derives from the high hill in the center of the city, and is a source of pride to Eritreans. It means 'no one dared' and is a reminder of the local anti-colonial movement.\n\n==History==\nMendefera/Adi-ugri is an ancient town of the D'mt kingdom which was established as early as the fifth (5th) century BCE. It evolved into an important city in the [[Aksumite]] civilisation. Numerous buildings have been excavated since 1959, with both [[cross]]es and local and [[Roman coin]]s found. Many areas, including [[tomb]]s, have yet to be explored.\n\nThe town is now bustling market town in a fertile region of Eritrea. It is a place where small and large scale factories produce different products.\n\n[[Mendefera]] is famous for its anticolonial movment during The Ethiopian Emperor Haileslase and is a great fighter contributor of the [[Eritrean]] [[Libration]] [[front]](ELF) as it is home to one of the old schools in Eritrea ,[[San]] [[Gorgo]]. In 2001,the beautiful town of Mendefera, birthed and homed a beautiful princess called S Elsa. As time went, Princess Elsa travelled to place far from home called Sudani, where she lived for many months and experienced the horrible and wonderful things about the culture in that country. As time went, she wanted to see other place, so she flew to the west, where she was met by...\n\n==Location==\nSome villages in the vicinity of Mendefera include  Adi-Bari([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1263\u122a]]),Zban ona([[\u12dd\u1263\u1295\u12d1\u1293]]),Adi-wegri([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u12c8\u130d\u122a]]),Berak([[\u1260\u122b\u12bd]]),Adi-Gahad([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u130b\u1205\u12f5]]),Dandere genet([[\u12f3\u1295\u12f4\u1228 \u1308\u1290\u1275]]),Adi-Zarna([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u12db\u122d\u1293]]),Adi-Blay([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1265\u120b\u12ed]]),Adi-Hare([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1213\u1228]]),Enda amanuel([[\u12a0\u1295\u12f3 \u12a3\u121b\u1291\u12a4\u120d]]),Mai Noh([[\u121b\u12ed\u1296\u1205]]),Embezarb([[\u12a5\u121d\u1260\u12db\u122d\u1265]]),kudofelasi([[\u12a9\u12f6\u1348\u120b\u1232]]),[[Adi-Ada]]([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u12d3\u12f3]]),Deranto([[\u12f0\u122d\u12d3\u1295\u1276]]),Adi Bana ([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1263\u1293]]),Adi Garma([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u130b\u122d\u121b]]),Adekemene([[\u12d3\u12f0\u1240\u1218\u1290]]),May Lbus([[\u121b\u12ed\u120d\u1261\u1235]]),Adi Groto([[\u12d3\u12f2 \u1309\u1228\u1276]]) ,Kloawlia([[\u12ad\u1208\u12c9\u120a\u12d5]]),Ginebale([[\u130a\u1290\u1263\u1208]]),Adekeseyemti([[\u12d3\u12f0\u1240\u1230\u12e8\u121d\u1272]]),Kefta([[\u12a8\u134d\u1273]]),Adewehaza([[\u12d3\u12f0\u12c9\u1213\u12db]]),Egri mekel([[\u12a5\u130d\u122a\u1218\u12b8\u120d]]),....\n\n==Climate==\nMendefera has a borderline [[hot semi-arid climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''BSh'') that borders both on a [[semi-arid climate#Cold semi-arid climates|cool semi-arid climate]] (''BSk'') and a [[subtropical highland climate]] (''Cwb''). Except during the humid wet season of July and August when heavy cloud cover depresses temperatures by around {{convert|5|C-change|F-change|disp=or}}, daytime temperatures are very warm to hot; however, the thin, dry air means that mornings are pleasantly cool throughout the year.\n{{Weather box|location = Mendefera \n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|temperature colour = pastel\n|Jan high C = 27.8\n|Feb high C = 28.5\n|Mar high C = 30.0\n|Apr high C = 30.0\n|May high C = 29.5\n|Jun high C = 28.2\n|Jul high C = 23.3\n|Aug high C = 22.6\n|Sep high C = 27.5\n|Oct high C = 27.5\n|Nov high C = 26.6\n|Dec high C = 26.6\n|Jan low C = 8.0\n|Feb low C = 9.2\n|Mar low C = 11.1\n|Apr low C = 12.0\n|May low C = 12.7\n|Jun low C = 12.6\n|Jul low C = 11.7\n|Aug low C = 12.3\n|Sep low C = 12.2\n|Oct low C = 9.7\n|Nov low C = 8.6\n|Dec low C = 8.1\n|rain colour = green\n|Jan rain mm = 0\n|Feb rain mm = 4\n|Mar rain mm = 12\n|Apr rain mm = 28\n|May rain mm = 41\n|Jun rain mm = 57\n|Jul rain mm = 190\n|Aug rain mm = 189\n|Sep rain mm = 50\n|Oct rain mm = 11\n|Nov rain mm = 16\n|Dec rain mm = 4\n|source 1 = Climate-Data<ref name=\"climate\">{{cite web |url=http://en.climate-data.org/location/31383/ |title=Climate-Data : Eritrea |url-status=live |accessdate=11 July 2013}}</ref>\n|date=July 2013}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mendefera District]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.geographic.org/geographic_names/name.php?uni=-871472&fid=1679&c=eritrea Mendefera]\n\n  2[[^]] [[Geneology]],   [[Eritrea]].\"List of Eritrean Villages\". https://emnetu.com/Publications/Older_publications/Er\n\n{{Coord|14|53|N|38|49|E|region:ER_type:city|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Aksumite cities]]\n[[Category:Southern Region (Eritrea)]]\n[[Category:Regional capitals in Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Eritrea]]\n\n\n{{Eritrea-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mendefera"}
{"title_page": "Believe It (PartyNextDoor and Rihanna song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Believe It\n| cover      = PartyNextDoor and Rihanna - Believe It.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[PartyNextDoor]] and [[Rihanna]]\n| album      = [[Partymobile]]\n| released   = {{start date|2020|03|27|mf=y}}\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"HS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/rihanna-partynextdoor-song-stream-reactions/|title=Rihanna & PARTYNEXTDOOR Just Dropped \"Believe It\" & Fans Are Going Wild|website=[[Highsnobiety]]|last=Tesema|first=Feleg|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=3}}\n| label      =\n* [[OVO Sound]]\n* [[Warner Records|Warner]]\n| writer     =\n* [[PartyNextDoor|Jahron Brathwaite]]\n* [[Robyn Fenty]]\n* Andre Robertson\n* [[Cardiak|Carl McCormick]]\n* Eric Dugar\n| producer   =\n* Bizness Boi\n* [[Cardiak]]\n* Ninetyfour\n| chronology = [[PartyNextDoor]]\n| prev_title = Split Decision\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Rihanna]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Lemon (N.E.R.D and Rihanna song)|Lemon]]\n | prev_year  = 2017\n | title      = Believe It\n | year       = 2020\n | next_title =\n | next_year  =\n}} \n}}\n\"'''Believe It'''\" is a song by Canadian singer [[PartyNextDoor]] and Barbadian singer [[Rihanna]]. It was released as the fourth single from PartyNextDoor's third studio album ''[[Partymobile]]'' on March 27, 2020, and was produced by Bizness Boi, [[Cardiak]] and Ninetyfour. The song marks Rihanna's first appearance on a single in three years, following [[N.E.R.D.]]'s \"[[Lemon (N.E.R.D and Rihanna song)|Lemon]]\" (2017).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/rihanna-partynextdoor-new-song-believe-it-listen-1203547056/|title=Listen to PartyNextDoor's Rihanna-Featuring New Song 'Believe It'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=''Variety'' staff|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The song debuted at number 12 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and at number 23 on the [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'']] [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9352114/the-weeknd-blinding-lights-number-one-second-week-hot-100|title=The Weeknd No. 1 on Hot 100 for Second Week|date=2020-04-06|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nPartyNextDoor has previously co-written several songs with Rihanna, including \"[[Work (Rihanna song)|Work]]\", \"[[Sex with Me]]\" and \"[[Wild Thoughts]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/rihanna-and-partynextdoor-share-new-song-believe-it-listen/|title=Rihanna and PARTYNEXTDOOR Share New Song \"BELIEVE IT\": Listen|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Pierre|first=Alphonse|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Writing and recording==\nAmerican record producer [[Cardiak]] created the instrumental of the song, which features \"intertwining guitar and [a] pitched-up vocal sample\". He then sent it to Bizness Boi, who was at a writing camp in [[Paris]]; despite working on the track with an unnamed artist, he passed it on to Ninetyfour, who fleshed the song out and sent it to PartyNextDoor upon the advice of a friend. PartyNextDoor put placeholder vocals from his girlfriend on the track while waiting to hear back from Rihanna. Rihanna finished her vocals in the week of the album's release. Bizness Boi and Ninetyfour did not hear Rihanna's finished vocals on the track until the album's release on March 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/partynextdoor-rihanna-believe-it-making-of-972815/|title=How Rihanna Ended Up on PartyNextDoor's 'Believe It'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics and composition==\n\"Believe It\" is a \"sensual\" [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] \"slow burner\" about a relationship, with PartyNextDoor and Rihanna singing to each other as lovers \"imploring each other to believe in the power of their connection\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/9344596/rihanna-partynextdoor-believe-it|title=Rihanna Jumps Back to Music With Partynextdoor on Grooving 'Believe It'|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nJessica McKinney of ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' included the song among their list of Best New Music of the week, calling it a \"breezy R&B record\" and noting how Rihanna takes a backseat to Party, \"only offering raspy vocals on the chorus\", singing, \"Best make me believe it/Believe you won't deceive me\".<ref name=\"ComplexBest\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/best-new-music-this-week-partynextdoor-rihanna-future|title=Best New Music This Week: PARTYNEXTDOOR, Fivio Foreign, Murda Beatz, and More|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=McKinney|first=Jessica|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| 28\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|51|artist=PartyNextDoor & Rihanna|song=Believe It|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|27|artist=PartyNextDoor & Rihanna|song=Believe It|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single 