ght-speed tiptronic transmission.\n\n==== Production ====\n2013\u20132014 Audi A8 and S8 vehicles equipped with a standard sunroof, manufactured between March 12, 2013 and July 15, 2013 were recalled due to possible shattering of sunroof glass panel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2013/10/29/audi-a8-s8-recall-sunroof-issue/|title=Audi also calling in A8, S8 over sunroof issue|author=Noah Joseph|work=Autoblog|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Marketing ====\nAs part of the 2013 S8 4.0 TFSI quattro launch in the US, a TV commercial called 'Suspect' was produced in association with Venables Bell & Partners, USA, Furlined, The Whitehouse, 740 Sound Design & Mix, Lime Studios;<ref>{{cite web|url= http://adsoftheworld.com/media/tv/audi_s8_suspect|title=Audi S8: Suspect|accessdate=14 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150715030603/http://adsoftheworld.com/media/tv/audi_s8_suspect|archivedate=15 July 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> starring Abigail Spencer.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://whoisthathotadgirl.tumblr.com/post/30998637977/q-who-is-the-hot-girl-in-the-audi-s8-suspect|title=Q: Who is the hot girl in the Audi S8 \"Suspect\"...|publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2015 }}</ref> The ad takes cues from quintessential heist films with the S8 taking center stage against a mysterious and suspenseful bank robbery scene. As the thrill escalates, viewers will be left deciding whether a true robbery has transpired, or if the scene was purely a figment of the driver's imagination. With the power, speed and innovation of the S8 at the driver's fingertips, it's easy to get carried away behind the wheel of an Audi S model. The spot closes with the tagline \"Heighten Every Moment.\" The commercial was premiered during the 2012 NFL season kick-off game on 5 September 2012. The \"Suspect\" commercial featuring the Audi S8 also aired on [[CBS]] and [[NBC]], and select cable networks, including: [[The Food Network|Food]], [[FX Network|FX]], [[National Geographic]], [[ESPN]], [[USA Network|USA]], [[CNN]], and [[AMC Network|AMC]]. A 30-second version would also be viewable on CNN.com, Reuters.com, Wired.com, Yahoo! and more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2012/09/05/s8-ad-to-air-in-nfl-kickoff-game-tonight-as-audi-recommits-to-su/|title=S8 ad to air in NFL kickoff game tonight as Audi recommits to Super Bowl|author=Zach Bowman|work=Autoblog|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.audiusanews.com/newsrelease.do?&id=3120&mid=1 Audi Kicks Off NFL Season with First-Ever Campaign for S Models]</ref>\n\n=== 2014 model year facelift ===\n{{Multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width =\n| image1 = Audi A8 3.0 TDI Facelift.jpg\n| image2 = Audi A8 3.0 TDI Facelift Heck.jpg\n| caption2 = MY14 facelift Audi A8 (Europe)\n| image3 = 2015 Audi A8L quattro rear 5.20.18.jpg\n| caption3 = MY14 Audi A8 L (US)\n| image4 = Audi A8 2013 (11209948916).jpg\n| caption4 = Interior\n}}\n\n==== A8, S8, A8 Audi exclusive concept, A8 hybrid (2013\u2013) ====\nChanges include:<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2013/08/21/audi_a8.html |title= Composure redefined \u2013 the Audi A8 |accessdate= 2014-12-29 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141229152405/https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2013/08/21/audi_a8.html |archivedate= 2014-12-29 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Multi Media Interface]] with faster [[Tegra 3]]-Processor and [[LTE (telecommunication)|Long Term Evolution]] broadband Internet.\n* First worldwide series production car with digitally controlled, full-LED glare-free adaptive [[highbeam]]: [[Matrix LED]].<ref>http://www.audi.com/com/brand/en/vorsprung_durch_technik/content/2013/10/audi-a8-in-a-new-radiant-light.html Audi Matrix LED Headlights</ref> The high-beam comprises 25 individual light-emitting diodes per unit that can be switched on and off or dimmed individually depending on the situation. This enables the headlight system to react extremely precisely to other vehicles while always brightly illuminating the road. Additional features of the new headlights are the intelligent cornering light, new-look daytime running lights and dynamic turn signals. The lighting system in the A8 uses predictive route data from the navigation system to adjust the distribution of light in response to the current driving situation. In combination with the optional Navigation plus with MMI touch, the system recognizes route data contained in the navigation system, such as curves and road classifications.\n* Cornering light: Using predictive route data supplied by the MMI navigation plus, the focus of the Matrix LED beam is shifted towards the bend even before the driver turns the steering wheel.<ref name=\"audi.com\">[http://www.audi.com/com/brand/en/vorsprung_durch_technik/content/2013/10/audi-a8-in-a-new-radiant-light.html Audi Matrix LED]</ref>\n* Night Vision Assistant can now recognize larger [[animal]]s in addition to [[pedestrian]]s. Pedestrian Marker Lights work together with the optional night vision assistant. As soon as a pedestrian is detected in a critical range in front of the vehicle, individual LEDs flash briefly three times in succession to alert that person, who is then clearly visible to the driver<ref name=\"audi.com\"/>\n* [[Automotive head-up display|Head-up display]]\n* Standard electromechanical power steering (optional dynamic steering varies its ratio with the car's speed)\n* [[Active lane assist]], which makes slight steering adjustments when necessary\n* [[Park assist]] system with 360\u00b0 display,\n* [[Side assist]] [[blind spot monitor]] coupled with expanded version of the standard pre sense basic safety system\n* [[Active noise cancellation]] (ANC) for A8 L W12 quattro, cylinder on demand with six-cylinder mode.\n* Additional [[noise damping]]\n* Other changes: altered trunk layout with optional power trunk closing assist, flatter rear LED lights joined together by a continuous chrome strip, redesigned bumper houses two rhomboid tailpipes (except S8), available wheel sizes up to 21 inches with 275/35-series tires, optional sport differential (standard on S8 and A8 4.2 TDI clean diesel quattro)\n\nThe A8 Audi Exclusive Concept is a limited (50 units) version of the A8 L W12 quattro with interior leather upholstery from Italian furniture manufacturer Poltrona Frau in the color Agatha cognac, inlays are made of fine grain olive ash natural silver brown, Tierra Del Fuego body colour. Production was set to begin at the quattro GmbH facility in Neckarsulm starting in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2013/11/14/a8_audi_exclusive.html |title= The A8 Audi exclusive concept |work= Audi MediaCenter |accessdate= 14 July 2015 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131207153941/https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2013/11/14/a8_audi_exclusive.html |archivedate= 7 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe Audi S8 includes a four-cylinder mode with ANC, two elliptical dual tailpipes, dynamic steering, sport differential, adaptive air suspension sport with an S-specific setup, 20-inch wheels, S8 emblems on front brake calipers, optional Audi design selection black/Vermont brown with Carbon twill copper inlays.\n\nThe Audi A8 hybrid includes a custom Audi luggage set for the trunk.\n\nThe vehicles were unveiled at the 2013 Frankfurt Motor Show, followed by the 2014 Detroit Auto Show<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1089657_2015-audi-a8-and-s8-u-s-specs-announced |title= 2015 Audi A8 And S8 U.S. Specs Announced |author= Viknesh Vijayenthiran |work= Motor Authority |accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> and the 2014 Toronto Auto Show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ca.autoblog.com/2014/02/15/toronto-auto-show-2014-audi-s8-canada-msrp-specs-debut/|title=Autoblog - We Obsessively Cover the Auto Industry|author=Greg Migliore|work=Autoblog|accessdate=14 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150125080757/http://ca.autoblog.com/2014/02/15/toronto-auto-show-2014-audi-s8-canada-msrp-specs-debut/ |archivedate=25 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\nGerman models arrived at German Audi dealerships in November 2013. Early A8 models include 3.0 TFSI quattro (310PS), 4.0 TFSI quattro (435PS), 3.0 TDI quattro clean diesel (258PS), 4.2 TDI clean diesel quattro (385PS), A8 L W12 quattro (500PS), A8 hybrid 2.0 TFSI (211/245PS), S8 4.0 TFSI quattro (520PS).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2013/09/10/audi_a8.html|title=More composed than ever \u2013 the new Audi A8|work=Audi MediaCenter|accessdate=14 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305194842/https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2013/09/10/audi_a8.html|archivedate=5 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2013/09/10/2015-audi-a8-s8-frankfurt-2013/|title=2015 Audi A8 rises to meet the challenge [w/video]|author=John Neff|work=Autoblog|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nUS models went on sale as 2015 model year vehicles. Early models included A8 3.0 (L) TFSI quattro (310PS), A8 (L) 4.0 TFSI quattro (435PS), A8 L 3.0 TDI quattro clean diesel (258PS), A8 L W12 quattro (500PS), S8 4.0 TFSI quattro (520PS).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2014/06/04/2015-audi-a8-starts-77400/|title=Refreshed 2015 Audi A8 starts at $77,400*|author=Chris Bruce|work=Autoblog|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nEngines are the same in Canada as the US but PS ratings are higher due to less emission control devices needed.\n\n==== A8 L Security (2014\u2013) ====\nAvailable in V8 4.0 TFSI or W12 FSI engines, the A8 L Security is an armoured version of the A8 L with VR9 ballistic protection standard in accordance with the BRV 2009 guideline, with VR 10 in certain areas, and explosives resistance tested in accordance with the ERV 2010 guideline (Explosion Resistant Vehicles). The occupant cell is made of heat-formed armor steel, aramid fabric, ceramic, a special aluminum alloy, and multi-laminated glass, with protective materials overlap at transitions. The aluminum side sills incorporate ballistic-proof profiles. The armor-plated vehicle floor made from a special aluminum alloy for explosive weapons resistance. Door windows, windshield and rear window incorporate special glass with a splinter-inhibiting polycarbonate layer on the inside, with doorstop function and optional electromechanical side windows. Other optional security equipment include emergency exit system with pyrotechnic fracture bolts in the hinges detach the door from the body, fire extinguisher system with two tanks and nozzles spray to wheel arches, onto the underbody and tank, and into the engine compartment; emergency fresh-air system with two pressurized cartridges housed in the protected zone, security start with remote radio signal engine start, selective unlocking of doors, a smoke extractor for the interior, an LED signal system for convoy driving, pennant holder, flashing lights, a siren, a preparation for or installation of analog and digital radio networks for security authorities and organizations, a built-in phone, an accident data recorder, an additional rear camera, a heated windshield including partly heated side windows. Other features included LED (V8 4.0 TFSI) or Matrix LED (W12 FSI) headlights, quattro permanent all-wheel drive, armor-plated (ceramic doors, aluminum frame) communications box in the trunk with a supplementary battery, optional battery and fuel tank protection, intercom system with a loudspeaker in the Singleframe grille and microphones for the interior and the vehicle's surroundings, two electrically adjustable individual seats in the rear, front comfort seats with optional with massage and ventilation functions (optional front-passenger relaxation seat with electric-control footrest, ventilation and massage function), optional continuous center console with large storage compartments is also available, rear seat entertainment with two 10.2-inch displays, optional folding table, a cool box and auxiliary heating; new Unicum leather interior upholstery, forged 19-inch wheels, 255/70 tires with high load index 117, polymer rings on the rims, direct-measurement tire pressure monitoring system, optional spare wheel, 4-zone automatic air conditioning with an ionizer, electric rear blinds, Bose surround sound system, a TV tuner, parking system plus with surround view camera.\n\nDeliveries began in the third quarter of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2014/01/14/the_new_audi_a8_l.html|title=The new Audi A8 L Security \u2013 Supreme protection for passengers|work=Audi MediaCenter|accessdate=14 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714183457/https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2014/01/14/the_new_audi_a8_l.html|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2014/01/14/2015-audi-a8-l-security-official/|title=Audi reveals new beefed-up A8 L Security|author=Noah Joseph|work=Autoblog|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====S8 plus (2015\u2013)====\nBased on the short wheel base S8, the S8 plus includes increased engine power to {{convert|605|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|700|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} of torque, with overboost to {{convert|750|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} of torque, as well as unique 21-inch wheels with 275/35R21 tires in Germany\n\nThe vehicle was unveiled at the 2015 [[Los Angeles Auto Show]].<ref>[https://www.autoblog.com/2015/11/11/audi-s8-plus-us-la-confirmed/ Audi confirms S8 Plus for US to debut in LA]</ref>\n\nGerman model went on sale in end of November 2015 for a base price of 145,200 euros.<ref>[https://www.autoblog.com/2015/08/05/audi-s8-plus-official/ Audi S8 Plus packs 605 horsepower]</ref>\n\nUS model went on sale in December 2015 as 2016 model year vehicle for $114,900 USD.<ref>[https://www.autoblog.com/2015/11/12/audi-s8-plus-rs7-performance-pricing-official/ Audi prices S8 Plus at $115k, RS7 Performance at $129k]</ref>\n\n====Engines<ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/audi-s8-55 Audi S8 (2013)]</ref><ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/the-pinnacle-of-sportiness-the-audi-s8-plus-5024 The pinnacle of sportiness \u2013 the Audi S8 plus]</ref>====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" style=\"font-size:98%;\"\n|+Petrol engines\n!Model!!Years!!Type!!Power, torque at rpm\n|-\n|rowspan=3|A8 (L) 2.0 TFSI hybrid||rowspan=3| 2013\u2013||{{convert|1984|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} I4 turbo|| {{convert|211|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 4,300\u20136,000, {{convert|350|Nm|2|abbr=on}} at 1,500\u20134,200\n|-\n|electric motor, 1.3&nbsp;kWh lithium-ion battery||{{convert|54|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at TBC, {{convert|210|Nm|2|abbr=on}} at TBC\n|-\n|combined||{{convert|245|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at TBC, {{convert|480|Nm|2|abbr=on}} at TBC\n|-\n|A8 (L) 3.0 TFSI quattro (310PS)||2013\u2013||{{convert|2995|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V6 supercharged|| {{convert|310|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,200\u20136,500, {{convert|440|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|0|abbr=on}} at 2,900\u20134,750\n|-\n|A8 (L) 4.0 TFSI quattro||2013\u2013||{{convert|3993|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V8 twin turbo (VW [[EA 825]])<ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/techday-on-combustion-engine-technology-8738/efficiency-and-driving-pleasure-innovative-v-engines-at-audi-8748 Efficiency and driving pleasure: innovative V engines at Audi]</ref>|| {{convert|435|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,100\u20136,000, {{convert|600|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|0|abbr=on}} at 1,500\u20135,000\n|-\n|A8 L W12 6.3 FSI quattro||2013\u2013||{{convert|6299|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} [[W12 engine|W12]] || {{convert|500|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,200, {{convert|625|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|0|abbr=on}} at 4,750\n|-\n|A8 L Security 4.0 TFSI quattro||2014\u2013||{{convert|3993|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V8 twin turbo (VW [[EA 825]])|| {{convert|435|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,100\u20136,000, {{convert|600|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|0|abbr=on}} at 1,500\u20135,000\n|-\n|A8 L Security W12 6.3 FSI quattro||2014\u2013||{{convert|6299|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} [[W12 engine|W12]] || {{convert|500|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,200, {{convert|625|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|0|abbr=on}} at 4,750\n|-\n|S8 4.0 TFSI quattro||2015\u2013||{{convert|3993|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V8 twin turbo (VW [[EA 825]])|| {{convert|520|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,800, {{convert|650|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|2|abbr=on}} at 1,700\u20135,500\n|-\n|S8 plus 4.0 TFSI quattro||2015\u2013||{{convert|3992|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V8 twin turbo (VW [[EA 825]])|| {{convert|605|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,100-6,800, {{convert|700|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} at 1,700\u20136,000<br>Overboost: {{convert|750|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}}\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" style=\"font-size:98%;\"\n|+Diesel engines\n!Model!!Years!!Type!!Power, torque at rpm\n|-\n|A8 (L) 3.0 TDI clean diesel quattro (258PS)||2013\u2013||{{convert|2967|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V6 turbo || {{convert|258|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 4,000\u20134250, {{convert|580|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|0|abbr=on}} at 1,750\u20132,500\n|-\n|A8 (L) 4.2 TDI clean diesel quattro (385PS)||2013\u2013||{{convert|4134|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V8 turbo || {{convert|385|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 3,750, {{convert|850|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|0|abbr=on}} at 2,000\u20132,750\n|}\n\n====Transmission====\nAll models include an eight-speed tiptronic transmission.\n\n====Production====\nThe A8's aluminum chassis was built at Neckarsulm plant.<ref>{{cite web|title=Audi reveals new A8 technologies, tightens links with Porsche - SAE International|url=http://articles.sae.org/15364/|website=articles.sae.org|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Marketing====\nAs an [[April Fools' Day]] joke on 1 April 2015, Audi Japan announced a special edition A8 5.5 with a [[rice cooker]] on the rear center console. The 5.5 designation is a play on the Japanese words \"go\" (five) and \"han\" (half); when combined, they become {{nihongo|\"gohan\"|\u609f\u98ef}}, which is the Japanese word for \"rice\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.audi.jp/rice/ |title=Audi Japan debuts special edition A8 featuring a rice cooker |publisher=[[Audi]] |date=1 April 2015 |accessdate=5 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nAudi S8 was used in [[The Transporter Refueled]].<ref>[https://www.autoblog.com/2015/03/23/transporter-4-refueled-prequel-trailer-audi-video/ New Transporter 4 Refueled prequel trailer comes with new lead, new Audi S8]</ref>\n\nAudi S8 was used in [[Avengers: Age of Ultron]].<ref>[https://www.autoblog.com/2015/05/03/audi-s8-stan-lee-cameo-avengers-age-ultron-video/ Audi S8 makes cameo in commercial about cameos with Stan Lee]</ref>\n\nAudi A8 was used in [[Spider-Man: Homecoming]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=km3TGBPo_Jc/ Audi A8L, Spider-Man: Homecoming, Driving Test]</ref>\n\n== {{anchor|D5|fourth}} Fourth generation (D5 ''Typ'' 4N; 2018\u2013present) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Fourth generation (D5/4N)\n| image = Audi A8-D5.jpg\n| production = 2017\u2013present\n| model_years = 2018\u2013present (Europe)<br>2019\u2013present (Outside of Europe)\n| assembly = Germany\n| engine = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V8/W12 petrol engine \n|1 = 4.0&nbsp;L V8 twin-scroll turbo [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]]<br>6.0 L W12 twin-turbo [[Turbo fuel stratified injection|TFSI]] [[W12 engine|W12]]\n}}<ref>\"\u0431\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0431\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043c 4.0 V8 \u043c\u043e\u0449\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c\u044e 460 \u043b\u043e\u0448\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0438\u043b \u0438 660 \u041d\u043c \u043a\u0440\u0443\u0442\u044f\u0449\u0435\u0433\u043e \u043c\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430.\" https://web.archive.org/web/20190408225626/https://motor.ru/news/a845tdi-08-04-2019.htm</ref>\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 petrol engine\n|2 = 3.0&nbsp;L V6 twin-scroll turbo [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 petrol Hybrid system engine\n|3 = 3.0&nbsp;L V6 twin-scroll turbo [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]] MHEV system<br>3.0&nbsp;L V6 twin-scroll turbo [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]] PHEV system\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 diesel engine\n|4 = 3.0&nbsp;L V6 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]\n}}{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V8 diesel engine\n|4 = 4.0&nbsp;L V8 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]\n}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2998|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|3128|mm|1|abbr=on}} (LWB)\n| length = {{convert|5172|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|5302|mm|1|abbr=on}} (LWB)\n| width = {{convert|1945|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1485|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| related = [[Volkswagen Touareg#Third generation (2019\u2013present)|Volkswagen Touareg]]<br>[[Audi Q8]]<br>[[Audi A4#B9|Audi A4]]<br>[[Audi Q7#4M|Audi Q7]]<br>[[Audi A5#Second generation (2016\u2013present)|Audi A5]]<br>[[Audi A6#C8|Audi A6]]<br>[[Audi A7#Type 4G9 (2018\u2013present)|Audi A7]]<br>[[Porsche Cayenne#Third generation (2018\u2013present)|Porsche Cayenne]]<br>[[Lamborghini Urus]]\n}}\n[[File:Audi A8L 60 TFSIe Quattro 1Y7A5435.jpg|thumb|Audi A8L 60 TFSIe Quattro]]\n\n===A8, A8 L (2017\u2013)===\nThe design of the A8 and A8 L was based on the [[Audi Prologue]] concept. Changes include buttons being replaced by a touch screen, and self-parking.\n\nOne new feature outside of the United States is Traffic Jam Pilot, consisting of level 3 [[Self-driving car|autonomous driving]] at speeds up to 60&nbsp;km/h (37&nbsp;mph) when on a divided highway. Audi had planned to also include Traffic Jam Pilot in cars delivered to the U.S. starting in 2019, but cancelled those plans due to autonomous driving having a complicated legal, infrastructure and consumer environment in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/2019-audi-a8-level-3-traffic-jam-pilot-self-driving-automation-not-for-us/|title=Why the 2019 Audi A8 won't get Level 3 partial automation in the US|date=2018-05-14|work=Roadshow|access-date=2018-09-25|language=en |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe vehicle was unveiled at the Audi Summit in Barcelona on July 11, 2017, followed by the [[Frankfurt Motor Show#2017|2017 Frankfurt Motor Show]].<ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/press-releases/audi-at-the-iaa-2017-autonomous-driving-in-three-steps-9311 Audi at the IAA 2017: Autonomous driving in three steps]</ref>\n\nThe petrol engine will be a 3.0 L TFSI V6 with {{Convert|340|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}}. The 4.0 L TFSI V8 with {{Convert|460|PS|kW hp|abbr=on|0}} and the 6.0 L TFSI W12 from the [[Bentley Bentayga]], detuned to {{Convert|585|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} will be available only as dealer orders in Europe (not available directly from Audi's websites). Diesel engines will be a 3.0 L TDI V6 with {{Convert|286|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} and lifted from Audi SQ7 and Bentley Bentayga Diesel, the 4.0 L TDI V8 with {{Convert|435|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}}. Like the previous generation, all cars will feature all-wheel drive and an 8-speed Tiptronic automatic.\n\nIt went on sale in November 2017, while pre-orders began on October 5, 2017. Early variants included 55 TFSI (3.0 TFSI) quattro, 50 TDI (3.0 TDI) quattro.<ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/press-releases/audi-a8-and-a8-l-6796 Audi A8 and A8 L]</ref><ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/press-releases/presales-start-for-new-audi-a8-9406 Presales start for new Audi A8]</ref>\n\nThe new A8 went on sale in September 2017. The estimated UK base price is \u00a370,000.\n\nThe Audi A8 L arrived in the U.S. on October 5, 2018, with deliveries started in November.<ref>https://auto.ndtv.com/news/2018-audi-a8-sales-to-start-in-us-from-october-5-deliveries-in-november-1757637</ref>\n\nThe A8 L 60 TFSI e quattro was revealed on October 16, 2019. It combines a {{Convert|340|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} 3.0 L TFSI V6 with a {{Convert|136|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} electric motor. The combined system output is {{Convert|449|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} and {{convert|700|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} of torque. The car gets a 14.1 kWh battery pack that delivers a pure electric range of 46 km (28.6 mi).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autodevot.com/2019/10/audi-a8-l-60-tfsi-e-quattro-plug-in-hybrid/|title=Audi A8 plugs-in, gets 46 km pure electric range|website=www.autodevot.com|accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Engines<ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/the-fourth-generation-of-the-audi-a8-heading-into-a-new-era-9403 The fourth generation of the Audi A8: heading into a new era]</ref>===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" style=\"font-size:98%;\"\n|+Petrol engines\n!Model!!Years!!Type!!Power, torque at rpm\n|-\n|A8 (L) 55 TFSI/3.0 TFSI quattro||2017-||{{convert|2995|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V6 twin-scroll turbo (VW EA 839 (CZSE))<ref>[https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/techday-on-combustion-engine-technology-8738/efficiency-and-driving-pleasure-innovative-v-engines-at-audi-8748 Efficiency and driving pleasure: innovative V engines at Audi]</ref>|| {{convert|340|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,000-6,000/6,400, {{convert|500|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} at 1,370-4,500\n|-\n|A8 (L) 60 TFSI quattro||2017-||{{convert|3993|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V8 twin turbo (CTGA)|| {{convert|460|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,000, {{convert|600|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} at 1,500\u20134,500\n|-\n|A8 (L) 55 TFSI-e/60 TFSI-e quattro||2019-||{{convert|2995|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V6 twin-scroll turbo Mild Hybrid (VW EA 839 (CZSE)) + Electric Motor|| {{convert|340|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,000-6,000 (Engine)<br>{{convert|100|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} (Electric Motor)<br>{{convert|442|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} (Combined),<br>{{convert|NNNN|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} at 1,370-4,500 (Engine)<br>{{convert|NNNN|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} (Electric Motor)<br>{{convert|700|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} (Combined)\n|-\n|A8 L e-tron PHEV quattro||2019-||{{convert|2995|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V6 twin-scroll turbo Plug-in Hybrid (VW EA 839 (CZSE)) + Electric Motor|| {{convert|340|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,000-6,000 (Engine)<br>{{convert|128|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} (Electric Motor)<br>{{convert|449|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} (Combined),<br>{{convert|500|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} at 1,370-4,500 (Engine)<br>{{convert|NNNN|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} (Electric Motor)<br>{{convert|700|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} (Combined)\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" style=\"font-size:98%;\"\n|+Diesel engines\n!Model!!Years!!Type!!Power, torque at rpm\n|-\n|A8 (L) 50 TDI/3.0 TDI quattro||2017-||{{convert|2967|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V6 turbo (VW EA 897 evo (DDVC)) || {{convert|286|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 3,750-4,000, {{convert|600|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} at 1,250-3,250\n|-\n|A8 (L) 60 TDI/4.0 TDI quattro\n|2019-\n|{{convert|3956|cc|cuin||abbr=on}} V8 twin-turbo (VW EA 898)\n|{{convert|435|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}} at 3,750-4,750, {{convert|900|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|1|abbr=on}} at 1,250-3,250\n|}\n\n===Transmission===\nAll models include an eight-speed tiptronic transmission.\n\n===Production===\nThe A8 and A8 L are produced at the [[Neckarsulm]] plant.\n\n===Marketing===\nAs part of the deal between [[Marvel Studios]] and Audi, the fourth generation of A8 first premiered in the \"Driver's Test\" commercial that premiered on June 19, 2017, as a tie-in to [[Spider-Man: Homecoming]] movie.<ref>{{Citation|last=Audi USA|title=Audi \"Driver\u2019s Test\" - Spider-Man: Homecoming|date=2017-06-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GIXyL9vlYo4 |accessdate=2017-07-30 |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/marvel/2017/06/20/spider-man-homecoming-peter-parker-takes-his-driving-test/|title=Spider-Man: Homecoming - Peter Parker Takes His Driving Test|website=Marvel|access-date=2017-07-30 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> In the commercial, [[Peter Parker]] ([[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]) takes the car, a prototype belonging to [[Tony Stark]], for a test-drive alongside his driving instructor played by [[J. B. Smoove]]. The car also had a small product placement appearance in the actual movie itself.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.imcdb.org/vehicle_1050098-Audi-A8-2018.html|title=Audi A8 in \"Spider-Man: Homecoming\" |work= IMCDb.org |access-date= 2017-07-30 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year!!Units\n|-\n|2001<ref name=\"volkswagenag2003\">http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2003/03/annual_report_2002.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/vw_gb_2002_en.pdf</ref>||11,708\n|-\n|2002<ref name=\"volkswagenag2003\"/>||10,942\n|-\n|2003<ref name=\"volkswagenag2005\">{{cite web |url= http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2005/03/annual_report_2004.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/Gbericht_2004_en.pdf |title= Kom_engl_2602_1320.qxd |format=[[PDF]] |accessdate= 2011-02-02 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110112130117/http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2005/03/annual_report_2004.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/Gbericht_2004_en.pdf |archivedate= 12 January 2011 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref>||21,748\n|-\n|2004<ref name=\"volkswagenag2005\"/>||22,429\n|-\n|2005<ref name=\"volkswagenag2007\">[http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2007/03/Geschaeftsbericht_2006.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/Annual_Report_2006_e.pdf untitled<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>||21,509\n|-\n|2006<ref name=\"volkswagenag2007\"/>||22,468\n|-\n|2007<ref name=\"volkswagenag1\">{{cite web |url= http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2009/03/GB_2008.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/Y_2008_e.pdf |title= Volkswagen AG Annual Report 2008 |format=[[PDF]] |accessdate= 2011-02-02 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110110144055/http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2009/03/GB_2008.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/Y_2008_e.pdf |archivedate= 10 January 2011 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref>||22,182\n|-\n|2008<ref name=\"volkswagenag1\"/>||20,140\n|-\n|2009<ref name=\"volkswagenag3\">http://www.volkswagenag.com/vwag/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2010/03/Annual_Report_2009.-bin.acq/qual-BinaryStorageItem.Single.File/Y_2009_e.pdf</ref>||8,599\n|-\n|2010<ref name=\"volkswagenag3\"/>\n|22,435\n|-\n|2011{{fact|date=March 2019}}\n|38,542\n|-\n|2012<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2013/03/Y_2012_e.bin.html/binarystorageitem/file/GB+2012_e.pdf |format=[[PDF]] |title= Archived copy |accessdate= 2013-03-16 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131002114230/http://www.volkswagenag.com/content/vwcorp/info_center/en/publications/2013/03/Y_2012_e.bin.html/binarystorageitem/file/GB+2012_e.pdf |archivedate= 2013-10-02 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n|35,932\n|-\n|2013<ref>http://www.audi.com/content/dam/com/EN/investor-relations/financial_reports/annual-reports/2013_audi_annual_report.pdf</ref>\n|39,757\n|-\n|2014<ref>http://www.audi.com/content/dam/com/EN/investor-relations/financial_reports/annual-reports/2014_audi_annual_report.pdf</ref>\n|39,606\n|-\n|2015<ref>http://www.audi.com/content/dam/com/EN/investor-relations/financial_reports/annual-reports/audi-ar-2015.pdf</ref>\n|27,077\n|-\n|2016<ref>https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/overview-of-audi-5702/smart-factory-the-digital-production-of-the-future-5708</ref>\n|24,147\n|-\n|2017<ref>https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/overview-of-audi-5702/smart-factory-the-digital-production-of-the-future-5708</ref>\n|15,854\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Audi A8}}\n* Audi pages: [http://www.audi.com/com/brand/en/models/a8/a8.html A8], [http://www.audi.com/com/brand/en/models/audi_security_cars/audi_a8_l_security.html Audi A8 L Security], [http://www.audi.com/com/brand/en/experience/design___technology/design_studies/audi_a8_hybrid.html A8 hybrid (concept)]\n\n{{Audi}}\n{{Audi vehicles timeline (Europe)}}\n{{Audi vehicles timeline (North America)}}\n\n[[Category:Audi vehicles|A8]]\n[[Category:All-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Euro NCAP executive cars]]\n[[Category:Flagship vehicles]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Full-size vehicles]]\n[[Category:Limousines]]\n[[Category:Luxury vehicles]]\n[[Category:Plug-in hybrid vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sedans]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1994]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:2020s cars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Audi A8\n| image = 2018 Audi A8 50 TDi Quattro Automatic 3.0.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Audi AG]]\n| assembly = Germany: [[Neckarsulm]] (Neckarsulm Audi Factory)\n| aka = Audi A8L, [[#Audi A8 (L) W12|Audi A8 W12]]<br>[[Audi S8|Audi S8, Audi S8 Plus]]\n| production = '''[[#D2|D2]]:''' 1994\u20132002<br>'''[[#D3|D3]]:''' 2002\u20132010<br>'''[[#D4|D4]]:''' 2010\u20132017<br>'''[[#D5|D5]]:''' 2017\u2013present\n| class = [[Full-size]] [[luxury car]] ([[F-segment|F]])\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| platform = [[List of Volkswagen Group platforms|MLB]]\n| layout = [[Longitudinal engine|Longitudinal]] [[FF layout|FF]] / [[F4 layout]] ([[quattro (four-wheel-drive system)|quattro]])\n| related = [[Audi S8]], [[Bentley Continental Flying Spur|Bentley Flying Spur]]\n| predecessor = [[Audi V8]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Audi A8''' is a four-door, [[full-size]], [[luxury vehicle|luxury]] [[sedan (car)|sedan]] manufactured and marketed by the German automaker [[Audi]] since 1994. Succeeding the [[Audi V8]], and now in its fourth generation, the A8 has been offered with both [[front-wheel drive|front-]] or permanent [[four-wheel drive|all-wheel drive]]\u2014and in short- and long-wheelbase variants. The first two generations employed the [[Volkswagen Group D platform]], with the current generation deriving from the [[Volkswagen Group MLB platform|MLB platform]]. After the original model's 1994 release, Audi released the second generation in late 2002, the third in late 2009, and the fourth and current iteration in 2017.\n\nNotable for being the first mass-market car with an aluminium chassis, all A8 models have used this construction method co-developed with [[Alcoa]] and marketed as the ''Audi Space Frame''.<ref name=\"nytalcoa\">{{cite news |title= Speaking of Understatements |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Lawrence |last=Ulrich |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/14/automobiles/autoreviews/14audi-a8.html?_r=1&hp |date=12 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nA mechanically-upgraded, high-performance version of the A8 debuted in 1996 as the '''[[Audi S8]]'''. Produced exclusively at Audi's [[Neckarsulm]] plant, the S8 is fitted standard with Audi's [[quattro (four wheel drive system)|quattro]] all-wheel drive system, and is available in short- and long-wheelbase form, the latter coming in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1123880_2020-audi-s8-barrels-in-with-563-horsepower-v-8|title=2020 Audi S8 barrels in with 563-horsepower V-8|website=Motor Authority|language=en|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref>\n\n== {{anchor|D2|4D|first}} First generation (D2, ''Typ'' 4D; 1994\u20132002) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = First generation (D2/4D)\n| image = A8 white.jpg\n| caption = Pre-facelift Audi A8 4.2 quattro (US)\n| production = June 1994 \u2013 August 4, 2002<ref name=ETKA/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-12-29/business/9312290075_1_aluminum-space-frame-audi-ag-audi-a8 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | first=Jim | last=Mateja | title=Audi Puts Aluminum-car Plans In Gear | date=1993-12-29 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n| assembly = Germany: [[Neckarsulm]]\n| platform = [[Volkswagen Group D platform#D2|Volkswagen Group D2]]\n| engine = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 petrol engine\n|1 = 2.8 [[V6 engine|V6]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V8 petrol engine\n|1 = 3.7 [[List_of_Volkswagen_Group_petrol_engines|Volkswagen Group AEW]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n|2 = 4.2 [[List_of_Volkswagen_Group_petrol_engines#4.2_V8_32v_FSI|Volkswagen Group]] V8\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = W12 engine\n|1 = 6.0 [[Volkswagen W12 engine|W12]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 diesel engine\n|1 = [[List of discontinued Volkswagen Group diesel engines#Six-cylinder diesels|2.5]] [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI V6]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V8 diesel engine\n|1 = [[List of discontinued Volkswagen Group diesel engines#Eight-cylinder diesels|3.3 TDI V8]]\n}}\n| transmission = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Manual transmission\n|1 = 5-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]\n|2 = 6-speed manual (S8)\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Automatic transmission\n|1 = 4-speed [[ZF 4HP24 transmission|ZF 4HP24]] [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n|2 = 5-speed [[ZF 5HP19 transmission|ZF 5HP19]] automatic\n|3 = 5-speed [[ZF 5HP24 transmission|ZF 5HP24]] automatic\n}}\n| wheelbase = SWB: {{convert|2882|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br>LWB: {{convert|3010|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = SWB: {{convert|5034|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br>LWB: {{convert|5164|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1880|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1438|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = '''2.5:''' {{convert|1630|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (TDI)<br>'''2.5:''' {{convert|1735|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (TDI AWD)<br>'''3.3:''' {{convert|1860|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (TDI AWD)<br>'''2.8:''' {{convert|1540|kg|lb||abbr=on}}<br>'''3.7:''' {{convert|1645|kg|lb||abbr=on}}<br>'''3.7:''' {{convert|1725|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (AWD)<br>'''4.2:''' {{convert|1750|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (AWD)<br>'''4.2:''' {{convert|1845|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (US)<br>'''4.2:''' {{convert|1790|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (AWD A8L)<br>'''4.2:''' {{convert|1885|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (US)<br>'''6.0:''' {{convert|1950|kg|lb||abbr=on}}<br>'''6.0:''' {{convert|1980|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (AWD A8L)<br>'''S8:''' {{convert|1730|kg|lb||abbr=on}}<br>'''S8:''' {{convert|1845|kg|lb||abbr=on}} (US)\n| designer = Chris Bird; Dirk van Braeckel (1990, 1991)<ref>http://i184.photobucket.com/albums/x136/GTO-Carsouce/audi.jpg</ref>\n| sp = uk\n}}\n\n=== Development ===\n[[File:Audi Space Frame.JPG|thumb|left|Audi Space Frame concept car|alt=]]\n\nIn 1982, [[Ferdinand Pi\u00ebch]] signed an agreement with [[Alcoa|Aluminum Company of America]]. The objective was to design and develop a car that would be substantially lighter than any other vehicles in its class (to compensate for the fact that standard all-wheel drive was around {{Convert|100|kg|0|abbr=on}} heavier than competitors' rear-wheel drive). In the late 1980s, it was decided that the target vehicle would be a successor to the V8 (Typ 4C) flagship introduced in 1988. By 1990, a final design by Chris Bird and [[Dirk van Braeckel]] was chosen and frozen for series production in mid-1991. In September 1993, the Audi Space Frame (ASF) Concept was unveiled at the [[Frankfurt Motor Show#1993|1993 Frankfurt Motor Show]] (IAA) as a D2 Typ 4D prototype in polished aluminum. Pilot production began in December 1993 and development ended in early 1994, at a total cost of $700 million (\u00a3418.1 million).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0bh_Wu6YjLMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22N.+Anyadike%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WeR5UbufJajk2AXa2IHgDg&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Aluminium|publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Introduction ===\nThe Audi A8 (''Typ'' 4D) was presented in February 1994 and debuted at the [[Geneva Auto Show#1994|1994 Geneva Auto Show]] in March, with full-scale factory production commencing in June 1994,<ref name=ETKA>[[ETKA]] official factory data</ref>{{Clarify|date=April 2010|reason=This is not a proper reference citation.Use {{tl|Cite web}} or similar to provide source details.}} although it was not until October 1996, for the 1997 [[model year]] that it became available in North America. Unlike its predecessor, the [[Audi V8]] model, which was built on an existing steel platform, the A8 debuted on the then-new [[Volkswagen Group D platform#D2|Volkswagen Group D2 platform]], an all [[aluminium]] [[monocoque]], marketed as the {{nowrap|\"Audi Space Frame\"}} (ASF), which helped to reduce weight and preserve structural rigidity. The [[sedan (automobile)|saloon/sedan]] was offered in both the A8 (standard wheelbase), and the A8 L extended or long-[[wheelbase]] (LWB) version. The A8 L adds {{convert|5|in|0}} of rear legroom. Updates to the car in 1997 included the addition of six interior [[airbag]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/9610111755/renaissance-rings|title=Renaissance of the rings|publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>http://audi-q7.bootnetworks.com/</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topcars.am/en/brand/audi/a8.html|title=Audi A8 :: Top Cars ::|accessdate=14 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715031009/http://www.topcars.am/en/brand/audi/a8.html|archivedate=15 July 2015}}</ref> The A8 was designed as a competitor to fellow German rivals [[Mercedes Benz S Class]] and the [[BMW 7 Series]].\n\n{{multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width = 200\n| image2 = 1996 Audi A8 (4D) 4.2 crimson quattro sedan, back.jpg\n| caption2 = Pre-facelift Audi A8 4.2 quattro\n| image3 = 1st Audi A8 L 4.2 -- 03-21-2012.JPG\n| caption3 = Facelift Audi A8 L 4.2 quattro (US)\n| image4 = A8 W12.JPG\n| caption4 = First series production Audi with [[list of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#6.0 WR12 48v|W12]] engine\n}}\n\nIn 1997, Audi introduced the first series production [[electronic stability control]] (ESP) for all-wheel drive vehicles (Audi A8 and Audi A6)\u2013 the world's first production cars with both front and rear [[side airbag]]s.\n\nFor 1997, the new A8 was available with either [[front-wheel drive]] (FWD), or the [[Torsen]]-based [[quattro (four-wheel drive system)|quattro]] permanent [[four-wheel drive]]. The FWD models are powered by a [[list of discontinued Volkswagen Group petrol engines#2.8V6-24v|2.8-litre V6 engine]], producing {{convert|142|kW|PS bhp|0|abbr=on}}, and a 3.7-litre [[V8 engine]] producing {{convert|169|kW|PS bhp|0|abbr=on}}, while the quattro received a [[list of discontinued Volkswagen Group petrol engines#4.2 V8 32v 206-220kW|4.2-litre V8]] producing {{convert|221|kW|PS bhp|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe A8 is available with standard luxury amenities, including dual-zone [[climate control]], wood and leather interior trim, 14-way power and heated seats, and an enhanced [[Bose Corporation|Bose]] audio system.\n\nIn 1999, Audi's flagship received [[side curtain airbag]]s, new colours, and restructuring of option packages. The North American \"warm weather package\" added a solar [[sunroof#Sunroof Types|sunroof]] which allows the interior ventilation fans to run, keeping the interior cool while the car is parked with the engine turned off. Changes to all models included a larger passenger-side mirror, and a [[first aid kit]] located in the rear centre armrest.\n\nIn 1999 for the 2000 [[model year]] came a minor front-end restyle, with new, larger, clear [[headlamp|headlights]], a revised grille, and lower front valance with standard projection fog lamps. On the interior, the seats received a new, horizontal stitch pattern. Also, the [[list of discontinued Volkswagen Group petrol engines#3.7V8-32v|3.7-litre V8]] FWD model was dropped, leaving the 2.8 V6 model and the long-wheelbase and short-wheelbase 4.2-litre quattro. These restyled cars also featured revised external door handles and an integrated radio antenna. For 2000, the North American A8 line-up was expanded to include the A8 L.\n\nIn 2001, Audi introduced its new [[W12 engine]], a compact [[Volkswagen Group W12 engine|6.0-litre unit]] developed by effectively mating two [[VR6 engine]]s together at the crankshaft. The engine quickly became available in the A8, though only to European and Asian customers. From its introduction through its discontinuation in 2003, only 750 of the D2 \"W12\" models were produced. 2001 also marked the debut of the high-performance S8 variant in North American markets.\n\nIn 2002, the A8 L received standard [[xenon arc lamp|xenon]] [[high-intensity discharge lamp]] (HID) headlights, and a heated steering wheel. A [[tire pressure monitoring system|tyre pressure monitoring system]] (TPMS), an updated Symphony II stereo, and new exterior colours were also added. For 2002, all A8 variants received a trunk/boot interior release lever to facilitate escape in the event an individual became trapped within.\n\nFactory production of this generation ceased at Number 105,092<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.audiworld.com/news/02/080402/content.shtml|title=Audi A8 Number 105,092 Initiates Change of Generation - AudiWorld|work=AudiWorld|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref> on August 4, 2002.<ref name=ETKA/>\n\n=== Coup\u00e9 (prototype) ===\nIn 1997, [[IVM Automotive]] of Munich, Germany built a two-door Audi A8 Coup\u00e9. The car was unveiled at the 1997 [[Salon International de l'Auto|Geneva Motor Show]]. Audi contracted IVM to build the [[prototype]], and was considering production of the vehicle. The [[coup\u00e9]] had a re-engineered aluminium body, shorter than the production A8 saloon. Like the [[Mercedes-Benz CL-Class]], there was no central \"B\" pillar, giving the car a seamless design with a gradually sloping roofline. The car included custom leather seats which could seat four. Ultimately, Audi decided not to put the A8 Coup\u00e9 into production, citing lower-than-expected sales figures for the similar [[BMW 8 Series (E31)]] and [[Mercedes-Benz CL-Class#C140|Mercedes-Benz S-Class Coup\u00e9]]. Only one A8 Coup\u00e9 was ever built. The single prototype, painted in a colour called \"Ming Blue pearl\", remains the property of IVM Automotive, and resides in Munich. Its last public appearance was in 2002 on a series of test drives.{{Clear}}\n\n=== S8 ===\n{{multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width = 200\n| image1 = Audi S8 D2 (Typ 4D) (3962439095).jpg\n| image2 = Audi S8 schwarz hl 1024x768.jpg\n| caption2 = Facelift Audi S8\n}}\n\nAudi introduced the S8 4.2 quattro into the European market in 1996. The S8 followed the naming convention of other high-performance [[Audi S and RS models|Audi \"S\" models]] such as the [[Audi A6]]-derived S6 and was similar in vein of [[Mercedes-Benz AMG]] models. In markets such as the UK, the S8 was only available with the automatic transmission. Cosmetically, Audi differentiated the S8 from the A8 with solid aluminium alloy door mirror housings, chrome-effect beltline and lower front grille trim, and polished twin exhaust pipes, along with subtle \"S8\" badging. 14-way power adjustable and heated sports front seats with memory function were fitted as were heated rear seats. Standard [[alloy wheel]]s were 18-inch cast [[aluminium alloy]] \"Avus\" six-spoke style. After the 1999 facelift, 20-inch polished nine-spoke RS wheels became an option. In 2002, 18-inch nine-spoke RS wheels became a no-cost option.\n\nAt the same time of the A8's facelift in late 1999, the S8 received the same cosmetic upgrades. This update marked the release of the S8 to the North American market. Production of the D2 series S8 ended in September 2002.\n\nThe D2 series S8 featured an uprated, {{convert|250|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} version of the 4.2-litre V8 with four valves per cylinder. From late 1999, Audi increased this to five valves per cylinder with power increased to {{convert|265|kW|hp|0}} and {{convert|430|Nm|lbft|0}}. From launch in 1996, European-market models came standard with a six-speed manual transmission. A sports-recalibrated version of the [[ZF 5HP24 transmission|ZF ''5HP24'']] five-speed [[tiptronic]] automatic, featuring \"Dynamic Shift Programme\" (DSP) was released a year later and was the only transmission available in most other markets.\n\nA retuned, {{convert|20|mm|in|1|adj=on}} lowered sports suspension included a 30 percent stiffer spring rate and 40 percent more compression damping in the [[shock absorber]]s. Speed-sensitive \"[[servotronic]]\" power assisted steering was also standard.\n\nThe brakes featured [[Robert Bosch GmbH|Bosch]] 5.3 [[anti-lock braking system]] (ABS), with [[electronic brakeforce distribution]] (EBD), and worked radially ventilated front [[disc brake|discs]]. From 2002, an upgraded Bosch 5.7 [[electronic stability control|electronic stability programme]] became standard fitment.\n\n=== Engines ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:98%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|Engine\n!rowspan=2|Power Torque at rpm\n!rowspan=2|0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h<br><small>(0\u201362&nbsp;mph)</small>\n!rowspan=2|Top speed\n|-\n!Displacement\n!Year\n!Type\n|-\n|2.8 (2771&nbsp;cc) || 1994\u20132002 || [[V6 engine|V6]] || {{convert|174|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|250|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9.1&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|228|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|2.8 (2771&nbsp;cc) || 1994\u20132002 || V6 ||{{convert|193|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|280|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8.4&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|236|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.7 (3697&nbsp;cc) || TBC\u20131999 || V8 ||{{convert|230|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|315|Nm|lb\u00b7ft|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8.7&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|247|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.7 (3697&nbsp;cc) || 1999\u2013TBC || [[V8 engine|V8]] || {{convert|260|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|350|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7.8&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|250|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|4.2 quattro (4172&nbsp;cc) || 1997\u20132002 || V8 || {{convert|300|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|400|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6.9&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|250|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|4.2 quattro (4172&nbsp;cc) || || V8 || {{convert|310|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|410|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6.5&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|250|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|4.2 quattro (4172&nbsp;cc) (S8) || 1996\u20131999 || V8 || {{convert|340|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|420|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5.6&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|250|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|4.2 quattro (4172&nbsp;cc) (S8) || 1999\u20132002 || V8 || {{convert|360|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|430|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5.4&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|250|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|6.0 (5998&nbsp;cc) (A8 L) || 2001\u20132002 || [[W12 engine|W12]] || {{convert|420|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|550|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5.8&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|250|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|2.5 (2496&nbsp;cc) || || V6 TDI || {{convert|150|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|310|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9.9&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|220|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|2.5 (2496&nbsp;cc) || || V6 TDI || {{convert|180|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|370|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8.8&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|227|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.3 (3328&nbsp;cc) || || V8 TDI || {{convert|225|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|480|Nm|0|abbr=on}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8.2&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|242|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n|}\n\n== {{anchor|D3|4E|second}} Second generation (D3, ''Typ'' 4E; 2002\u20132009) ==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Second generation (D3/4E)\n| image = 2003-2005 Audi A8 (4E) 4.2 quattro sedan (2011-01-05).jpg\n| caption = Pre-facelift Audi A8 4.2 quattro \n| production = August 2002 \u2013 November 2009<ref name=ETKA/><ref name=Audi-Motors.net/>\n| assembly = Germany: [[Neckarsulm]]\n| platform = [[Volkswagen Group D platform#D3|Volkswagen Group D3]]\n| engine = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 petrol engine\n|1 = 2.8&nbsp;[[litre|L]] [[V6 engine|V6]]\n|2 = 3.0&nbsp;L V6<br>3.2&nbsp;L V6 [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V8 petrol engine\n|1 = 3.7&nbsp;L [[V8 engine|V8]]\n|2 = 4.2&nbsp;L V8\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V10 petrol engine\n|1 = 5.2&nbsp;L [[V10 engine|V10]] [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = W12 engine\n|1 = 6.0&nbsp;L [[List of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#6.0 WR12 48v|W12]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V6 diesel engine\n|1 = 3.0&nbsp;L V6 [[Turbocharged Direct Injection|TDI]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = V8 diesel engine\n|1 = 4.0&nbsp;L V8 TDI\n|2 = 4.2&nbsp;L V8 TDI\n}}\n| transmission = {{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Automatic transmission\n|1 = 6-speed [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] [[ZF 6HP26 transmission|6HP26]] [[tiptronic]] [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0;| title = Continuously variable transmission\n|1 = LuK [[multitronic]] [[continuously variable transmission|CVT]]\n}}\n| wheelbase = SWB: {{convert|2944|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br>LWB: {{convert|3074|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = SWB:<br>pre 2007: {{convert|5051|mm|1|abbr=on}},<br>post 2007: {{convert|5062|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br>LWB:<br>pre 2007: {{convert|5181|mm|1|abbr=on}},<br>post 2007: {{convert|5192|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1894|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = SWB: {{convert|1444|mm|1|abbr=on}}<br>LWB: {{convert|1455|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|1670|-|1990|kg|0|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| designer = Mikl\u00f3s Kov\u00e1cs, Imre Hasanic, Dany Garand (1999)<ref name=cdn>{{cite web |last= Livingstone |first= Sam |title= The Audi A8 Design Story |url= http://archive.cardesignnews.com/features/2003/030802audi-a8/index.html |publisher= Car Design News |accessdate= 23 November 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130411015836/http://archive.cardesignnews.com/features/2003/030802audi-a8/index.html |archivedate= 11 April 2013 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n| sp = uk\n}}\n\nThe second-generation Audi A8 (''Typ'' 4E) built on the [[Volkswagen Group D platform#D3|Volkswagen Group D3 platform]] was unveiled via press release in July 2002 and introduced in November 2002 in Europe<ref name=ETKA/><ref name=Audi-Motors.net>{{cite web|url=http://www.audi-motors.net/audi13.html|title=Audi A8 Design|work=Audi-Motors.net|year=2006|accessdate=4 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909002756/http://www.audi-motors.net/audi13.html|archivedate=9 September 2010}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=March 2010}} and in June 2003 (as a 2004 model) in the United States. The model was longer than the previous generation, with room for four or five large adult occupants in the cabin, depending on rear seat configuration. The D3 development program began in 1996, with the design process commencing in Ingolstadt in 1997. The whole Audi design studio based in Ingolstadt first contributed sketch proposals, from which numerous different themes emerged. Six of them were developed into full size clay models and worked up in a traditional manner adjacent to full size tape drawings. At least three one quarter scale models were produced to explore other design variations.\n\n{{multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width = 225\n| image1 = 2004 Audi A8 (4E) 4.2 quattro sedan (2015-07-14) 02.jpg | caption1= Pre-facelift Audi A8 4.2 quattro\n| image2 = Audi A8 L D3 II.Facelift 20090720 front.JPG\n| image3 = Audi A8 L D3 II.Facelift 20090720 rear.JPG | caption3 = Facelift Audi A8 L 3.0 TDI\n}}\n\nThe six full size exterior clay models were reduced to two in late 1998 and these continued to be refined in parallel for a year. At the end of 1999 the final theme selection was made, by [[Mikl\u00f3s Kov\u00e1cs (automobile designer)|Mikl\u00f3s Kov\u00e1cs]] and Imre Hasanic the main contributing designers. This lengthy development time was in part due to the body being made from aluminium, a material less able to take the small radii of sharp feature lines such as those on the (steel bodied) A4 (B6) designed in 1998.\n\nIn parallel to the exterior design development the interior design was progressed with a total of four full size models produced and the production car's horizontally themed instrument panel design dominant from early on, with Norbert Schneider, Mark Bergold and Enzo Rothfuss the main contributing designers.\n\nGrouping major controls nearer the driver for a more driver focused identity whilst creating a more airy and spacious feel were early priorities for the interior design team was headed by Jurgen Albamonte. This was in part facilitated by the [[Multi Media Interface]] (MMI) designed by Jurgen Schr\u00f6der, that pioneered on the D3 A8 after the [[Audi Avantissimo]] concept car preview, and also by class leading colour and trim from Barbara Kr\u00f6meke and Melinda Jenkins.\n\nUnder the supervision of Dany Garand, during the first half of 2000 exterior and interior clay models were digitized and developed using digital design tools in a supporting, not leading, capacity. The D3 final production design was later frozen in the summer of 2000 for an August 2002 start of production.<ref name=\"cdn\"/>\n\nThe A8 was previewed at the [[Frankfurt Motor Show#2001|2001 Frankfurt Motor Show]] by the [[Audi Avantissimo]] concept car. This concept introduced much of the technology later available on the series production A8 D3, including: [[Multi Media Interface]], 6-speed automatic transmission with shift paddles, V8 [[biturbo]] engine (RS6), [[self-levelling suspension|self-levelling]] [[adaptive air suspension]] with [[continuously controlled damping]], [[electric park brake]], [[bi-xenon headlight]]s with static [[Adaptive Front Lighting System (AFS)]] curve headlights, dashboard, driver identification systems with [[fingerprint scanner]].\n\nAs with the previous version, two body variants of the second generation A8 are offered, the A8 (standard, or short wheelbase), and the long-[[wheelbase]] (LWB) A8 L. The A8 L adds {{convert|120|mm|abbr=in}} to the rear legroom and {{convert|11|mm|2|abbr=on}} to the overall height of the car.\n\nFor quattro all wheel drive models, a [[ZF 6HP26 transmission|ZF ''6HP26-A61'']] (lower torque capacity 6HP19 version for 6 cylinder models) six-speed [[tiptronic]] automatic transmission with \"Dynamic Shift Programme\" (DSP) and \"sport\" mode, with optional steering wheel mounted paddle-shifters, is the only transmission offering. Output is transmitted via Audi's [[quattro (four wheel drive system)|quattro]] generation IV all-wheel drive system using the [[Torsen]] T-1 centre [[differential (mechanical device)|differential]] with a default 50:50 torque split front/rear. If the road conditions change, the purely mechanical Torsen differential responds without any delay; it can divert up to 70 percent of power to the front or rear axles.\n\n=== Innovations ===\n* World premiere of [[Multi Media Interface]] (MMI) in-car [[user interface]] (similar to BMW [[iDrive]])\n* [[Multiplexing|Multiplexed]] high speed [[MOST Bus]] [[optical fiber]] data networks (interconnecting tens of [[microprocessor]]s on common [[bus (computing)|databusses]]), integrated with MMI\n* First Audi with [[Bi-Xenon]] [[HID headlamp]]s for both low and high beam\n* World premiere of static [[Adaptive Front Lighting System (AFS)]] curve headlights (from [[Hella (company)|Hella]])<ref>[http://www.kfztech.de/kfztechnik/elo/licht/Lichttechnik_modern.htm Moderne Lichttechnik] - Kurvenlicht - statisch und dynamisch (AFS)</ref>\n* First Audi with 4-wheel [[adaptive suspension|Adaptive]] [[air suspension|Air Suspension]] and [[Continuous Damping Control]] (CDC)-(Skyhook suspension).\n* First Audi GPS [[automotive navigation system|navigation system]] with [[DVD]] maps\n* First Audi with six-speed automatic transmission (Tiptronic)\n* First Audi featuring [[fingerprint recognition|driver identification system]]\n\nIn 2005, new internal combustion engines became available. For European and Asian market customers, the entry-level 3.0-litre [[V6 engine]] was replaced with a new 3.2-litre unit featuring [[gasoline direct injection|Fuel Stratified Injection]] (FSI), which it shared with the [[Audi A4#B7|Audi B7 A4]] and [[Audi A6#C6|Audi C6 A6]]. The top-of-the-line W12 version debuted that year. The advantage of the [[W12 engine]] layout is its compact packaging, allowing Audi to build a 12-cylinder sedan with all-wheel drive, whereas a conventional V12 could only have a rear-wheel drive configuration as it would have no space in the engine bay for a differential and other components required to power the front wheels. In fact, Audi's 6.0-litre W12 is actually slightly smaller by overall dimensions than the 4.2-litre V8.<ref name=\"newcartestdrive1\">{{cite web |url= http://www.newcartestdrive.com/review-intro.cfm?Vehicle=2005_Audi_A8&ReviewID=2934 |title= 2005 Audi A8 Review, Prices, Photos |work= New Car Test Drive |date= |accessdate= 2010-10-03 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the added power trains, Audi restyled the D3 platform A8 range slightly in 2005, giving all variants a taller, wider [[trapezoid]]al ''single-frame'' grille. The top-of-the-line [[W12 engine]]d '''W12''' version was the first model to be equipped with this grille; [[V8 engine]]d models were fitted with the new grille the following year.<ref name=\"newcartestdrive1\"/>\n\n[[File:AudiA8BangAndOlufsenTweeterLens.JPG|thumb|The unique, motorized [[Bang & Olufsen]] tweeter in a 2008 Audi A8|alt=]]\n\nThe D3 generation A8 introduced the {{convert|235|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} 4.2-litre [[Turbocharged Direct Injection]] (TDI) [[V8 engine]] (subsequently uprated to {{convert|240|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}}). The engine uses two [[turbocharger]]s and two [[intercooler]]s, with each turbocharger functioning exclusively for one bank of four [[cylinder (engine)|cylinders]].\n\nThe adaptive air suspension gives the vehicle clearance a range from its normal 120&nbsp;mm up to 145&nbsp;mm in lift mode and down to 95&nbsp;mm in the ''Autobahn'' mode, which is automatically activated when a speed of more than {{Convert|120|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} is maintained for more than 30 seconds.<ref>{{cite book|title=Audi A8 Betriebsanleitung|page=151|chapter=adaptive air suspension|publisher= [[Audi AG]]|year=2008|trans-title=Audi A8 Operating Instructions|language=German}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2005 Audi became the first car maker to offer the 1,000-watt 14-channel [[ICEpower]] sound system option from [[Bang & Olufsen]].<ref>{{cite book| title = Preisliste A8 S8 A8 W12 (633/1512.80.00)|date=October 2006| page=16|language=German| publisher=Audi AG}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ing.dk/artikel/audi-med-indbygget-koncertsal-fra-bo-62966|title=Audi med indbygget koncertsal fra B&O|trans-title=Audi with built in concert hall from B&O|last=Kr\u00f8yer|first=Kent|date=13 March 2005|accessdate=6 November 2014|publisher=Mediehuset Ingeni\u00f8ren A/S|language=Danish}}</ref>\n\n=== 2007 facelift ===\nChanges include:\n* Updated front fascia incorporating Audi's signature single frame full-nose grill. Complimenting the pronounced styling of the nose, designers tossed the understated round fog lights, opting for larger rectangular fog Light housings- inside a set of 'Side-View illuminators' have been integrated into the housing; aiding drivers in low-light or poor visibility conditions by automatically illuminating depending on speed and steering angle. Side-View Illuminators operate independent of fog lights.\n* Updated tail-light assembly featuring much brighter and more efficient LED bulbs. Dual rear fog lights are still standard.\nNew Optional Features:\n* Full speed range [[adaptive cruise control]] ACC Plus, can now brake until stop\n* [[Braking guard]] [[radar]]-guided [[forward collision warning]] system\n* [[Side Assist]]\" detects cars in the A8's blind spots\n* [[Lane assist]] helps when the driver attempts to change lanes without signalling first.\n\n=== A8 L W12 quattro Security ===\n[[File:Black Audi A8 L W12 Security (D3-2) fr IAA 2011.jpg|right|thumbnail|Armored A8]]\nThe A8 L W12 quattro Security is an armoured vehicle with B6+ and B7 (European standard) ballistic ratings. It includes a W12 engine rated at {{convert|450|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on|order=flip}} and {{convert|580|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of torque, emergency exit system featuring pyrotechnic blown-out doors, fire extinguisher system with spray jets located in the engine compartment, underbody and in the wheel arches; smoke extractor in passenger compartment, run flat tires, bullet proof windows, the full protection plus package and LED flashers in the exterior mirrors. Buyers are also offered facility to dispatch two drivers on a special training course.<ref>{{cite web|author= Chris Shunk RSS feed |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2007/03/05/a-685k-audi-a8-that-will-blow-its-own-doors-off/ |title=A $685k Audi A8 that will blow its own doors off |publisher=Autoblog.com |date=2007-03-05 |accessdate=2012-04-08 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== {{anchor|D3S8}} S8 5.2 FSI quattro ===\nThe S8 high-performance sports variant, now called the \"Audi S8 5.2 FSI quattro\", was announced in the last quarter of 2005 and full production started in June 2006 and ended in September 2009.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url= http://www.carsuk.net/audi-a8-w12-and-audi-s8-cancelled-for-2010/ |title=Audi A8 W12 and Audi S8 cancelled for 2010 &#124; Cars UK &#124; UK Car News |work= Cars UK |date= 2009-04-25 |accessdate= 2010-10-03| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100919144037/http://www.carsuk.net/audi-a8-w12-and-audi-s8-cancelled-for-2010/ |archivedate= 19 September 2010 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe S8 includes subtle detailing to distinguish it from its related A8. The [[trapezoid]]al \"single-frame\" grille bears the characteristic Audi \"S model\" vertical strut detail which are highlighted in a chrome finish. \"S8\" badging is displayed front and rear, whilst \"V10\" badges are displayed on each front wing above the side-repeater indicators. The rear boot-lid incorporates a subtle rear spoiler, and the rear is finished with four chromed oval exhaust tailpipes. Adaptive [[xenon arc lamp|Xenon]]-plus [[high-intensity discharge lamp|high-intensity discharge]] (HID) headlamps include static turning lights, along with \"swiveling\" dynamic cornering lights. [[Daytime running lamp]]s are five [[light-emitting diode]]s (LEDs) incorporated into a [[:wikt:cloverleaf|cloverleaf]] designed reflector, incorporated into the main headlamp housing.\n\n{{multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width = 200\n| image1 = 2007-Audi-S8.jpg\n| image2 = Audi S8 V10 black with blue fence.jpg\n| caption2 = Pre-facelift Audi S8\n}}\n\nThe D3 series S8 features a 5.2-litre all-[[aluminium alloy]] four-valves per cylinder [[V10 engine|V10]] petrol engine. [[list of Volkswagen Group petrol engines#BSM|This engine]] is a derivative of the [[Lamborghini Gallardo]]'s original 5.0-litre [[Lamborghini V10]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reviews.cnet.com/sedan/2009-audi-s8/4505-10865_7-33512962.html |title=Review on CNet |publisher=[[CNet]] |date=2009-02-06 |accessdate=2010-10-20 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> which was also developed under the Volkswagen Group ownership. On this Audi-only variant, compared to the Lamborghini engine, it features a longer [[stroke (engine)|stroke]] and wider [[bore (engine)|bore]]\u2014which increases the [[engine displacement|displacement]] of the engine, and produces more torque at lower revs, making it more suitable for the larger and heavier full-sized luxury Audi application. It produces {{convert|331|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|540|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque. By having its bore whittled out an additional {{convert|2|mm|in|1}}, displacement in the S8 application increases from 5.0- to 5.2-litres. The engine also features Audi's direct-injection system, called [[gasoline direct injection|Fuel Stratified Injection]] (FSI).<ref name=\"caranddriver1\"/>\n\n{{multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width = 200\n| image1 = Audi S8 -- 09-24-2011.jpg\n| image2 = Audi S8 rear 20080303.jpg\n| caption2 = Facelift Audi S8\n| image3 = S8 D3 cockpit 2009.jpg\n| caption3 = Facelift interior\n}}\n\nA sports-optimised [[ZF 6HP26 transmission|ZF ''6HP26-A61'']] six-speed [[tiptronic]] automatic transmission with \"Dynamic Shift Programme\" (DSP) and \"sport\" mode, with steering wheel mounted paddle-shifters, is the only offering. Output is transmitted via Audi's [[quattro (four wheel drive system)|quattro]] generation IV all-wheel drive system, initially using the [[Torsen]] T-1 50:50 dynamic centre [[differential (mechanical device)|differential]], and from 2007 for the 2008 [[model year]], utilising the Torsen T-3 asymmetric dynamic centre differential, with a \"default\" torque distribution of 40 percent to the front axle and 60 percent to the rear. If the road conditions change, the purely mechanical differential responds without any delay; it can divert up to 85 percent of power to the rear wheels, and as much as 65 percent to the front wheels.\n\nThe S8's top speed is electronically limited to {{convert|250|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}. Audi's factory performance claims indicate a {{convert|0|to|100|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} time of 5.1&nbsp;seconds whilst consuming 98&nbsp;[[Research Octane Number|RON]] unleaded petrol. The S8 has similar performance to Audi's own top-of-the-line A8 L [[W12 engine|W12]], though the W12 is more expensive, has more torque, and built on a longer wheelbase.<ref name=\"caranddriver1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/car/06q1/2007_audi_s8-first_drive_review |title=2007 Audi S8 \u2013 First Drive Review \u2013 Auto Reviews |publisher=Car and Driver |date= |accessdate=2011-04-02 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Compared to the A8 L W12, the S8 has sportier mechanical features such as a firmer suspension, larger wheels, and ceramic brakes. The shorter wheelbase and 10-cylinder engine save weight for better handling, but at 5.4 seconds from 0\u201360&nbsp;mph the S8 trails the W12.<ref name=\"canadiandriver1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.canadiandriver.com/2009/07/09/inside-story-2009-audi-s8.htm|title=Inside Story: 2009 Audi S8|first=Michael|last=Clark|date=July 9, 2009|work=Canadian Driver|accessdate=November 12, 2009 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090813044455/http://www.canadiandriver.com/2009/07/09/inside-story-2009-audi-s8.htm |archivedate= August 13, 2009|url-status=dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.automobilemag.com/roadtests/sedans/0703_sports_sedans_supreme_maserati_quattroporte_audi_s8_mercedes_benz_s63/index.html |title=Sports Sedans Supreme: 2007 Maserati Quattroporte Executive GT vs 2007 Audi S8 vs 2007 Mercedes-Benz S63 \u2013 Latest News, Features, and Road Tests \u2013 Automobile Magazine |publisher=Automobilemag.com |date=2010-12-13 |accessdate=2011-04-02 |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jbcarpages.com/audi/a8/2009/index3.php |title=2009 Audi A8 4.2 V8, A8L, W12, S8 V10 \u2013 Used Car Review / Specs / Handling / Performance Parts |publisher=Jbcarpages.com |date=2007-03-03 |accessdate=2011-04-02 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe S8, like its related A8, utilises a multi-link suspension layout front and rear, with pressurised air springs. However, for the S8, the effective spring and damper rates are noticeably firmer, along with re-engineered suspension mounts.\n\nThe brake system consists of radially ventilated [[disc brake|discs]] all round. The discs are clamped with gloss-black painted dual-piston calipers up front, and a single-piston sliding caliper at the rear, coupled to an electro-mechanical parking brake. A [[Robert Bosch GmbH|Bosch]] ESP&nbsp;5.7 (later upgraded to ESP&nbsp;8.0) [[electronic stability control]], with ABS, brake assist, EBD complete the brake system. Optional \"Audi ceramic\" [[reinforced carbon-carbon#Similar products|carbon fibre-reinforced silicon carbide]] (C/SiC) composite front and rear brakes are available, which use radially vented, and floating [[SGL Carbon]] discs, with anthracite grey painted twelve-piston fixed [[Brembo]] monobloc alloy calipers. Standard [[alloy wheel]]s consist of 20-inch \"S design\" alloy wheels.\n\n=== A8L Centennial Limited Edition (2009\u2013) ===\nThe A8L Centennial Limited Edition (\u5967\u8feaA8L\u767e\u5e74\u9650\u91cf\u7248) is a limited (800 units total) version of the A8L 3.0 FSI with multitronic and the A8L 6.0 W12 quattro for the Chinese market, commemorating Audi's 100th anniversary. It includes a horizontal chrome-plated front grille (from the A8L 6.0 W12 quattro), \"V6\" metal logo at the upper left of the air-inlet grille (A8L 3.0 FSI), LED daytime running lights, heated leather steering wheel, 19-inch 12-spoke polished aluminium alloy wheels, heated steering wheel in grey leather with beige stitching, [[Bang & Olufsen]] advanced audio system, Alcantara equipment bag, Assam ash red veneer, floor mat with aluminium trim and a metal 'Audi exclusive' commemorative logo at inn door trims.\n\nThe vehicles went on sale on the 18 October 2009 as 2010 model year vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/bizchina/09gzautoexpo/2009-10/26/content_8990513.htm|title=Audi A8L Centennial Limited Edition|publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://big5.xinhuanet.com/gate/big5/yn.xinhuanet.com/auto/2009-10/19/content_17979958.htm|title=\u5967\u8feaA8L\u767e\u5e74\u9650\u91cf\u7248\u4e0a\u5e02105.8-254\u842c|publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autonet.com.tw/cgi-bin/view.cgi?/news/2009/10/a9100546.ti+a2+a3+a4+a5+b1+/news/2009/10/a9100546+/car/A20060003+b3+d6+c1+c2+c3+e1+e2+e3+e5+f1|title=AutoNet \u6c7d\u8eca\u65e5\u5831\uff1aAUDI A8L\u767e\u5e74\u7d00\u5ff5\u7248\u4e2d\u570b\u9650\u91cf\u767c\u552e\uff01|publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Engine variants ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:98%;\"\n!colspan=2|Engine<ref>{{cite book|title=Automobile Revue 2007|last= |first= |year=2007|publisher=Espace Media Groupe|location=Bern|isbn=978-3-905386-07-3|pages=113\u2013114}}</ref>\n!rowspan=2|Power, Torque at rpm\n!rowspan=2|0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h<br><small>(0\u201362&nbsp;mph)</small>\n!rowspan=2|Top speed\n|-\n!displacement\n!type\n|-\n|2.8 (2773&nbsp;cc) || [[V6 engine|V6]] [[gasoline direct injection|FSI]] || {{convert|210|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on|lk=on}}; {{convert|280|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3,000 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8.0&nbsp;[[second|sec]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|237|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.0 (2976&nbsp;cc) || V6 || {{convert|220|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|300|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3,200 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7.9&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|241|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.2 (3123&nbsp;cc) || V6 FSI || {{convert|256|PS|kW bhp|0|abbr=on}}; {{convert|330|Nm|0|abbr=on}} at 3,250 || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7.7&nbsp;sec || style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{convert|250|km/h|1|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|3.7 (3697&nbsp;cc) || [[V8 engine|V8]] || 